<HEAD>
<TITLE>CEI EBB: Clean Air Act Reform</TITLE>
</HEAD>

<BODY BGCOLOR="#EEEEEE" TEXT="000000" LINK="009900" VLINK="000099">

<TABLE BORDER=0 WIDTH=100%><TR><TD ALIGN=LEFT><A HREF="/ebb/"><IMG SRC="/images/ceiebb.gif" ALT="CEI Environmental Briefing Book" ALIGN=LEFT BORDER=0></A></TD></TR></TABLE>
<P>
<BR CLEAR>
<table border=0 cellpadding=15><tr><td>

<CENTER>
<H2>Clean Air Act Reform</H2>
</CENTER>

<P><BR>  State and local governments should be afforded more flexibility in the
  determination of air pollution control methods and goals.  At present, areas not meeting
  federal clean air standards are forced to implement costly and inefficient air pollution
  control strategies and are discouraged from using more cost-effective and equitable
  approaches.
  
     <P>The 1990 Clean Air Act is the most expensive single piece of environmental
  legislation ever enacted.  It amended the clean air laws passed in the 1970s.  In addition to
  industrial emissions, the 1990 law regulates automobile design, gasoline content, energy
  production and emissions from dry cleaners, bakeries and other small businesses.  Air
  quality is steadily improving in most major cities, yet the federal government insists upon
  imposing layer-upon-layer of additional regulatory controls.
  
  <P>   A significant portion of federal clean air law is aimed at controlling emissions
  associated with motor vehicles.  It imposes broad "drift-net" strategies that impact all
  vehicles and car owners irrespective of their relative contributions to pollution levels.  It is
  well-established that only a small fraction of motor vehicles generate the lion's share of
  emissions.  Ten percent of the vehicles on the road are responsible for approximately half
  of automobile-related emissions.  This means that for every ten vehicles on the road, the
  dirtiest car emits as much as the remaining nine.  By failing to focus emission-reduction
  efforts on the dirtiest of vehicles, federal air pollution control strategies are both inefficient
  and inequitable.
  
  <P>   Under federal law, those areas that do not meet federal air quality standards are
  required to implement particular pollution control measures, even if better options are
  available.  Some of these include:
  <UL>
<LI>    The imposition of expensive, centralized vehicle inspection and maintenance programs
       that impose significant costs and inconvenience upon car owners without providing
       corresponding benefits as opposed to less-expensive, decentralized testing methods.
     <LI>    Requirements that state and local agencies implement case-specific, interim emission
       limits for industrial facilities, even though the EPA is in the process of developing its
       own national standards.
     <LI>   Potential requirements that certain states impose low-emission vehicle standards on all
       new cars sold within the state, and include sales mandates for electric vehicles.
       </UL>
<P>  Additional measures impose burdensome regulatory programs on businesses and local
  government agencies.  For instance, Title V, which requires over 30,000 industrial jobsites
  to obtain a new class of operating permit.  This will require tremendous amounts of
  paperwork and significant financial cost at no environmental gain.
  
  <P>      There are few parts of the country that would voluntarily adopt these methods to
  achieve the federal government's stringent air quality standards.  Air pollution strategies that
  are effective in one area, may be less so somewhere else.  Moreover, most air pollution
  concerns are local or regional in nature.  States need to be given greater flexibility to meet
  federal clean air standards, if not the authority to evaluate proper regional standards for
  themselves.
  <P><BR>
  
  <I>Q: Are existing federal clean air standards stringent enough to protect human health?
  </I>
<P>  A: Yes, and for some pollutants they may even be too stringent.  Non-attainment status for
  ozone is triggered by surpassing the federal standard for an hour more than three times
  over a three year period.  Thus, four bad hours on four bad days over three years are
  sufficient to classify a city as a nonattainment area by federal standards.  Residents in some
  areas may prefer such stringent standards, but it would be better if communities had that
  choice, rather than having these standards imposed upon them by the federal government.
  
  
<P>  <I>Q: Aren't most of the costs of the Clean Air Act paid for by big business, and not the
  public?</I>
  
  <P>A: The cost and inconvenience of the Clean Air Act is increasingly being shouldered by
  consumers.  Higher new car prices, costlier maintenance, mandatory inspections and
  repairs, and higher gas prices directly affect all drivers.  The costs of hundreds of everyday
  goods and services, from a loaf of bread to one's dry cleaning, have increased because of
  the Act.
  
  <P><I>Q: Why shouldn't automakers be forced to manufacture cleaner cars and the oil
  companies forced to make cleaner fuels?</I>
  
  <P>A: New cars produced today are already over 90 percent cleaner than those produced prior
  to 1970.  There simply is not much to be gained from tightening vehicle emission standards
  yet again.  If further emission reductions are necessary, it is better to focus on the greatest
  source of emissions -- older and poorly maintained vehicles.  Targeting the most polluting
  vehicles for emission reductions will be fairer and more effective than imposing another
  round of fuel or vehicle standards.
  
  <P><I>Q: Are electric cars a viable way to reduce auto-related air pollution?</I>
  
  <P>A: While electric cars sound wonderful on paper, they are less so in practice.  Electric cars
  have many drawbacks that make them insufficient for the needs of most car owners,
  including high costs, limited range, recharge requirements and a lack of amenities (air
  conditioning, heater, etc.).  Moreover, electric cars are not without their environmental
  impacts.  The electricity to charge the batteries must come from some source, often
  resulting in air emissions, and due to their chemical composition replacing batteries every
  few years raises disposal questions.
  
  <P><I>Q: Is the air getting cleaner?
 </I> 
<P>  A: Yes. The quality of the air we breathe has improved markedly over the last three
  decades.  The number of localities exceeding federal standards for regulated pollutants has
  substantially declined since 1970.  Even without the enactment of the 1990 Clean Air Act
  Amendments, there is reason to believe that these trends would continue, just as some air
  quality trends were improving before the imposition of federal clean air laws.
  
  
</td></tr></table>
<P><BR>
<CENTER>
