<DOCNO>WT14-B01-10</DOCNO>
<DOCOLDNO>IA002-000015-B002-47</DOCOLDNO>
<DOCHDR>
http://www.cei.org:80/ebb/ecomgmt.html 207.33.42.44 19970101095735 text/html 6373
HTTP/1.0 200 OK
Date: Wed, 01 Jan 1997 09:57:47 GMT
Server: Apache/1.1.1
Content-type: text/html
Content-length: 6202
Last-modified: Tue, 27 Aug 1996 23:42:20 GMT
</DOCHDR>
<HTML>
<HEAD>
<TITLE>CEI EBB: Ecosystem Management</TITLE>
</HEAD>

<BODY BGCOLOR="#EEEEEE" TEXT="000000" LINK="009900" VLINK="000099">

<TABLE BORDER=0 WIDTH=100%><TR><TD ALIGN=LEFT><A HREF="/ebb/"><IMG SRC="/images/ceiebb.gif" ALT="CEI Environmental Briefing Book" ALIGN=LEFT BORDER=0></A></TD></TR></TABLE>
<P>
<BR CLEAR>
<table border=0 cellpadding=15><tr><td>

<CENTER>
<H2>Ecosystem Management</H2>
</CENTER>

<P><BR>Ecosystem management is the newest regulatory strategy advocated by
environmentalists to limit urban growth and preserve undeveloped land.  It
provides the most expansive scheme for national land-use planning yet devised.
Those who want to limit federal control over and regulation of private land
should adamantly oppose the implementation of ecosystem management.<p>
	<a href="/ebb/esa.html">The Endangered Species Act (ESA)</A> currently allows federal regulation only when
a species is listed as threatened or endangered.  Under the ESA, land-use
regulations are authorized only to protect members of listed species from
&#147;harm.&#148;  Harm, according to the Supreme Court, must result in
&#147;actual death or injury&#148; to the animal in question.  Advocates of
ecosystem management want to amend the ESA to enact a different approach. <p>
	&#147;Instead of focusing on individual species, we would do it on the basis
of a whole ecosystem,&#148; explains Interior Secretary Bruce Babbitt.  Yet
ecosystems, according to Babbitt, are &#147;in the eye of the beholder.&#148;
This means that ecosystem management would greatly expand federal land-use
regulation at the discretion of federal agencies.  The Yellowstone
&#147;ecosystem,&#148; for example, expanded from two million acres in 1980 to
18 million acres by 1991.<p>
	Consider the application of ecosystem management to the protection of the
coastal California gnatcatcher, a small songbird in southern California.  There
are approximately 250 pairs of gnatcatchers in Riverside County.  Because each
pair requires less than 20 acres of habitat, the most expansive regulations
authorized by the ESA would preserve approximately 5,000 acres of land.  Under
the Interior Department&#146;s ecosystem management plan, however, nearly
150,000 acres of land would be locked up.  Ecosystem management will lock up
almost 30 times more land.<p>
	The loss of the use of private property without compensation is the primary
problem with the current species-by-species approach; but the ecosystem
approach promises that property owners will lose even more of their land.  The
ESA requires that members of a listed species be present on the land in
question.  Ecosystem management only requires that the land exist, and that
federal agencies wish to &#147;protect&#148; it.<p>
	Ecosystem management will not solve the many conflicts over species
protection.  Rather it will exacerbate them.  Ecosystem management would mark
the beginning of the end for private property rights in America.  Ecosystems
are comprised of the constituent elements of land.  Every landowner owns a
part, if not the entirety, of some &#147;ecosystem.&#148;  If ecosystems become
&#147;public,&#148; as species have, then private property will suddenly become
&#147;public,&#148; too.  This is the goal of ecosystem management, and this is
the reason to oppose it.<p>
<p>
<i>Q:  Isn&#146;t the protection of ecosystems the purpose of the Endangered
Species Act?</i><p>
<p>
A:  No.  The ESA&#146;s stated goal is to &#147;provide a means whereby the
ecosystems upon which endangered species and threatened species depend may be
conserved.&#148;  To &#147;conserve,&#148; according to the ESA, &#147;means to
bring any endangered species or threatened species to the point at which the
measures provided pursuant to this Act are no longer necessary.&#148;  In other
words, to &#147;conserve&#148; an ecosystem is to &#147;recover&#148; a
species.<p>
	Only species can be listed under the ESA, and only species can trigger the
Act&#146;s regulations; ecosystems cannot.  This is why the Fish &amp; Wildlife
Service delists species, not ecosystems.  Implementing ecosystem management on
private land legally requires amending the ESA.<p>
<p>
<i>Q:  How can the ESA&#146;s specific reference to ecosystems be
explained?</i><p>
<p>
A:  &#147;Species&#148; are mentioned more than 350 times in the ESA;
&#147;ecosystems&#148; are mentioned only twice.  In 1973, when the ESA was
enacted, few people thought the Act authorized regulation of private land use
to protect species, let alone to protect &#147;ecosystems.&#148;  The only
plausible rationale for even mentioning ecosystems in the ESA was to justify
the protection of species by referencing their importance, as integral parts,
to a larger, more important whole.  Losing one species was presumed to increase
the risk of losing other species, as &#147;everything is connected to
everything else.&#148;<p>
<p>
<i>Q:  Even if current law does not authorize it, would it not be good to have
a law that protects rare or unique ecosystems?</i><p>
<p>
A:  No. Ecosystems are inherently subjective and infinitely elastic.  They are
mental constructs, designed for categorical convenience, not objective
realities in nature.  As such, there are no objective criteria to determine
where one ecosystem ends and another begins.  Like a fingerprint, every spot on
the surface of the earth is unique.  Thus, as a matter of law, regulating rare
or unique ecosystems is an open invitation to regulating anything or
everything.
</td></tr></table>
<P><BR>
<CENTER>
<P>
