<HEAD>
<TITLE>CEI EBB: Endangered Species Act</TITLE>
</HEAD>

<BODY BGCOLOR="#EEEEEE" TEXT="000000" LINK="009900" VLINK="000099">

<TABLE BORDER=0 WIDTH=100%><TR><TD ALIGN=LEFT><A HREF="/ebb/"><IMG SRC="/images/ceiebb.gif" ALT="CEI Environmental Briefing Book" ALIGN=LEFT BORDER=0></A></TD></TR></TABLE>
<P>
<BR CLEAR>
<table border=0 cellpadding=15><tr><td>

<CENTER>
<H2>Endangered Species Act</H2>
</CENTER>

<P><BR>The Endangered Species Act (ESA) is one of the most controversial of all
environmental laws.  Not only has the ESA failed to recover a single species
from the brink of extinction, it has pushed countless landowners to the point
of financial ruin.  By penalizing property owners for having threatened or
endangered species on their land, the ESA is turning landowners into enemies of
wildlife and wildlife assets into economic liabilities.  The ESA is in need of
fundamental reform.<p>
	Enacted in 1973, the ESA&#146;s stated objective is to &#147;conserve&#148;
listed species of animals and plants.  This means &#147;to bring any endangered
species or threatened species to the point at which [the Act&#146;s
protections] are no longer necessary.&#148;  Thus the goal of the ESA is
&#147;recover&#148; listed species.  Yet, after more than twenty years, the Act
has failed to recover a single one.<p>
	Since 1973, only 27 species have been removed from the endangered species
list.  Seven of those were &#147;delisted&#148; because they went extinct.
Nine of them (according to the Fish &amp; Wildlife Service) were &#147;data
errors,&#148; which means they never should have been listed in the first
place.  The FWS claims to have &#147;recovered&#148; the remaining eleven
species, but not one of them was saved by the ESA.  Eight of these purportedly
&#147;recovered&#148; species did not even merit listing in the first place,
for they were not in danger of extinction.  The three remaining species (the
Eastern population of the brown pelican, the arctic peregrine falcon and the
California gray whale) were indeed in trouble, but were helped by measures
other than the ESA.<p>
	The ESA has been a complete and utter failure.  Perhaps the single most
important reason for the Act&#146;s abysmal record is that it has imposed
draconian regulations on private landowners.  The ESA has stopped people from
building homes, constructing roads, plowing fields, felling trees, filling
ditches and even clearing firebreaks to protect their homes and family from
fire hazards.  The risk of being regulated out of business has driven some
landowners to &#147;shoot, shovel and shut up,&#148; while many others simply
destroy the animal&#146;s habitat so as to avoid the ESA&#146;s often onerous
land-use regulations.<p>
	If you want more of something you reward those who provide it, not punish
them.  But the ESA is all stick and no carrot.  A good law would make
landowners want to attract rare wildlife to their land &#151; not rid their
land of rare wildlife.  A good law would recover endangered species, not ruin
people.  But it is precisely because the ESA is harming people that it is also
harming wildlife.  The only way to turn this around is by removing the
law&#146;s authority to prevent landowners from using their own land.  In the
104th Congress, however, only one bill (HR 2364) embodied a non-regulatory
approach to endangered species conservation. <p>
	At the very least, landowners should be compensated for their losses from
land-use regulations.  If species protection benefits all of us, then the costs
of protecting species should be borne by all of us.  Under the ESA, those costs
are borne by the unlucky landowners who happen to own the wrong piece of land.
Reform is imperative, for both landowners and wildlife.<p>
<i>Q:  A recent Times-Mirror poll found that most Americans support the ESA.
Why should it be reformed?</i><p>
<p>
A:  Americans care about wildlife, and so they support government efforts to
protect  endangered species.  However, Americans also believe in property
rights.  That same <i>Times Mirror</i> poll found that 66 percent of Americans
believe that landowners should be compensated when their land is devalued by
the ESA.  For federal wildlife protection to truly reflect the will of the
American people, it must compensate landowners for their losses.  It is a
simple matter of fairness that most Americans understand and support.<p>
<i></i><p>
<i>Q:  According to the Fish &amp; Wildlife Service, the ESA has
&#147;recovered&#148; 11 species.  Isn&#146;t this true?</i><p>
<p>
A:  No.  The government has effectively admitted that four of them (the Palau
dove, Palau owl, Palau fantail flycatcher and the Rydberg milk-vetch) were data
errors, and should never have been listed in the first place.  The National
Wildlife Federation has documented that a fifth species, the American
alligator, did not warrant listing either.  Equally unwarranted was the listing
of three species of Australian kangaroos.  <p>
	Only 3 of the 11 &#147;recovered&#148; species were helped by the federal
government.  The brown pelican and arctic peregrine falcon were by most
accounts saved by the 1972 ban on DDT and the remoteness of the Falcon&#146;s
habitat &#151; not the passage of the ESA in 1973.  Last, but not least, the
California gray whale was pushed to the brink of extinction by commercial
whaling in open access waters.  But hunting these whales was banned by
international treaties in 1937 and 1946.  The gray whale was well on its way to
recovery long before the ESA was enacted.  <p>
<p>
<i>Q:  Is not habitat protection vital to the conservation of most endangered
species?</i><p>
<p>
A:  Yes.  But punishing landowners through confiscatory regulations for having
such habitat is no way to save it.  In fact, the ESA&#146;s punitive approach
is more likely to ensure the destruction of habitat than its preservation.
Look at it this way: Habitat is also key to solving the homeless problem, yet
the government does not force urbanites to provide shelter for the homeless in
their backyards.  If it did, many urbanites would surely build over their
backyards and do away with such spaces altogether.  Many landowners would
proudly conserve habitat for endangered species on their own land were they not
penalized by government regulation.<p>
<i></i><p>
<i>Q:  Since less than one percent of all projects reviewed under the ESA have
been halted, isn&#146;t the Act much more flexible than its critics
claim?</i><p>
<p>
A:  The ESA&#146;s impact on private projects on private land (through Section
9) has never been reviewed; that statistic pertains only to federal projects
that received federal funding or authorization (through Section 7).  Moreover,
project approval does not demonstrate flexibility particularly when onerous
conditions are attached.  Just ask David Trotter of Austin, Texas, whose 1,100
acre development project conflicted with golden-cheeked warbler habitat.  The
Interior Department said the residential development could proceed because
there were &#147;reasonable and prudent alternatives.&#148;  The alternative
proposed by the FWS was for Trotter to give the government 765 acres, and buy
the government an additional 873 acres for a warbler preserve elsewhere &#151;
<i>in exchange for allowing the private landowners to develop less than 25%
of their own property</i>.  The FWS later modified its position only after
extensive legal wrangling.  Some flexibility.
</td></tr></table>
<P><BR>
<CENTER>
<P>
