<DOC>
<DOCNO>WT14-B01-19</DOCNO>
<DOCOLDNO>IA002-000015-B002-197</DOCOLDNO>
<DOCHDR>
http://www.cei.org:80/ebb/biotech2.html 207.33.42.44 19970101100005 text/html 7825
HTTP/1.0 200 OK
Date: Wed, 01 Jan 1997 10:00:16 GMT
Server: Apache/1.1.1
Content-type: text/html
Content-length: 7654
Last-modified: Tue, 27 Aug 1996 23:41:43 GMT
</DOCHDR>
<HTML>
<HEAD>
<TITLE>CEI EBB: Biotechnology</TITLE>
</HEAD>

<BODY BGCOLOR="#EEEEEE" TEXT="000000" LINK="009900" VLINK="000099">

<TABLE BORDER=0 WIDTH=100%><TR><TD ALIGN=LEFT><A HREF="/ebb/"><IMG SRC="/images/ceiebb.gif" ALT="CEI Environmental Briefing Book" ALIGN=LEFT BORDER=0></A></TD></TR></TABLE>
<P>
<BR CLEAR>
<table border=0 cellpadding=15><tr><td>

<CENTER>
<H2>Biotechnology</H2>
</CENTER>

<P><BR>

The field of biotechnology promises tremendous advances in medicine and agriculture.  Biotechnology products should be regulated no differently than other products.  Policymakers should focus on the safety of particular products and innovations, rather than upon their origin or means of production. <p>
	
Biotechnology&#146;s advance from the pharmacy to the supermarket shelf has
spurred a host of regulatory proposals, fueled in large part by scare stories about mutant cows and killer tomatoes.  Where specific biotechnology products are shown to pose risks that are higher than those of their &#147;natural&#148; counterparts, regulations may well be appropriate.  However, merely because a product has been produced through biotechnological means does not justify its being singled out for special regulation.  <p>
	
Nonetheless, several agencies, such as the Environmental Protection Agency and
the Food and Drug Administration, in the past have imposed precisely such
regulations on products ranging from bio-engineered bacteria for use in
agriculture to biotech foods and pharmaceuticals.  Some of these agencies have
revised recently revised their policies.  For example, in the wake of the 1994
Congressional elections, FDA withdrew its proposal to subject biotech foods to
a host of extensive regulations; the agency now takes the far more reasonable
course of focusing on whether a genetic change may have created a new risk or
produced a substance significantly different than that commonly found in food.
Nonethless, in many cases the biotech origins of a product will still trigger
excessive regulatory scrutiny.<p>
	
Product labelling is another area of political and regulatory contention.  The
Food and Drug Administration&#146;s 1993 approval of rBST to enhance milk
production drew fire from some consumer groups, who argue for mandatory
labelling of rBST-derived products.  Such labelling requirements, they claim,
are necessary for consumers to be fully informed.  But the real effect would be
to restrict consumer choice under the guise of protecting the public&#146;s
&#147;right to know.&#148;<p>
	
If consumers really are interested in knowing whether their foods have been
biotechnologically produced, then they will be able to get that information
without labelling mandates.  Producers and sellers of &#147;non-biotech&#148;
foods can freely advertise that fact, just as many companies and stores today
advertise that their products are &#147;organic&#148; or
&#147;preservative-free.&#148;  Mandatory labelling laws are not needed to
produce such information.<p>
	
Labelling mandates, on the other hand, would not merely produce unneeded
information; <i>they would ultimately restrict consumer choice</i>.  Such
mandates would almost certainly target man-made substances over natural
substances and new technologies over older ones.  They would make it difficult
if not impossible to sell these products, because consumers would naturally
believe that they were being warned about some significant risk that they would
be better off avoiding.  The end result would be closed markets and undeveloped
products.  This, for example, was the chief effect of laws earlier in this
century that imposed labelling and packaging restrictions on margarine and
other dairy substitutes.  Their alleged purpose was to prevent consumer
deception, but their <i>anti</i>-consumer nature is well recognized today.<p>
	The field of biotechnology has an incredible potential to produce a wide-range
of medical and consumers products.  Biotechnology has already produced such
wondrous developments as clotting-factor VIII, an important treatment for
hemophilia, and cloned insulin, upon which many diabetics depend.  This
potential should not be compromised by excessive regulation.<p>

<i>Q:  Doesn&#146;t biotechnology pose new risks greater than those we&#146;ve
faced before?</i><p>

A:  No.  Nearly all our agricultural products have been developed by breeding,
which is itself a process of genetic alteration.  For example, tomatoes were
once small and bitter.  But careful selective breeding of tomatoes,
occasionally with other plant species, enabled the development of sweeter
modern varieties.  Biotechnology is simply a more advanced technique of this
same process that entails no special risks.  Many biotech techniques involve no
more than a speeding up of the breeding process.  The real risk is that of
across-the-board biotechnology regulation, and the delay that this can cause in
the availability of new products.<p>


<i>Q:  Don&#146;t consumers have a right to know what they are buying? </i><p>

A:  The basic consumer right is to able to buy what one wants, and companies
should not be allowed to deceive their customers.  If consumers demand
particular information about a series of products, companies should be free to
provide that information and to advertise it.  However, the government should
refrain from selecting which types of information should be placed on packaging
merely to satisfy certain interest groups.  When scientifically irrelevant
factors become the subject of arbitrary labelling rules, the end result will be
fewer products for people to choose from.<p>


<i>Q:  Why is biotechnology necessary?  Why can&#146;t we leave things the way
they are?</i><p>


A:  To stand still in a world where nature is steadily changing is to fall
behind.  Rapid technological and institutional change has made the world a
safer, healthier place; similarly rapid improvements will be necessary to
continue this trend.<p>
	
Biotechnology, thus, is a vital field of research.  Few people are aware of
how important biotechnology is to improving the lives of millions of people.
In the field of medicine, for example, biotechnological processes have been
used to develop vaccines, cloned insulin for diabetics, heart attack drugs like
TPA (Tissue Plasminogen Activator), and the diagnostic techniques used to keep
our nation&#146;s blood supply free of hepatitis B and HIV.  Biotechnology also
shows promise in the field of environmental remediation.  Scientist hope that
biotechnology will develop safer and more effective means of addressing
pollution and cleaning up contaminated ground water. <p>
	
We also should not forget the economic importance of this growing industry.
The U.S. is the world leader in biotechnology with over 1,000 biotech companies
which employ over 50,000 people.  Biotechnology is expected to be an $80
billion industry within several years.  These benefits, too, should not be
overlooked.


</td></tr></table>
<P><BR>
<CENTER>
<P>
<A HREF="/ebb/cleanair.html"><IMG SRC="/images/forward.gif" ALT="Forward to the next page" BORDER=2></A>
<A HREF="/ebb/"><IMG SRC="/images/back.gif" ALT="Back to the beginning" BORDER=2></A>
<P>
