<HTML>
<HEAD>
<TITLE>CEI EBB: Electricity Competition</TITLE>
</HEAD>

<BODY BGCOLOR="#EEEEEE" TEXT="000000" LINK="009900" VLINK="000099">

<TABLE BORDER=0 WIDTH=100%><TR><TD ALIGN=LEFT><A HREF="/ebb/"><IMG SRC="/images/ceiebb.gif" ALT="CEI Environmental Briefing Book" ALIGN=LEFT BORDER=0></A></TD></TR></TABLE>
<P>
<BR CLEAR>
<table border=0 cellpadding=15><tr><td>

<CENTER>
<H2>Electricity Competition</H2>
</CENTER>

<P><BR>The nation&#146;s electricity system is currently dominated by local,
regulated monopolies.  This should change.  An &#147;electricity
superhighway&#148; now links utility customers with hundreds of power
producers.  Consumers should have direct access to this network.  Direct access
would enable consumers to pick electric utilities the way they can now pick
long distance telephone service.   Moreover, consumers would no longer be
forced to subsidize wasteful utility &#147;conservation&#148; programs that
benefit some utility consumers at the expense of others.  States have the
authority to allow for direct consumer access within their borders and many are
moving aggressively in that direction.  National competition in electricity
markets at the wholesale level is now being!  implemented by the Federal Energy
Regulatory Commission (FERC).<p>
	Utilities already have access to the &#147;electricity superhighway.&#148;
Because most utilities have been granted a local monopoly by government, they
can charge what are often exorbitant rates and deny their patrons access to the
wholesale and retail electricity markets. Giving consumers access to the grid
or allowing competition in transmission would reduce rates dramatically, saving
homeowners and businesses hundreds of billions of dollars and eliminating the
need for a cumbersome regulatory bureaucracy to oversee the industry.<p>
	The wholesale electricity market, which has existed in limited form since the
1920s, is made possible by a national network of transmission lines connecting
utilities, wholesale electricity producers, and utility customers to one
another. Power producers use the system to trade electricity with one another
in a diverse and vibrant wholesale market, free of the cost-of-service
regulation imposed on retail consumers. Allowing utility customers to use the
same system would liberate them from regulation and give them the same market
options their utilities enjoy.<p>
	Utilities oppose retail competition for obvious reasons: Substantial
investments in power plants and equipment will be rendered obsolete by
competition from leaner, more efficient generators.  As a &#147;price&#148; for
competition, utilities are demanding reimbursement for these &#147;stranded
costs.&#148;  Law makers should oppose such transfers of wealth from captive
customers to monopoly utilities and their shareholders.  Many <i>efficient</i>
utilities &#151; as opposed to poorly managed ones &#151; oppose the awarding
of stranded cost surcharges on the competitive grid.  No customer owes this
kind of obligation to any seller, in any event.<p>
	Unfortunately, even some environmental groups have joined utilities in
opposing reform of the electricity system.  Environmental activists are seeking
to preserve Demand-Side Management (DSM) programs administered by the
utilities. Through DSM programs, utilities increase their rates in order to pay
for energy conservation programs that only benefit a select portion of
ratepayers.  State regulators give privately-owned utilities various incentives
to administer the programs. Ratepayers are often entirely unaware of the
existence of this scheme, which costs them billions annually. <p>
	A competitive electricity system would render inefficient energy conservation
programs obsolete.  Conservation investments that could not pay for themselves
through increased efficiency would be jettisoned as utilities were forced to
compete for customers by offering lower prices.  The result would be dramatic
savings for consumers and increased efficiency within the electricity
industry.<p>

<i>Q:  Why should we abandon a proven system of public oversight and regulation
of electric utility monopolies in favor of the uncertainties of a competitive
system?</i><p>

A:  Competition has repeatedly proven itself superior to government regulation.
Only in a free market will producers have incentives to satisfy the demands of
a varied clientele. The current system of command-and-control regulation of
utility monopolies disregards consumer choice, and virtually eliminates
incentives for electricity producers to innovate and cut costs. In a free
market, producers would be immediately accountable to power consumers, who
would have the option to switch providers if the current one proves
unsatisfactory.<p>

<i>Q:  How much would competition in electricity markets reduce prices for
consumers?</i><p>

A:  The U.S. spends about $200 billion annually on electricity.  The consumer
savings from electricity competition would vary from community to community.
In some parts of the country, electricity bills would decline by as much as 50
percent.<p>

<i>Q:  If direct access eliminates DSM programs, will it be bad for the
environment? </i><p>

A:  Efficiency is a friend of the environment.  By encouraging greater
efficiency within the electricity industry, competition will also spur
utilities to develop new and innovative methods of electricity generation that
produce more energy by using fewer resources, thereby lessening much of the
environmental impact of regulated electricity generation.<p>
<p>
<p>
<i>Q: Aren&#146;t DSM programs simply an efficient alternative to building new
power plants?</i><p>
<p>
A: Proponents of DSM often argue that utilities should compare the cost of
constructing new power plants to the cost of avoiding the construction of a new
plant by reducing their customers&#146; electricity demand. If the latter is
less expensive, then clearly it is the optimal choice. Unfortunately, DSM
programs are no longer used as a less-expensive alternative to power plant
construction, which would lower electricity rates for all consumers. Instead,
DSM programs apply a &#147;surcharge&#148; to rates, raising them to pay for
energy-efficiency subsidies. DSM is not an efficient alternative to power plant
construction &#151; it is a system of taxation and redistribution.
</td></tr></table>
<P><BR>
<CENTER>
<P>
<A HREF="/ebb/esa.html"><IMG SRC="/images/forward.gif" ALT="Forward to the next page" BORDER=2></A>
<A HREF="/ebb/"><IMG SRC="/images/back.gif" ALT="Back to the beginning" BORDER=2></A>
