<HTML>
<HEAD>
<TITLE>CEI EBB: Energy Taxes</TITLE>
</HEAD>

<BODY BGCOLOR="#EEEEEE" TEXT="000000" LINK="009900" VLINK="000099">

<TABLE BORDER=0 WIDTH=100%><TR><TD ALIGN=LEFT><A HREF="/ebb/"><IMG SRC="/images/ceiebb.gif" ALT="CEI Environmental Briefing Book" ALIGN=LEFT BORDER=0></A></TD></TR></TABLE>
<P>
<BR CLEAR>
<table border=0 cellpadding=15><tr><td>

<CENTER>
<H2>Energy Taxes</H2>
</CENTER>

<P><BR>Congress should not impose an energy tax of any kind.  Neither a broad-based
energy tax, such as the &#147;Btu tax&#148; or carbon tax, nor an increased
gasoline tax should be used for deficit reduction or environmental protection.
<p>
	Energy taxes would weaken U.S. industry and destroy jobs.  America enjoys an
abundance of energy sources, and as a result the U.S. economy abounds with
energy-intensive industries, from petrochemicals to timber.  Taxing energy will
hurt these industries and compromise America&#146;s competitiveness.  In 1992,
Pittsburgh&#146;s CONSAD Research Corporation estimated that a proposed carbon
tax would destroy 600,000 jobs over an 8-year period.  Other studies have
confirmed that imposing a tax on energy would have dire economic
consequences.<p>
	Moreover, a tax on energy would increase consumer prices and have a general
inflationary impact.  Taxing energy would increase the costs of producing raw
materials and transporting goods, in addition to the costs of heating and
maintaining family homes.  This economic impact would be felt by every
American, particularly the least fortunate.  Energy taxes and other policies
that raise prices have the most pernicious effect on those with fixed incomes.
Also, fuel taxes tend to hit hardest motorists in low-density rural areas
&#151; areas least affected by pollution.<p>
	Some claim that higher energy taxes, by restricting consumption, will promote
efficiency and protect the environment.  These claims are false.  Raising the
price of energy would certainly result in reduced energy use.  However, energy
<i>conservation</i> &#151; using less energy &#151; is not necessarily the same
as energy <i>efficiency</i> &#151; using less energy to produce the same or
higher level of goods.  Energy is used, after all, for a purpose.  If that
purpose is valuable, then taxing energy will just hinder the production of
valuable goods and services.<p>
	Energy taxes may of course impel businesses to adopt new technologies and so
become more energy-efficient.  But <i>energy</i> efficiency is not necessarily
the same as <i>economic</i> efficiency.  The investments businesses make in
response to energy taxes represent resources that cannot be used to develop new
products, raise wages, create jobs, or make other, more urgently-needed
efficiency enhancements.  Attempts by government to force businesses to
&#147;save&#148; energy are inherently wasteful.<p>
	Energy taxes cannot be justified on environmental grounds either.  Energy
taxes are at best a crude and unreliable method of curbing pollution.  Energy
use is not a reliable indicator of pollution created.  For example, two
different automobiles will produce different levels of emissions from the same
amount of gasoline.  Taxing energy is not the same thing as taxing pollution.<p>
	A tax on energy is a tax on the lifeblood of an industrial economy.  Such a
tax is regressive in nature, and cannot be justified on either economic or
environmental grounds.<p>

<i>Q:  Isn&#146;t it true that Europeans pay more in gas taxes than
Americans?</i><p>

A:  Yes, but Europe also has a higher population density and few wide-open
expanses equivalent to those spanning the American West.  These factors reduce
per capita energy consumption, and the economic impact of higher energy prices.
Hauling goods from Frankfurt to Berlin is hardly the same as from St. Louis to
Seattle.  The U.S. transports over 3.7 trillion ton-kilometers of inland
freight annually.  This is more than ten times the amount shipped in Germany
and over five times that transported in the United Kingdom, Italy, France,
Spain, Belgium and Denmark combined.<p>
<p>
<i>Q:  The U.S. contains only 5 percent of the world&#146;s population, yet
accounts for approximately 25 percent of energy use.  Moreover, America uses 10
percent to 25 percent more energy per unit of output than many other industrial
nations.  Doesn&#146;t this mean the U.S. is energy inefficient?</i><p>
<i></i><p>
A:  Several factors make it reasonable for Americans to use more energy than
people in Western Europe and Japan.  America has more abundant energy
resources, so energy tends to be less expensive here.  America has a lower
population density, so we must consume more energy for transportation.
Americans have 50 percent to 80 percent more living space, per capita, than do
Europeans, and 250 percent more than do the Japanese.  Larger domiciles require
more energy to heat and cool.  More living space also means more and larger
household appliances such as refrigerators and washing machines.  Europeans and
Japanese use significantly more energy than do Africans and Latin Americans.
Does this make Europe and Japan energy inefficient?  To enjoy the benefits of
economic progr! ess and prosperity is not necessarily to &#147;waste&#148;
energy.<p>
<p>
<i>Q:  Won&#146;t energy taxes help prevent the depletion of fossil
fuels?</i><p>
<i></i><p>
A:  The world is in no danger of running out of fossil fuels.  Political
pundits and policy analysts have predicted impending energy shortages for
years, without ever having these projections materialize.  For example, in 1970
the International Energy Agency claimed that the world&#146;s proven oil
reserves of 645 billion barrels would be depleted in the mid-1980s, yet by 1990
world oil reserves had actually increased to 1 trillion barrels.  Proven oil
reserves are more a function of market prices and extraction technologies than
they are of actual underground supplies.  As knowledge increases, so do proven
reserves.  The most recent estimates place the world&#146;s oil supply at
several hundred years.  Energy taxes, by discouraging consumption without
augmenting the profit margins of energy producers, actually discourage the
exploration and recovery of fossil fuels. 
</td></tr></table>
<P><BR>
<CENTER>
<P>
<A HREF="/ebb/fornaid.html"><IMG SRC="/images/forward.gif" ALT="Forward to the next page" BORDER=2></A>
<A HREF="/ebb/"><IMG SRC="/images/back.gif" ALT="Back to the beginning" BORDER=2></A>
