<HTML>
<HEAD>
<TITLE>CEI EBB: Environmental Politics Are Politics Nonetheless</TITLE>
</HEAD>

<BODY BGCOLOR="#EEEEEE" TEXT="000000" LINK="009900" VLINK="000099">

<TABLE BORDER=0 WIDTH=100%><TR><TD ALIGN=LEFT><A HREF="/ebb/"><IMG SRC="/images/ceiebb.gif" ALT="CEI Environmental Briefing Book" ALIGN=LEFT BORDER=0></A></TD></TR></TABLE>
<P>
<BR CLEAR>
<table border=0 cellpadding=15><tr><td>

<CENTER>
<H2>Environmental Politics Are Politics Nonetheless</H2>
</CENTER>

<P><BR>Nobel economist George Stigler once joked that choosing government
regulation on the assumption of &#147;market failure&#148; is like an opera
audition in which you reject the first singer before you hear the second one.
Most environmental problems result from the abuses and wastefulness endemic to
open-access, common-property resource systems, not from private property rights
and markets.   Yet even if shortcomings in our market economy were the primary
cause of environmental problems, it would not necessarily follow that
government can provide sensible solutions.  Political arrangements are also far
from perfect.  The relevant test for policymakers is not whether markets are
perfect but whether they perform better or worse than legislative mandates and
bureaucratic controls.<p>
	Although most Americans recognize that politics have a lot to do with the
pursuit of power, privilege, and special interest, there is a general
presumption that environmental politics are different.  When it comes to the
environment, we take it for granted that laws are what they seem, that the
legislators who enact those laws and the bureaucrats who implement them are
earnestly struggling to protect public interests and that these laws and rules
will be enforced in a fair and sensible manner.  Far more often than is
commonly realized, however, the purpose and effect of environmental regulation
is to serve narrow political and economic interests, not environmental
objectives.<p>
	The details of environmental policy have major economic consequences.  Thus
when environmental policies are framed and implemented, economic interests
lobby and litigate and make alliances with environmental organizations to
ensure favorable treatment for their own industries or companies.  Several
major environmental programs contain traditional &#147;pork-barrel&#148;
programs wrapped in green packaging or special-interest protections designed to
tilt the economic playing field in a particular direction.  Many environmental
programs do more to line the pockets of special interests than they do to
protect the planet.<p>
<UL>
<LI>	To placate agricultural interests the Clinton administration proposed
guaranteeing ethanol, a corn-based fuel, 30 percent of a lucrative fuel
additive market under the <A HREF="/ebb/cleanair.html">Clean Air Act</A> Amendments of 1990.  Had it not been
invalidated by a federal court, this move (which was opposed by groups ranging
from Consumer Alert to the Sierra Club to the American Petroleum Institute)
would have cost consumers between $48 million and $350 million per year.  Even
EPA officials acknowledged the proposal would do little, if anything for the
environment.  This program is itself only a small part of alternative fuel
subsidies and set-asides that could cost consumers as much as $3 billion each
year.<A HREF="#1"><sup>1</sup></A> <p>

<LI>	Of the first $8 billion ostensibly spent for toxic waste cleanup under
<A HREF="/ebb/suprfund.html">Superfund</A>, the biggest federal environmental program, the lion&#146;s share
ended up in the pockets of lawyers and consultants.  These &#147;transaction
costs,&#148; which include administative overhead, consume &#147;35 percent of
corporate Superfund expenditures, 88 percent of insurance company Superfund
expenditures, and 50 percent of public Superfund
expenditures.&#148;<A HREF="#2"><sup>2</sup></A> As a result, cleanup at Superfund sites has
proceeded at a snail&#146;s pace; After 15 years, only 108 of the 1,219
landfills and chemical dumps on EPA&#146;s priority list have been cleaned up
and deleted from the list.<A HREF="#3"><sup>3</sup></A><p>

<LI>	Aside from lawyers and consultants, the principal beneficiaries of Superfund
have been environmental organizations and waste treatment companies.  In the
mid-1980s, a coalition of those groups lobbied successfully to expand the
number of Superfund sites and mandate use of the most expensive cleanup
methods.  They even succeeded in blocking measures aimed at reducing the
production of hazardous waste!<A HREF="#4"><sup>4</sup></A><p>

<LI>	<A HREF="/ebb/cleanair.html">The Clean Air Act</A> of 1970 allowed utilities to choose whatever means they
considered most cost-effective in meeting federal requirements to limit sulfur
dioxide emissions.  The 1977 Amendments put an end to this sensible policy
after producers of high-sulfur coal lobbied to require set emission reductions
irrespective of the initial amount of emissions being produced.  This made it
too expensive to use cleaner-burning, low-sulfur coal.  The result was not only
to perpetuate large-scale use of dirtier coal, but also to raise consumer costs
by forcing many utilities to install scrubbers, even when using low-sulfur coal
would have provided the same environmental benefit.<A HREF="#5"><sup>5</sup></A><p>
</UL>
	<P>Also, let&#146;s not forget that bureaucrats have their own organizational
interests, which do not automatically coincide with the public interest.  A
1987 survey of EPA officials found little correlation between the
officials&#146; judgments as to which areas merited most attention and what the
agency actually did.<A HREF="#6"><sup>6</sup></A> In part, these skewed priorities result from
the political nature of the budget process.  To enlarge its share of federal
resources, EPA has not been above sensationalizing environmental risks such as
asbestos in schools, radon in homes, and pesticide residues on food.  When
environmental protection is political, it is bound to be distorted by fads,
careerism, and greed, while being simultaneously insulated from the market
disciplines that correct for such failings in private firms.  In this respect,
politics is politics, even if you paint it green.<p>
	
The lesson for policymakers?  Don&#146;t assume that every measure proposed or
adopted in the name of the environment will actually advance environmental
goals.  All too often, environmental regulation &#151; like many policies
enacted by the federal government &#151; is regulation of, by, and for special
interests.<p><br>

<b>Notes:</b><p>
<DL><DD>
<A NAME="1"></A><sup>1</sup> See, for example, Jonathan Adler,&#148;Alternative Fuel
Follies With Ethanol Vapors,&#148; <i>The Washington Times</i>, May 3, 1995, p.
A14.<p>

<A NAME="2"></A><sup>2</sup> See Jerry Taylor, &#147;Salting the Earth: The Case for Repealing
Superfund,&#148; <i>Regulation</i> (Spring 1995), p. 53.<p>

<A NAME="3"></A><sup>3</sup> Information provided by RCRA/Superfund/EPCRA Hotline, June 12,
1996.<p>

<A NAME="4"></A><sup>4</sup> Marc K. Landy and Mary Hague, &#147;The Coalition for Waste:
Private Interests and Superfund,&#148; in <i>Environmental Politics: Public
Costs, Private Rewards</i>, M. Greve and F. Smith eds. (New York: Praeger,
1992), p. 74.<p>

<A NAME="5"></A><sup>5</sup> Bruce A. Ackerman, and William T. Hassler, <i>Clean Coal, Dirty Air
</i>(New Haven, Conn.: Yale University Press, 1981).<p>

<A NAME="6"></A><sup>6</sup> U.S. EPA, <i>Unfinished Business: A Comparative Assessment of
Environmental Problems</i> (Washington, D.C.: U.S. EPA, Office of Policy
Analysis, February 1987).
</DL>

</td></tr></table>
<P><BR>
