<HTML>
<HEAD>
<TITLE>CEI EBB: The True State of America's Environment</TITLE>
</HEAD>

<BODY BGCOLOR="#EEEEEE" TEXT="000000" LINK="009900" VLINK="000099">

<TABLE BORDER=0 WIDTH=100%><TR><TD ALIGN=LEFT><A HREF="/ebb/"><IMG SRC="/images/ceiebb.gif" ALT="CEI Environmental Briefing Book" ALIGN=LEFT BORDER=0></A></TD></TR></TABLE>
<P>
<BR CLEAR>
<table border=0 cellpadding=15><tr><td>

<CENTER>
<H2>The True State of America&#146;s Environment</H2>
</CENTER>

<P><BR>Environmental lobbying organizations seem preoccupied with visions of
man-made ecological catastrophe.  Each year the Worldwatch Institute publishes
a <i>State of the World</i> report that purports to document the planet&#146;s
deteriorating environmental condition.  Michael Oppenheimer of the
Environmental Defense Fund compares the earth to a truck careening down a
highway about to plunge over rail and into the abyss.  On the basis of such
predictions policy makers are called upon to enact costly new regulatory
programs that can cause tremendous economic and social dislocations.<p>
	Yet while real environmental problems do exist, the earth, and more
specifically the United States, is a long way from catastrophe.  Indeed, in
most respects environmental trends are getting better, not worse, and in many
cases environmental regulations had little to do with it.  These facts are
documented in the Competitive Enterprise Institute&#146;s <A HREF="/trustate.html"><i>The True State of
the Planet</i></A>, edited by Ronald Bailey.<A HREF="#1"><sup>1</sup></A> Among the environmental
successes that should be celebrated are the following:<p>
<UL>
<LI>	In the United States ambient levels of sulfur dioxide, carbon monoxide,
volatile organic compounds, atmospheric ozone and particulates in the air are
decreasing.<A HREF="#2"><sup>2</sup></A><p>

<LI>	Industrial pollution has been largely eliminated as a source of contamination
in most of America&#146;s rivers, lakes and streams.  Consequently, 95 percent
of the nation&#146;s rivers are considered fishable.<A HREF="#3"><sup>3</sup></A> <p>

<li>	The United States has achieved no net loss of wetlands; in fact, in the 1990s
more wetlands have been created than have been converted to other land-uses.
Every year the U.S. is gaining tens of thousands of acres of
wetlands.<A HREF="#4"><sup>4</sup></A><p>
<LI>	In the last fifty years, life expectancy at birth has increased by more than
a decade, and continues to increase.<A HREF="#5"><sup>5</sup></A><p>

<LI>	In the last forty years, the amount of cropland in production has declined by
40 million acres.  At the same time crop production per acre has more than
doubled.<A HREF="#6"><sup>6</sup></A><p>

<LI>	Over the last fifty years America has been the world&#146;s leading timber
producer.  During this period, total forest area remained stable and total
standing timber volume increased significantly.<A HREF="#7"><sup>7</sup></A><p>
</UL>
	<P>Many of the environmental concerns voiced by activists were, and continue to
be, overstated.  For example, while there is concern about the impact of
industrial chemicals on human health, pollution appears to account for less
than one percent of human cancer.  A recent study by the National Academy of
Sciences confirmed what many scientists have known for some time: synthetic
chemicals, such as pesticides, in the human diet are not a significant source
of cancer.<A HREF="#8"><sup>8</sup></A>  People are at a greater risk for cancer as a result of
unhealthy behavior, such as smoking or an unhealthy diet, than from industrial
pollution.<p>
	Environmental progress is important and should continue into the future.  One
of the greatest hopes for further environmental improvements is technological
advance.  Technological improvements reduce the environmental impact of
industrial production and lower the costs of maintaining a clean environment.
For example:<p>
<UL>
<LI>	Technological advances have greatly enhanced energy efficiency; energy
consumption per unit of gross domestic product has declined dramatically in
developed countries over the past twenty years.<A HREF="#9"><sup>9</sup></A><p>

<LI>	Using modern silvicultural techniques, the world&#146;s current industrial
wood needs can be met using only 5 percent of the world&#146;s total current
forestland.<A HREF="#10"><sup>10</sup></A><p>

<LI>	Modern agricultural methods, such as conservation tillage and no-till
farming, are capable of reducing soil erosion by 65 percent and 98 percent
respectively.<A HREF="#11"><sup>11</sup></A><p>
<LI>	Increased aquaculture production could lessen the pressures that encourage
overfishing; aquaculture production increased by over 60 percent between 1984
and 1991.<A HREF="#12"><sup>12</sup></A><p>
</UL>
	<P>It is well-documented that &#147;richer is cleaner.&#148;  As nations become
wealthier, there are more resources to devote to environmental concerns such as
air and water quality.<A HREF="#13"><sup>13</sup></A>  Moreover, economic growth finances the
development of advanced technologies that are more environmentally sensitive,
and market competition encourages greater efficiency in the use of material
inputs, thereby lessening the human impact on the natural world.  Finally, a
wealthier population is also more prone to concern for environmental
amenities.<p>
	
While apocalyptic scenarios are a staple of the environmental debate, the
global reality is not so alarming.  There are real environmental problems, but
few, if any, pose a threat to human civilization.  In those cases where
environmental concerns are real, the best thing concerned policy makers can do
to promote further environmental progress is encourage economic and
technological advance and the spread of free market institutions.<p>
<p>
<br>


<b>Notes:</b><p>
<DL><DD>
<A NAME="1"></A><sup>1</sup> <A HREF="/trustate.html"><i>The True State of the Planet</i></A>, Ronald Bailey, ed.
(New York: The Free Press, 1995).<p>

<A NAME="2"></A><sup>2</sup> Council on Environmental Quality, <i>Environmental Quality</i>
(Washington, D.C.: CEQ, 1992).<p>

<A NAME="3"></A><sup>3</sup> U.S. Environmental Protection Agency, <i>Environmental Indicators
of Water Quality in the United States</i> (Washington, D.C.: U.S. EPA, June
1996).<p>

<A NAME="4"></A><sup>4</sup> Jonathan Tolman, &#147;Achieving No Net Loss,&#148; <i>National
Wetlands Newsletter</i>, May-June 1995, p. 5.<p>

<A NAME="5"></A><sup>5</sup> U.S. Public Health Service, <i>U.S. Life Tables and Actuarial
Tables</i>, 1938-1941 and U.S. National Center For Health Statistics, <i>Vital
Statistics of the United States</i>, 1993.<p>

<A NAME="6"></A><sup>6</sup> Council of Economic Advisors, <i>Economic Report of the
President</i> (Washington, D.C.: Government Printing Office, January 1993), pp.
456-457.<p>

<A NAME="7"></A><sup>7</sup> Roger Sedjo, &#147;Forests: Conflicting Signals,&#148; in <i>The
True State of Planet</i>, chapter 6.<p>

<A NAME="8"></A><sup>8</sup> The National Research Council, Carcinogens and Anticarcinogens in
the Human Diet (Washington, D.C.: National Academy Press, 1996), pp. 303-312.<p>

