<HTML>
<HEAD>
<TITLE>CEI EBB: Grazing Reform</TITLE>
</HEAD>

<BODY BGCOLOR="#EEEEEE" TEXT="000000" LINK="009900" VLINK="000099">

<TABLE BORDER=0 WIDTH=100%><TR><TD ALIGN=LEFT><A HREF="/ebb/"><IMG SRC="/images/ceiebb.gif" ALT="CEI Environmental Briefing Book" ALIGN=LEFT BORDER=0></A></TD></TR></TABLE>
<P>
<BR CLEAR>
<table border=0 cellpadding=15><tr><td>

<CENTER>
<H2>Grazing Reform</H2>
</CENTER>

<P><BR>The current approach to grazing on federal lands is bad for ranchers, bad for
the taxpayer, and bad for environmental protection.  The lack of secure
property rights has disadvantaged western ranchers and weakened the incentives
for effective land management.  Property-based reform of grazing on federal
lands is a necessity. <p>
	
Federal grazing lands are currently subject to the &#147;scientific
management&#148; paradigm.  Under this approach, the federal government
determines how all of its rangeland should be utilized, and establishes
detailed land management guidelines.<p>
	Under a property-based policy, the management of rangeland would not be
determined by a central government planner subject to influence by various
interest groups (ranchers, environmentalists, recreationists, etc.).  Rather,
land management decisions would be made by those who hold forage access rights.
All groups that wish to benefit from federal rangeland resources would have the
opportunity to do so through the purchase and trade of private rights.  Whereas
the current system is marred by conflict, under this free market regime,
rangeland management would be based upon voluntary transactions, ensuring a
more peaceful process and just outcome.<p>
	Free market grazing reform should be based upon the following principles:<p>
<UL>
<LI> Existing rangeland subsidies to <i>all</i> parties (ranchers, recreationists,
bureaucrats, etc.) should be phased out over time.  So long as the federal
government owns rangeland, such lands should be managed at zero net cost to the
taxpayer.<p>
<LI>	Existing &#147;forage access&#148; (grazing) permits should be recognized as
tradable private property rights owned by the existing permit holders,
providing security of tenure to ranchers, and increasing the incentives for
sustainable stewardship of the land.  These rights should be of indefinite
tenure, requiring the payment of compensation should the government seek to
terminate them or otherwise prevent their use.<p>
<LI>	All Americans should have an equal opportunity to purchase, hold, and use
rangeland &#147;forage access&#148; permits (grazing permits).  Current
restrictions on nonranching access to forage resources on federal lands,
including base property requirements, restrictions on subleasing, and
&#147;use-it-or-lose-it&#148; rules, should be eliminated.<p>
<LI>	Holders of &#147;forage access&#148; (grazing) permits should have the
freedom to manage their forage resources as they desire, and determine the
proper level of use; the government&#146;s role should be limited to enforcing
nuisance rules (i.e. preventing one rancher from harming the land, forage, or
resources of other users) and enforcing voluntary transactions. <p>
</UL>
	<P>These principles would lead to sounder rangeland management through the use of
the marketplace. Environmental groups concerned about the state of current
grazing lands could seek to modify existing ranching practices by negotiations
with ranchers or the purchase of grazing rights (as some environmental groups
have sought to do in the past with minimal success).  Ranchers would also have
the security of knowing that forage access rights are recognized by the federal
government and could not be arbitrarily taken away or infringed upon in the
future.  Although some believe that existing rights are secure, the experience
of federal land management and regulation suggests otherwise.  Free-market
grazing reform is a win-win alternative to current federal land management.<p>
<i>Q:  Are the grazing reforms put forward by either the Clinton Administration
or the Republican Congress market oriented?</i><p>
<p>
A:  No.  Both reform proposals fall far short of necessary grazing reforms.
The Clinton proposal, advanced by Interior Secretary Bruce Babbitt, would
increase bureaucratic meddling in the management of Western rangelands and
would impose significant burdens on many ranchers. The proposals advanced in
the Republican Congress would allow insufficient flexibility in land management
and alternative uses of federal rangelands.  Free-market grazing reform would
be superior to both approaches.<p>
<p>
<i>Q:  Don&#146;t ranchers pay below-market rates to use federal
rangeland?</i><p>
<p>
A:  Grazing permit fees are set by a bureaucratic formula, not market
pressures.  This formula sets the permit fee for all federal rangeland.  It is
fair to assume that this relatively arbitrary fee is too high for some lands,
and too low for others.  This is inevitable so long as the federal government
seeks to set a single fee for all federal rangeland.  <p>
	It is true that grazing permits on federal lands cost less than those on
private land.  However, federal lands are also typically lower quality, and
federal land ranchers are more likely to have to finance any land improvements
on federal lands. The only way to get market pricing for rangeland is to allow
the market to operate, and end the practice of politically-set grazing fees.<p>
<p>
<i>Q:  Is ranching subsidized on federal lands?</i><p>
<p>
A:  The net costs of federal land grazing programs are over $200 million per
year in the Bureau of Land Management alone.  However it would be a mistake to
assume that this necessarily represents a subsidy to ranchers, as a significant
portion of rangeland management costs is certainly due to BLM inefficiency and
burdensome regulatory requirements.<p>
	However, ranchers, on both public and private lands, do receive some federal
subsidies.  These include the emergency feed program, which costs approximately
$26.5 million per year, and the Animal Damage Control program, which spends
over $20 million per year controlling predators that can impact livestock
operations.  Both of these programs should be eliminated.<p>
<p>
<i>Q:  Will market-based grazing reform drive ranchers off of federal
lands?</i><p>
<p>
A:  Free-market grazing reform would make it easier for federal-land ranchers
to sell their grazing permits to other parties, including non-ranchers.  Some
ranchers would certainly exercise this option.  Others would not.  Under the
free-market approach, ranchers would only leave federal lands if they
voluntarily chose to do so.  Neither federal bureaucrats nor environmental
groups would have the power to force ranchers off of the land.  Ranchers,
owning property in their forage access rights, would be protected from
regulatory takings, and would have greater control of how their forage is
used.
</td></tr></table>
<P><BR>
<CENTER>
<P>
<A HREF="/ebb/intersta.html"><IMG SRC="/images/forward.gif" ALT="Forward to the next page" BORDER=2></A>
<A HREF="/ebb/"><IMG SRC="/images/back.gif" ALT="Back to the beginning" BORDER=2></A>
