<DOCHDR>
http://www.cei.org:80/ebb/fedlands.html 207.33.42.44 19970101100329 text/html 7200
HTTP/1.0 200 OK
Date: Wed, 01 Jan 1997 10:03:41 GMT
Server: Apache/1.1.1
Content-type: text/html
Content-length: 7029
Last-modified: Tue, 27 Aug 1996 23:42:58 GMT
</DOCHDR>
<HTML>
<HEAD>
<TITLE>CEI EBB: Federal Lands</TITLE>
</HEAD>

<BODY BGCOLOR="#EEEEEE" TEXT="000000" LINK="009900" VLINK="000099">

<TABLE BORDER=0 WIDTH=100%><TR><TD ALIGN=LEFT><A HREF="/ebb/"><IMG SRC="/images/ceiebb.gif" ALT="CEI Environmental Briefing Book" ALIGN=LEFT BORDER=0></A></TD></TR></TABLE>
<P>
<BR CLEAR>
<table border=0 cellpadding=15><tr><td>

<CENTER>
<H2>Federal Lands</H2>
</CENTER>

<P><BR>The federal government is the largest landowner in the United States, owning
nearly one-third of the land.  Federal ownership of land is most pervasive in
the Western United States.  The federal government owns over half of the state
of California and over 80 percent of Nevada.  In some areas, such as
California&#146;s Inyo County, the federal government owns over 90 percent of
the land.  Federal land ownership has resulted in extensive land mismanagement
and is an affront to the tradition of private property in this country.  Policy
makers should seek to divest the federal government of most federal lands.<p>
	Expansive government control of land means that many land-use decisions are
based upon political considerations, rather than on economic or environmental
grounds.  Often these decisions are made in Washington, D.C. with little
concern for the needs and concerns of local communities.  As a result, federal
lands are routinely mismanaged and a drain on the American taxpayer.  Moreover,
federal ownership of lands often entails the imposition of land-use controls on
neighboring communities.  This increases the costs of federal ownership.<p>
	Federal land is managed by the Bureau of Land Management, the Bureau of
Reclamation, the National Park Service and the Fish and Wildlife Service in the
Department of the Interior, as well as by the Forest Service in the Department
of Agriculture, among others.  This duplication of responsibilities is
inefficient.  The problem is compounded by the fact that different land
agencies often work at cross purposes and fail to coordinate important
activities such as fire control.<p>
	Barring the wholesale transfer of federal lands to state governments and the
private sector, two key reforms should be implemented to ensure that the
federal government is more responsible and efficient in its management of
federal lands.  These are:<p>
<UL>
<LI>	<b>No Net Loss of Private Property</b> -- The federal government owns a
sufficient portion of the country as it is.  There is no need for federal
landholdings to increase.  At the same time, the federal government owns much
land that has no need to be in federal hands.  This reform would simply require
the federal government to sell off an offsetting portion of land before
engaging in further land acquisition.  Thus if the federal government wished to
purchase a 2,000 acre wilderness area, it could do so only if it transferred
2,000 acres of federal land into the private sector.<p>

<LI>	<b>Self-Sufficiency for Federal Land Units</b> -- Many federal lands are a
drain on the treasury, and therefore a burden on the taxpayer.  This is even
true on lands where the federal government collects user fees for
timber-cutting, grazing, or recreation.  Congress should require each federal
land unit that is used for commercial or recreational purposes to become
self-sufficient.  This means that land managers would be forced either to cut
administrative costs or increase user fees for resource development and
recreation so that the individual units no longer lose money.  Such efficient
management occurs on private and state lands; it should occur on federal lands
as well.<p>
</UL>
	Ultimately, the federal government should have to divest itself of significant
portions of its landholdings, devolving land to state governments, donating
ecologically-sensitive parcels to conservation organizations and/or selling
lands to private interests.  America was built upon a tradition of private
property and that tradition should be upheld.<p>
<i>Q:  Federal lands are clearly mismanaged.  But isn&#146;t there
mismanagement on private lands as well?</i><p>
<p>
A:  There is mismanagement on all types of land, private and federal.  However,
private lands, on the whole, tend to be managed better than public lands.  When
a private landowner mismanages land, that owner bears the cost, economic and
otherwise, as the value of the land declines.  Federal land managers, on the
other hand, bear none of the costs of land mismanagement.  This disparate
incentive structure means that private lands tend to be managed more soundly.<p>
<p>
<i>Q:  How would you propose transferring lands from the federal government to
the private sector?</i><p>
<p>
A:  There is no easy answer to this question.  One possibility would be for
Congress to appoint a Commission to inventory all federal lands and evaluate
what uses are appropriate on which lands.  Those lands that are primarily used
for logging, ranching, or other resource development purposes could be the
first to be transferred into the private sector.  After all, the private sector
is more than capable of providing for such economic concerns.  The Commission
also could identify which lands, if any, must remain under federal control
because of environmental sensitivity or other compelling concerns.  This
process could also be used to consolidate the numerous federal land agencies to
increase the efficiency of land management and prevent federal land agencies
from working at cross-purposes.  Another possibility would be to transfer many
landholdings to state governments, which would, in turn, have the opportunity
to privatize selected lands.<p>
<i></i><p>
<i>Q:  Would divesting the federal government of land ownership eliminate
outdoor recreational opportunities for Americans?</i><p>
<p>
A:  Not necessarily.  There are many private lands that are managed for
recreation in conjunction with other uses.  For example, IP Timberlands in the
southeastern United States manages many of its lands for both timber production
and recreation.  Because trees are only cut every few decades, IP Timberlands
is able to encourage the use of its land for hiking, camping, hunting and bird
watching in the interim.  This not only means that IP Timberlands makes a
greater profit off of its land, it means that the land is managed in a more
ecologically diverse manner as well.
</td></tr></table>
<P><BR>
<CENTER>
<P>
<A HREF="/ebb/gwarming.html"><IMG SRC="/images/forward.gif" ALT="Forward to the next page" BORDER=2></A>
<A HREF="/ebb/"><IMG SRC="/images/back.gif" ALT="Back to the beginning" BORDER=2></A>
