<DOCHDR>
http://www.cei.org:80/ebb/recfees.html 207.33.42.44 19970101100346 text/html 6696
HTTP/1.0 200 OK
Date: Wed, 01 Jan 1997 10:03:57 GMT
Server: Apache/1.1.1
Content-type: text/html
Content-length: 6525
Last-modified: Wed, 28 Aug 1996 01:09:20 GMT
</DOCHDR>
<HTML>
<HEAD>
<TITLE>CEI EBB: Recreation Subsidies</TITLE>
</HEAD>

<BODY BGCOLOR="#EEEEEE" TEXT="000000" LINK="009900" VLINK="000099">

<TABLE BORDER=0 WIDTH=100%><TR><TD ALIGN=LEFT><A HREF="/ebb/"><IMG SRC="/images/ceiebb.gif" ALT="CEI Environmental Briefing Book" ALIGN=LEFT BORDER=0></A></TD></TR></TABLE>
<P>
<BR CLEAR>
<table border=0 cellpadding=15><tr><td>

<CENTER>
<H2>Recreation Subsidies</H2>
</CENTER>

<P><BR>Although not thought of as a subsidized activity, recreation on federal land
costs the Federal Government $1.7 billion a year.  In contrast the government
only collects $159.7 million a year in user fees.  Recreation is probably the
most subsidized activity on federals lands.  Recreationists need to start
paying to play.  One way to do this is the adoption of broad based user fees.
These fees would be determined by the appropriate federal agency and kept
within the recreational system to pay for it.  The federal agencies that run
recreational services include not only the famous National Park Service and the
Forest Service, but also the Bureau of Land Management, the Fish and Wildlife
Service, the Bureau of Reclamation, and the Army Corp of Engineers.  <p>
	
Recreationists receive a tremendously greater benefit from the government
provision of goods and services than do other subsidized activities.  The
Forest Service has estimated the fees it receives for various activities and
has compared this to what these activities would cost in the market.  These are
the economic benefits that users receive.  In 1993 they were given as:<p>
<BR>
<CENTER>
<table border=2><tr><td></td><td>
RETURNS TO GOVERNMENT ECONOMIC BENEFITS (from user fees)</td>
	  
<td>RECEIVED BY USERS</td></tr>

<tr><td>Recreation</td><td>$49.3 million</td><td>$6.8 billion</td></tr>
<tr><td>Range	  </td><td>$10.5 million	</td><td>$61.4 million</td></tr>
<tr><td>Minerals	  </td><td>$210  million </td><td>              	$573.9 million</td></tr>
<tr><td>Timber	</td><td>$1.1019 billion</td><td> $1.020 billion</td></tr>
</table>
</CENTER>
<p>


	In other words, recreationists received benefits almost 138 times more
valuable than what they paid, while range, mineral and timber users received
far less, according to the Forest Service&#146;s own numbers.  These numbers
are for the Forest Service only, and do not include the other government
agencies that provide recreation.  Nevertheless, it is clear that
recreationists are making out like old West bandits.<p>
	Although recreation is treated differently than these other subsidized
activities it has something in common with them:  It causes environmental
damage.  Recreation is so underpriced that many areas are overused, which
damages environmental health.  Additionally, the millions of recreational
visitors damage the land in countless ways by camping, hiking, biking, skiing
and other activities.  Not only do they get to play for cheap, but the repairs
and upkeep needed to keep these federal areas in shape are not done.  The
combined repair backlog for the National Park Service and the Forest Service is
$5 billion.<p>
	Even environmental groups recognize the deleterious environmental effects of
subsidized recreation.  The <i>Green Scissors &#145;96</i> report, published by
Friends of the Earth, targets recreational subsidies for reform.  Radical
environmentalist Dave Foreman, co-founder of the Wildlands Project, wrote,
&#147;when conservationists cry about funding cuts for National Parks, we
stumble into the morass of the victim, of the irresponsible citizens who want
their entitlement handouts.&#148;  Foreman advocates recreational users start
paying for what they are using.<p>
	Were federal lands privately owned, recreation subsidies would be eliminated.
Barring that, one solution to this problem is to require the agencies to
collect fees to pay for the costs of the recreational services provided so that
no subsidy occurs.  Traditionally, some agencies have had a wide latitude in
setting fees but have had no incentive to do so because they get back so little
of the money collected.<p>
<i>Q:  Don&#146;t people already pay for the National Parks and other federal
recreational lands with their taxes?</i><p>
<p>
A:  All taxpayers pay for the recreational services, yet only some use them.
Those who use it are being subsidized by those who do not.  Recreational users
have not paid the full cost for their visit and this is causing damages to
federally owned lands.<p>
<p>
<i>Q:  Wouldn&#146;t requiring public lands to raise their own revenues
encourage uses that undermine conservation or biodiversity.</i><p>
<p>
A:  No.  In fact the exact opposite would happen.  Recreation can hurt the
environment by affecting and destroying plant life.  Having fees will reduce
visitors in over-crowded areas and reduce damage there.  Underutilitized areas
can have competitive prices that attract visitors.  This process will allow
recreational usage to be smoothed out among competing areas.  An added bonus is
that when people pay for a service they usually tend to value it more and treat
it better.  This has even been pointed out by environmentalists as a reason to
have fees.<p>
<p>
<i>Q: Wouldn&#146;t raising fees and charging new ones discourage poor people
from using the parks or make recreation an &#147;elitist&#148; activity?</i><p>

A:  Almost all the people that visit these places in the first place are what
we would at least call &#147;middle class.&#148;  This is because the costs to
visit most federal recreational areas is expensive compared to the small fee
that will be charged for its use.  These types of activities are not engaged in
by poor people who cannot afford the trip costs in the first place.  Concern of
this nature can be taken care of with fee free days in some areas for those
that find the fees too expensive.

</td></tr></table>
<P><BR>
<CENTER>
<P>
<A HREF="/ebb/delegate.html"><IMG SRC="/images/forward.gif" ALT="Forward to the next page" BORDER=2></A>
<A HREF="/ebb/"><IMG SRC="/images/back.gif" ALT="Back to the beginning" BORDER=2></A>
<P>
