<HTML>
<HEAD>
<TITLE>CEI EBB: Clean Water Act</TITLE>
</HEAD>

<BODY BGCOLOR="#EEEEEE" TEXT="000000" LINK="009900" VLINK="000099">

<TABLE BORDER=0 WIDTH=100%><TR><TD ALIGN=LEFT><A HREF="/ebb/"><IMG SRC="/images/ceiebb.gif" ALT="CEI Environmental Briefing Book" ALIGN=LEFT BORDER=0></A></TD></TR></TABLE>
<P>
<BR CLEAR>
<table border=0 cellpadding=15><tr><td>

<CENTER>
<H2>Clean Water Act</H2>
</CENTER>

<P><BR>The United States has experienced substantial gains in cleaning up our lakes,
rivers, and streams over the past three decades.  Yet today, the Environmental
Protection Agency continues to write more stringent and more expensive
regulations that produce minimal environmental results.  The Clean Water Act is
a perfect example of diminishing returns, and why environmental regulation
needs to be reformed.<p>
	America&#146;s waters were once in bad shape.  On June 22, 1969, sparks from a
passing train ignited floating debris and industrial chemicals in the Cuyahoga
river, near Cleveland, Ohio.  The image of a burning river spurred the passage
of the Clean Water Act.  <p>
	Today, the offensive industrial pollution that characterized the 1960s has
been virtually eliminated.  Many rivers are cleaner than they have been in
decades.  Along the Cuyahoga riverfront in Cleveland there are now dozens of
upscale restaurants and bars, and during the summertime the river is crowded
with pleasure boats.  Tremendous progress has been made.<p>
	While there is far less water pollution to address, complying with the Clean
Water Act has become far more expensive.  Full compliance would cost as much as
$99 billion per year, according to the EPA.  This is more than the federal
government collects in corporate income tax.  The majority of these costs
&#151; as much as $41 billion per year &#151; are placed upon businesses.  A
significant portion of the Clean Water Act&#146;s costs, however, are also born
by municipalities, up to $37 billion a year.<p>
	In some cases compliance costs are so high because the EPA regulations are
inflexible and overly stringent.  For example, the EPA requires city treatment
plants to remove 30 percent of the organic material from the sewage that they
treat.  In most cities this is not a problem.  However, in Anchorage, Alaska,
the sewage coming into the treatment plant was so clean that it would have cost
$135 million to build a facility to treat water that already meets the
EPA&#146;s discharge standards.  It was cheaper for Anchorage to allow two
local fish processing plants to dump 5,000 pound of fish guts into the sewer
system so that a 30 percent reduction in organic waste could be achieved at an
affordable cost.  This is not how environmental policy should work.<p>
	The following elements should be part of any Clean Water Act reform
proposal:<p>
<UL>
<li>	The EPA should be required to perform a cost/benefit analysis on each
regulation to ensure that costs of complying with clean water regulation do not
outweigh their benefits.<p>
<li>	If the EPA sets stringent new standards that will be expensive to implement
for state and local governments, it should also provide the funds to comply
with the standard.  In other words, the EPA should refrain from imposing
unfunded environmental mandates.<p>
<li>	The EPA should provide greater flexibility for state and local environmental
agencies to set standards based on local needs.<p>
</ul>
<p>
	In the long run, water pollution control efforts must move away from federal
command-and-control regulations in favor of common law-based-standards.  This
approach, which empowers landowners to protect water quality from pollution and
other nuisances through the court system, has shown promise in other countries.
Yet a common law approach to water pollution is often precluded by existing
federal law.<p><BR>
<i>Q:  Shouldn&#146;t the Clean Water Act be strengthened to prevent companies
from polluting our steams, lakes and rivers?</i><p>
<p>
A:  The number one cause of pollution in America&#146;s rivers and lakes is not
industrial pollution, but agricultural runoff.  The number two cause is
municipal and urban runoff.  According to the EPA, industrial pollution ranks
last as a cause of pollution.  Imposing more requirements on industry will
simply create higher costs without achieving significant environmental
improvement.  <p>
<p>
<i>Q:  How would you change the Clean Water Act without worsening water
quality?</i><p>
<p>
A:  The first thing that must be done is to put more flexibility in the hands
of state and local officials.  Even the current administrator of the EPA, Carol
Browner, thinks it&#146;s essential.  In a 1994 speech she said, &#147;We must
allow for flexibility, innovation, and common sense as states and communities
look for ways to achieve the standards.&#148;  Even according to Browner, under
the present scheme, &#147;innovation is stifled rather than encouraged.&#148;
If anything, the EPA should be providing technical assistance and funding to
communities not dictating priorities and technology.<p>
<p>
<i>Q:  Are there ways to protect water quality without resorting to federal
regulation?</i><p>
<p>
A:  Yes.  It would be more effective and equitable if water quality was
protected through the assertion and protection of private water rights, rather
than by command-and-control regulation.  Under common law principles,
individual polluters could be held liable for damaging the water quality of
those downstream.  This would provide a strict, but fair, standard whereby no
individual, corporation, or even municipality, could infringe upon the water
rights of another.  This approach also would be more flexible, because upstream
and downstream users could negotiate over competing water uses.  However, this
sort of common law, property rights-based approach has been preempted by state
and federal water pollution laws. <p>
<p>
<i>Q:  Should the Clean Water Act be expanded to control non-point sources of
pollution such as agricultural and urban runoffs?</i><p>
<p>
A:  Rather than expand the CWA, Congress should amend it to permit local
flexibility and experimentation.  Emissions create problems <i>somewhere</i>
before they create problems <i>elsewhere</i>.  Local communities and water
users should be allowed to deal with runoffs based on their own assessment of
the environmental and economic trade-offs.  In some cases, local solutions
might be facilitated by extending property rights to recreational and sporting
clubs, shell fisheries, and others with a stake in water quality.  When local
problems are addressed locally, they are less apt to become large problems
requiring federal intervention.
</td></tr></table>
<P><BR>
<CENTER>
<P>
<A HREF="/ebb/ecomgmt.html"><IMG SRC="/images/forward.gif" ALT="Forward to the next page" BORDER=2></A>
<A HREF="/ebb/"><IMG SRC="/images/back.gif" ALT="Back to the beginning" BORDER=2></A>
<P>
<TABLE BORDER=0 CELLPADDING=2>
<TR><TD WIDTH=175 ALIGN=RIGHT><B><A HREF="/about.html">About CEI</A> | <A HREF="/policy.html">Public Policy</A></B></TD> 
<TD WIDTH=175 HEIGHT=67 ALIGN=CENTER><A HREF="/"><IMG SRC="/images/cei-back.gif" HEIGHT=67 WIDTH=155 ALT="CEI Home Page" BORDER=0></A></TD>
<TD WIDTH=175 ALIGN=LEFT><B><A HREF="/quote.html">Quote</A> | <A HREF="/sellout.html">Sellout</A></B></TD></TR>
</TABLE>
</CENTER>
<BR CLEAR>

</BODY>
