<HTML>
<HEAD>
<TITLE>CEI: Pick a Number: A Critique of Contingent Valuation Methodology and its Application in Public Policy</TITLE>
</HEAD>

<BODY BGCOLOR="FFFFFF">

<A NAME="top"></A>
<IMG SRC="ceiesp.gif" ALT="Environmental Studies Program" ALIGN=LEFT>
<BR>
<BR>
<BR>
<BR>
<BR>


<CENTER>
<H1>PICK A NUMBER<BR>
A Critique of Contingent Valuation Methodology and its Application<BR>
in Public Policy
</H1>
by Roger Bate

<BR>
<BR>
<BR>
<H2>Executive Summary</H2>
</CENTER>

<P>How much would you be willing to pay for an untouched expanse of wilderness?
The process by which this question can be answered is called Contingent
Valuation (CV).  CV attempts to quantify the &#147;satisfaction&#148; of
knowing that a natural resource exists, called a &#147;nonuse value&#148;
(NUV), regardless of any actual attempt to enjoy it. <i> </i> Once enumerated,
NUVs could  be used to impose liability for injuries to natural resources
placing billions of dollars at stake.<p>
The CV procedure involves asking people what they would pay, through increased
taxes, prices, or some other mechanism, to protect a valued environmental
resource.  For example, CV surveys provide respondents with a selection of
choices, such as a set of charities. You may be willing to give $100 to charity
and there may be eight separate charities that you find appealing. It is
therefore possible that in separate CV surveys, your stated willingness to
donate to charity could equal $800 in total, even though $100 is all that will
be given.  Obviously, this approach has serious problems including the
following:<p>
<UL>
<LI>the survey process can create the very values which they purport to measure;<p>

<LI>answers are likely to be biased by strategic considerations regarding the uses
to which  the survey could be put;<p>

<LI>survey results are often inconsistent;<p>

<LI>individuals are ill-trained to evaluate the monetary value of environmental
damage; <p>

<LI>rarely do individuals have experience in purchasing environmental assets;<p>

<LI>results cannot be empirically verified.<p>

</UL>
In sum, CV results are uncertain, subjective and speculative. <p>
CV surveys are further hindered by a fundamental difference between an actual
choice and a potential preference.  People may state a preference  for many
things but in actuality choose something entirely different. <p>
<UL>
<LI>A choice is superior to a preference because with the latter &#147;there is no
cost to being wrong, and therefore no incentive to undertake the mental effort
to be accurate;&#148; <p>
<LI>The only way to discover the values people place on things is through the
actual choices made by individuals. <p>

</UL>
Contingent valuation is an attempt to replicate the workings of the market
without a system where natural resource sites have well-defined private
property rights.  Markets allow people to make choices based on the amount they
are willing to pay for a good or service.   CV surveys  bypass the workings of
a true market process<i>.</i> The results from these surveys therefore cannot
be equated with market behavior, and any use of these figures should be treated
with skepticism.  <p>
Despite these problems, CV surveys are becoming more prevalent.  For instance,
the 1989 Supreme Court declared, in <i>Ohio v. U.S. Department of Interior</i>,
that nonuse values can be used to measure damages in liability cases.  <i>CV
surveys are likely to result in unwanted litigation, and could be presented in
liability claims at considerable social cost.</i>   Because the use of surveys
cannot be tested or verified empirically the valuation of natural resources
through CV is simply inappropriate.  The results may be interesting, but are
little more than picking a number, any number.<p>


<BR>
<HR NOSHADE>
<BR>
<CENTER>
<A HREF="publist1.html">You can order the full printed version of this essay for $4.00</A>
<BR>
<BR>

<A HREF="index.html">Back to the CEI Home Page</A><BR>
</CENTER>
<BR>
<BR>
</BODY>
</HTML>
</DOC>
<DOC>
<DOCNO>WT14-B01-40</DOCNO>
<DOCOLDNO>IA002-000017-B018-356</DOCOLDNO>
<DOCHDR>
http://www.cei.org:80/ebb/delegate.html 207.33.42.44 19970101100421 text/html 6068
HTTP/1.0 200 OK
Date: Wed, 01 Jan 1997 10:04:34 GMT
Server: Apache/1.1.1
Content-type: text/html
Content-length: 5897
Last-modified: Tue, 27 Aug 1996 23:42:13 GMT
</DOCHDR>
<HTML>
<HEAD>
<TITLE>CEI EBB: Regulatory Accountability</TITLE>
</HEAD>

<BODY BGCOLOR="#EEEEEE" TEXT="000000" LINK="009900" VLINK="000099">

<TABLE BORDER=0 WIDTH=100%><TR><TD ALIGN=LEFT><A HREF="/ebb/"><IMG SRC="/images/ceiebb.gif" ALT="CEI Environmental Briefing Book" ALIGN=LEFT BORDER=0></A></TD></TR></TABLE>
<P>
<BR CLEAR>
<table border=0 cellpadding=15><tr><td>

<CENTER>
<H2>Regulatory Accountability</H2>
</CENTER>

<P><BR>Although the Constitution reads, &#147;All legislative Powers herein granted
shall be vested in a Congress of the United States,&#148; law is routinely made
by unelected federal bureaucrats who are unaccountable to the public.  This has
diminished accountability for regulatory policies and fostered an
out-of-control federal bureaucracy.  Measures must be taken to halt the
excessive delegation of congressional lawmaking power to agencies.  There
should be no regulation without representation.<p>
	Federal regulations cost Americans approximately $647 billion per year
according to the General Accounting Office.  This is greater than the entire
annual federal budget was prior to 1966, and three times larger than the
federal deficit.  Regulatory reforms that seek to impose quick administrative
fixes, such as simple risk assessment or cost-benefit analysis requirements,
will do little to advance the necessary changes in America&#146;s regulatory
system.<p>
	 While Congress frequently delights in blaming agencies for economic woes, the
fact is that Congress gave agencies much of their power in the first place.
This enables elected representatives to take credit for enacting popular laws
&#151; such as the Clean Air Act and the Americans with Disabilities Act &#151;
while disavowing the implementing regulations that inevitably follow from their
own vague, high-minded legislative language.  If America&#146;s environmental
laws are too costly, Congress ultimately is to blame, and Congress must be
forced to make the necessary legal revisions.  <p>
	Federal law should require an explicit legislative endorsement of agency
regulations before they take effect.  Congress should have to vote on final
major agency regulations, and the President should have to sign them into law,
before they are binding on the public.  That&#146;s no more, but no less, than
is required of ordinary legislation.  Congress could, of course, approve
regulations on a fast-track basis to expedite the process.  But there should no
longer exist an opportunity for an elected official to blame an agency for an
unreasonable law.  Agencies should not make law, that is the job of Congress.<p>
	Incremental steps &#151; such as extending application of the unfunded federal
mandates law to private sector mandates, and regulatory budgeting &#151; are
also important in establishing accountability.  Like ordinary legislation,
voters should be able to check the record and determine where their
Representative or Senator stood on any given regulatory matter.  Restoring
direct accountability should be the guiding principle of regulatory reform.<p>
<i>Q:  How will Congress have time to vote on every regulation?  Won&#146;t the
legislative process grind to a halt?</i><p>

A:  Congress need not perform a recorded roll call vote on each regulation
finalized by an agency.  Unanimous consent &#147;voice vote&#148; procedures
can expedite the process.  Such procedures are routinely used in the Senate to
approve nominations, and often used to pass routine and housekeeping
legislation in both Houses.  It also may make sense to package certain
regulations together to be voted on simultaneously where roll calls are
necessary.  No amount of administrative difficulty, however, can excuse
&#147;regulation without representation.&#148;<p>
<p>
<i>Q:  Does Congress have the expertise to make judgments about health and
safety issues?</i><p>

A:  The implication here that agencies do have such expertise may not always
hold, since regulation writers are typically lawyers rather than scientists.
Moreover, agencies routinely farm out studies and lab work to contractors.  A
congressional vote merely places a stamp of approval on finalized agency
regulations that owe their origins to delegated power in the first place.  The
key point, however, is that the policy decision regarding what to do about
scientific findings &#151; as opposed to performing the science itself &#151;
most emphatically is a job for Congress.  American government relies on
citizen-legislators, not philosopher-kings.  <p>
<p>
<i>Q:  Didn&#146;t federal courts strike down an effort to allow for a
&#147;legislative veto&#148; of regulation in the 1980s?</i><p>
<p>
A:  In 1983, the Supreme Court struck down a &#147;legislative veto&#148; that
allowed one Chamber of Congress &#151; either the House or Senate &#151; to
unilaterally strike a regulation, without a presidential signature.  This
policy clearly violated the doctrine of separation of powers.  However, since
Congress delegates power to executive agencies, there is nothing to stop
Congress from restricting that delegation, or from overriding regulations by
passing laws through both Chambers and sending such proposals to the
President&#146;s desk.
</td></tr></table>
<P><BR>
<CENTER>
