<TITLE>CEI: Books by Fellows and Staff Members</TITLE>
</HEAD>

<BODY BGCOLOR="FFFFFF" TEXT="000099" LINK="006633" VLINK="000099">

<A NAME="top"></A>

<P><BR>
<H1>Books by CEI Fellows & Staff Members</H1>
</CENTER>
<BR>
<BR>

<P>

<a name="true"></a>
<a href="trustate.html"><i>The True State of the Planet</i></A><p>
edited by Ronald Bailey<p>

Ten premier scholars shatter the myths of overpopulation, food, global warming, and pesticides, while redirecting environmentalists' concerns to the far more urgent problems of fisheries, fresh water, and third-world pollution--and
the political causes behind them.<p>

To order, call The Free Press at 1-800-323-7445. (ISBN: 0-02-874010-6)<p>
<p>

<BR><HR><BR>



<a name="public"></A>
<i>Public Lands and Private Rights:  The Failure of Scientific Management</i><p>

by Robert H. Nelson<p>

"Anyone who has struggled to make sense of the history of public lands
management in the American West will want to read this book.  It assembles a
marvelous argument for the decentralization of natural resource and land
management in the West.  Along the way, Nelson also untangles the brushpile of
law, policy, executive fiat, and political pandering that have punctuated the
public lands history of the West."
			--Donald Snow, Northern Lights Institute<p>

To purchase a copy, contact Rowman &amp; Littlefield Publishers, Inc. at
1-800-462-6420.<p>

<BR><HR><BR>


<a name="politics"></a>
<i>Environmental Politics:  Public Costs, Private Rewards</i><p>

co-edited by <a href="fred.html">Fred Smith</A> and Michael Greve<p>

What really happens when environmentalist legislation is passed?  Who is hurt and who is helped?  How does our modern democratic process lead to the
systematic overthrow of good intentions in the service of narrow political
gain?  CEI's first book effort is a collection of essays whose topics range
from Superfund and ozone depletion to clean air and property rights.<p>

Spring 1992, $15.00, Mail checks to Competitive Enterprise Institute, 
1001 Connecticut Avenue, NW, Suite 1250, Washington, DC  20036, call (202) 331-1010, fax (202) 331-0640, or e-mail <A HREF="mailto:orders@cei.org">orders@CEI.org</A><BR>

<p>

<BR><HR><BR>


<a name="green"></A>
<i>Environmentalism at the Crossroads:  Green Activism in
America</i><p>

by <a href="adler.html">Jonathan H. Adler</A>

<p>An analysis and overview of environmental lobbying organizations, the policies they promote, and trends in American environmentalism, past, present and future.  Includes appendices providing background on environmental groups from Audubon to Zero Population Growth.


<P>"Environmentalism at the Crossroads" clearly documents how Washington environmental groups have become yet another special interest calling for more government in our everyday lives.  This book is a wake-up call to all those who beleive--as I once did--that environmentalists are in their corner." --<b>Ann G. Corcoran</b>,
		former lobbyist, National Audubon Society
		founding editor, Land Rights Letter

<P>	"Jonathan Adler's book makes a strong argument that the environmental movement has strayed from its roots--its early ideals and its natural allies.  The further it strays, the more it risks.  This is a message that some will not like, but it is important for all to hear and weigh." --from the preface by <b>John Stossel</b>,
		ABC "20/20" Correspondent

<P>"Jonathan Adler well articulates the choices America and the world face in protecting the environment. His book tracks the advocates for increasingly radical and coercive environmental laws that rely on bad science to produce expensive policy failures. Adler explains why successful conservation requires a market for choices by free people." --<b>Hon. Malcolm Wallop</b>, former Senator (R-WY)

<P>To obtain a copy, contact Capital Research Center at (202) 393-2600 or fax: (202) 393-2626<p>



