<HEAD>
<TITLE>CEI: Environmental Briefing Book, Introduction</TITLE>
</HEAD>

<BODY BGCOLOR="FFFFFF">

<A NAME="top"></A>
<IMG SRC="ceiebb.gif" ALT="CEI Environmental Briefing Book" ALIGN=LEFT>
<BR>
<BR>
<BR>
<BR>
<BR>

<CENTER>
<H2>Introduction</H2>
</CENTER>

<P>It is often said that everyone is an environmentalist.  To be sure, every
American supports the goals of clean air, clean water, and the conservation of
natural resources.  This does not mean, however, that everyone supports current
environmental policies.  Indeed, the past few years have seen a rapid growth in
opposition to those policies now championed by environmental lobbying
organizations in Washington, D.C.  Today&#146;s overly politicized
environmental policy decisions too often result in poorly prioritized programs
more responsive to the sensational fear stories on the morning news than to
sound science.  State and local officials are bristling at the excessive costs
and rigidity of federally-imposed programs that divert resources and strain
local budgets.  Landowners nationwide are joining together in a grass-roots
movement against perceived environmentalist attacks on private property rights.
Business executives are crying &#147;enough is enough&#148; as the costs of
compliance continue to climb with no end in sight, and greater sums of money
are hurled fruitlessly at infinitesimal risks.  There is a growing consensus
that environmental policy is broken and needs to be fixed.<p>
     The Competitive Enterprise Institute shares that view, and has spent much of
the past decade advocating a critical reappraisal of environmental policy.  As
a former staffer at the Environmental Protection Agency, I have seen first hand
how misguided many environmental policies have become, and how easily
environmental protection can become a pretext for sacrificing individual
liberties and economic development to a green regulatory hydra.  What is needed
is for all of us to take environmental issues seriously enough that we open our
eyes to new approaches and a new environmental vision.<p>
     The environmental vision that CEI advocates is one that empowers individuals
and communities, not government  bureaucrats.  CEI believes that the best
defense of environmental resources comes from property rights, competitive
markets and common law liability rules, not politically determined and enforced
regulation.  This view is commonly referred to as &#147;free-market
environmentalism.&#148;<p>
     Under this approach, private stewardship arrangements would be encouraged to
empower all Americans to protect those environmental amenities that they value
most.  Free market environmentalism relies on creative approaches to extend
private property arrangements to ecological resources now exposed to the
tragedy of the commons, would reform the institutional arrangements for
addressing environmental risk by incorporating a recognition that regulations
can create risks as easily as they alleviate them, and would recognize that
pollution is best viewed as a trespass &#151; the coercive imposition of wastes
onto another&#146;s person or property &#151; rather than emissions per se.
These principles provide a powerful framework which would better integrate
ecological and economic values &#151; seeing people as a part of nature, rather
than as alien transgressors in the Garden of Eden.<p>
     This book is designed to help candidates share in the free-market
environmental vision, and to advocate a range of policies that can reorient
environmental policy so that it complements our political and economic
freedoms, rather than restricting them.  The first section of this book is a
series of brief essays to flesh out the insights of free-market
environmentalism.  The latter section consists of brief summaries of key issues
that will be in front of Congress in the years ahead.  We have also added a
selected bibliography for those who wish to learn more about the free-market
approach to environmental issues.  The CEI environmental staff &#151; the
largest free market environmental program in the Washington area, if not the
world &#151; is also ready, willing and able to explain CEI positions and
identify the research upon which CEI&#146;s positions are based.<p>
     In the past decade free market ideas have swept the globe.  The Berlin Wall
has fallen and the virtues of the free enterprise system and the individual
liberties upon which it rests are now widely recognized.  Tragically, current
environmental policies threaten a return to the horrors of centrally-planned
societies.  CEI is working to change that.  We hope that this monograph will
encourage you to as well.<p>

<BR>
<BR>
<P><A HREF="smith.html"><i>Fred L. Smith, Jr.</i></A><BR>
President<BR>
Competitive Enterprise Institute<BR>


