<HEAD>
<TITLE>CEI: Environmental Foreign Aid</TITLE>
</HEAD>

<BODY BGCOLOR="FFFFFF">

<A NAME="top"></A>
<IMG SRC="ceiebb.gif" ALT="CEI Environmental Briefing Book" ALIGN=LEFT>
<BR>
<BR>
<BR>
<BR>
<BR>

<CENTER>
<H2>Environmental Foreign Aid</H2>
</CENTER>

<P>U.S. taxpayers currently give $1.2 billion in foreign aid for environmental
purposes.  An additional sum of taxpayer money is given to the World Bank, and
a significant portion of the Bank&#146;s $20 billion-plus loans are used for
environmental projects in developing countries.  As a rule, this money is not
well spent.  Just as foreign aid has failed to alleviate poverty and
underdevelopment in the Third World, so too will it fail to foster
environmental protection.<p>
     The Global Environment Facility (GEF), an environmental foreign aid program
run jointly by the World Bank and the United Nations, was first set up on a
trial basis in 1991.  The United States will contribute $430 million over the
next four years.  The GEF is viewed as a refund for the economic restrictions
imposed on Third World nations in the U.N. &#147;biodiversity&#148; and
&#147;climate change&#148; conventions.  While the GEF&#146;s goals may be
laudable, an internal World bank audit labelled the GEF
&#147;dysfunctional,&#148; serving only to make the Bank&#146;s own faulty loan
projects look &#147;greener&#148; and to &#147;mitigate criticism alleging
World Bank insensitivity to environmental concerns.&#148;<p>
     Not only is the GEF misspending U.S. assistance, the World Bank as a whole has
been accused of colossal environmental mismanagement and of subsidizing
wide-scale environmental destruction.  World Bank loans to a massive Narmada
Valley dam and canal project in India had to be discontinued in 1993 because of
intense local resistance.  The project called for forced resettlement of over
240,000 people.  When complete, the Narmada dam will eradicate 60,000 acres of
forests, farmland, and wildlife habitat and devastate the productive fisheries
of the Narmada river.  Similarly, the World Bank made over $1 billion in loans
to Brazil to clear rainforests for agro-industrial complexes, logging projects
and mining operations between 1975 and 1986.<p>
     The World Bank has enacted environmental &#147;reforms&#148; for itself and
the GEF.  But there is little reason to believe the &#147;greening&#148; of
foreign aid will change the Bank&#146;s bottom line.  An internal audit of
nearly two thousand loan projects found that 35 percent of all outstanding Bank
loans were &#147;unsuccessful&#148; as of 1991.  The failure rate represents
over $50 billion worth of loans.  If these loans are not repaid, much of the
financial burden will ultimately be passed on to taxpayers in the U.S., which
has guaranteed up to $36 billion of the Bank&#146;s portfolio against
default.<p>
     Both the American taxpayer and the environment have been ill-served by foreign
aid.  Rather than try to reform the aid giving process, it should simply be
eliminated, giving the American taxpayer a much-needed &#147;peace
dividend.&#148;<p>
<p>
<p>
Q: <i>Will America lose global leadership without foreign aid?</i><p>
<p>
A: Foreign aid has not been successful in promoting economic progress in the
developing world.  It has only propped up corrupt bureaucracies and accelerated
environmental degradation.  If the U.S. opens its markets to developing
countries, they will be able to export their way out of poverty, while
enriching American consumers.  Trade, not aid, is the best way America can show
foreign policy leadership.<p>
<p>
<p>
Q: <i>If America cuts back on foreign aid, won&#146;t it lose jobs to Japan in
the rapidly growing field of environmental technology exports?</i><p>
<p>
A: Jobs cannot be created by transferring wealth from American taxpayers to
foreign governments.  Even if foreign governments spent all of the aid on U.S.
products and technology, American consumers would have less money to spend in
the U.S. domestic economy.  Recipients of foreign aid subsidies may benefit,
but the U.S. cannot get rich by giving money away.  American technology and
know-how would be more competitive abroad if the federal government lowered
taxes on capital, investment, and labor.<p>
<p>
<p>
Q: <i>How can America prevent degradation of the global environment without
foreign aid programs for &#147;sustainable development?&#148;</i><p>
<p>
A: Foreign aid programs launched at the 1992 U.N. Earth Summit have required
continued U.S. taxpayer contributions to the World Bank.  Yet this type of
foreign aid has been the chief cause of environmental degradation in the first
place.  World Bank loans have been responsible for destroying rainforests in
Brazil and for subsidizing unsustainable government construction projects in
India.  The World Bank is not the vehicle for saving the planet.<p>
     America cannot preserve biological diversity by subsidizing Third World
government restrictions on land use.  Rather, Third World countries should
create a more sustainable environment by placing more land under private
ownership, giving individuals greater incentives to conserve biological and
other natural resources.<p>



<BR>
