<HEAD>
<TITLE>CEI: Federal Lands</TITLE>
</HEAD>

<BODY BGCOLOR="FFFFFF">

<A NAME="top"></A>
<IMG SRC="ceiebb.gif" ALT="CEI Environmental Briefing Book" ALIGN=LEFT>
<BR>
<BR>
<BR>
<BR>
<BR>

<CENTER>
<H2>Federal Lands</H2>
</CENTER>

<P>The federal government is the largest landowner in the United States, owning
nearly one-third of the land.  Federal ownership of land is most pervasive in
the Western United States.  The federal government owns over half of the state
of California and over 80 percent of Nevada.  In some areas, such as
California&#146;s Inyo County, the federal government owns over 90 percent of
the land.  Federal land ownership has resulted in extensive land mismanagement
and is an affront to the tradition of private property in this country.<p>
     Such expansive government control of land means that land-use decisions are
based upon political considerations, rather than on economic or environmental
grounds.  Often these decisions are made in Washington, D.C. with little
concern for the needs and concerns of local communities.  As a result, federal
lands are routinely mismanaged and a drain on the American taxpayer.  Moreover,
federal control of lands often entails the imposition of land-use controls on
neighboring communities.  This increases the costs of federal ownership of
land.<p>
     Federal land is managed by the Bureau of Land Management, the Bureau of
Reclamation, the National Park Service and the Fish and Wildlife Service in the
Department of the Interior, as well as by the Forest Service in the Department
of Agriculture, among others.  This duplication of responsibilities is
inefficient.  The problem is compounded by the fact that different land
agencies often work at cross purposes and fail to coordinate important
activities such as fire control.<p>
     Two key reforms should be implemented to ensure that the federal government is
more responsible and efficient in its management of federal lands.  These
are:<p>
<UL>
<LI><p><B>No Net Loss of Private Property</b> &#151; The federal government owns a
sufficient portion of the country as it is.  There is no need for federal
landholdings to increase.  At the same time, the federal government owns much
land that has no need to be in federal hands.  This reform would simply require
the federal government to sell an offsetting portion of land before engaging in
further land acquisition.  Thus if the federal government wished to purchase a
2,000 acre wilderness area, it could do so only if it transferred 2,000 acres
of federal land into the private sector.<p>

<LI><p><b>Self-Sufficiency for Federal Land Units </b>&#151; Many federal lands are a
drain on the treasury, and therefore a burden on the taxpayer.  This is even
true of lands where the federal government collects user fees for
timber-cutting, grazing, or recreation.  Congress should require each federal
land unit that is used for commercial or recreational purposes to become
self-sufficient.  This means that land managers would be forced either to cut
administrative costs or increase user fees for resource development and
recreation so that the individual units no longer lose money.  Such efficient
management occurs on private and state lands; it should occur on federal lands
as well.<p>

</UL>
<p>
     Ultimately, the federal government should divest itself of significant
portions of its landholdings, donating ecologically-sensitive parcels to
conservation organizations and selling much of the remainder to private
interests.  America was built upon a tradition of private property; that
tradition should be upheld.<p>
<p>
Q: <i>Federal lands are clearly mismanaged.  But isn&#146;t there mismanagement
on private lands as well?</i><p>
<i></i><p>
A: There is mismanagement on all types of land, private and federal.  However,
private lands, on the whole, tend to be managed better than public lands.  When
a private landowner mismanages land, that owner bears the cost, economic and
otherwise, as the value of the land declines.  Federal land managers, on the
other hand, bear none of the costs of land mismanagement.  Taxpayers bear this
burden. This disparate incentive structure means that private lands tend to be
managed more soundly.<p>
<p>
<p>
Q:<i> How would you propose transferring lands from the federal government to
the private sector?</i><p>
<p>
A: There is no easy answer to this question.  One possibility would be for
Congress to appoint a Commission (akin to the military base commission) to
inventory all federal lands and evaluate what uses are appropriate on which
lands.  Those lands that are primarily used for logging, ranching, or other
resource development purposes could be the first to be transferred into the
private sector.  After all, the private sector is more than capable of managing
such economic concerns.  The Commission also could identify which lands, if
any, must remain under federal control because of environmental sensitivity or
other compelling concerns.  This process could also be used to consolidate the
numerous federal land agencies to increase the efficiency of land management
and prevent federal land agencies from working at cross-purposes.<p>
<p>
<p>
Q:<i> Would divesting the federal government of land ownership eliminate
outdoor recreational opportunities for Americans?</i><p>
<p>
A: Not necessarily.  There are many private lands that are managed for
recreation in conjunction with other uses.  For example, IP Timberlands in the
southeastern United States manages many of its lands for both timber production
and recreation.  Because trees are only cut every few decades, IP Timberlands
is able to encourage the use of its land for hiking, camping, hunting and bird
watching in the interim.  This not only means that IP Timberlands makes a
greater profit from its land, it means that the land is managed in a more
ecologically sound manner as well.<p>



<BR>
