␀␀␀␀␀␀␀␀␀␀␀␀␀␀␀␀␀␀␀␀␀␀␀␀␀␀␀␀␀␀␀␀␀␀␀␀␀␀␀␀␀␀␀␀␀␀␀␀␀␀␀␀␀␀␀␀␀␀␀␀␀␀␀␀␀␀␀␀␀␀␀␀␀␀␀␀␀␀␀␀␀␀␀␀␀␀␀␀␀␀␀␀␀␀␀␀␀␀␀␀␀␀␀␀␀␀␀␀␀␀␀␀␀␀␀␀␀␀␀␀␀␀␀␀␀␀␀␀␀␀␀␀␀␀␀␀␀␀␀␀␀␀␀␀␀␀␀␀␀␀␀␀␀␀␀␀␀␀␀␀␀␀␀␀␀␀␀␀␀␀␀␀␀␀␀␀␀␀␀␀␀␀␀␀␀␀␀␀␀␀␀␀␀␀␀␀␀␀␀␀␀␀␀␀␀␀␀␀␀␀␀␀␀␀␀␀␀␀␀␀␀␀␀␀␀␀␀␀␀␀␀␀␀␀␀␀␀␀␀␀␀␀␀␀␀␀␀␀␀␀␀␀␀␀␀␀␀␀␀␀␀␀␀␀␀␀␀␀␀␀␀␀␀␀␀␀␀␀␀␀␀␀␀␀␀␀␀␀␀␀␀␀␀␀␀␀␀␀␀␀␀␀␀␀␀␀␀␀␀␀␀␀␀␀␀␀␀␀␀␀␀␀␀␀␀␀␀␀␀␀␀␀␀␀␀␀␀␀␀␀␀␀␀␀␀␀␀␀␀␀␀␀␀␀␀␀␀␀␀␀␀␀␀␀␀␀␀␀␀␀␀␀␀␀␀␀␀␀␀␀␀␀␀␀␀␀␀␀␀␀␀␀␀␀␀␀␀␀␀␀␀␀␀␀␀␀␀␀␀␀␀␀␀␀␀␀␀␀␀␀␀␀␀␀␀␀␀␀␀␀␀␀␀␀␀␀␀␀␀␀␀␀␀␀␀␀␀␀␀␀␀ebb12.html␀␀␀␀␀␀␀␀␀␀␀␀␀␀␀␀␀␀␀␀␀␀␀␀␀␀␀␀␀␀␀␀␀␀␀␀␀␀␀␀␀␀␀␀␀␀␀␀␀␀␀␀␀␀␀␀␀␀␀␀␀␀␀␀␀␀␀␀␀␀␀␀␀␀␀␀␀␀␀␀␀␀␀␀␀␀␀␀␀␀100644 ␀  1647 ␀   144 ␀      15447  6061645641  11067␀ 0␀␀␀␀␀␀␀␀␀␀␀␀␀␀␀␀␀␀␀␀␀␀␀␀␀␀␀␀␀␀␀␀␀␀␀␀␀␀␀␀␀␀␀␀␀␀␀␀␀␀␀␀␀␀␀␀␀␀␀␀␀␀␀␀␀␀␀␀␀␀␀␀␀␀␀␀␀␀␀␀␀␀␀␀␀␀␀␀␀␀␀␀␀␀␀␀␀␀␀␀ustar  ␀cei␀␀␀␀␀␀␀␀␀␀␀␀␀␀␀␀␀␀␀␀␀␀␀␀␀␀␀␀␀users␀␀␀␀␀␀␀␀␀␀␀␀␀␀␀␀␀␀␀␀␀␀␀␀␀␀␀␀␀␀␀␀␀␀␀␀␀␀␀␀␀␀␀␀␀␀␀␀␀␀␀␀␀␀␀␀␀␀␀␀␀␀␀␀␀␀␀␀␀␀␀␀␀␀␀␀␀␀␀␀␀␀␀␀␀␀␀␀␀␀␀␀␀␀␀␀␀␀␀␀␀␀␀␀␀␀␀␀␀␀␀␀␀␀␀␀␀␀␀␀␀␀␀␀␀␀␀␀␀␀␀␀␀␀␀␀␀␀␀␀␀␀␀␀␀␀␀␀␀␀␀␀␀␀␀␀␀␀␀␀␀␀␀␀␀␀␀␀␀␀␀␀␀␀␀␀␀␀␀␀␀␀␀␀␀␀␀␀␀␀␀␀␀␀␀␀␀␀␀␀␀␀␀␀␀␀␀␀␀␀<HTML>
<HEAD>
<TITLE>CEI: Global Climate Change</TITLE>
</HEAD>

<BODY BGCOLOR="FFFFFF">

<A NAME="top"></A>
<IMG SRC="ceiebb.gif" ALT="CEI Environmental Briefing Book" ALIGN=LEFT>
<BR>
<BR>
<BR>
<BR>
<BR>

<CENTER>
<H2>Global Climate Change</H2>
</CENTER>

<P>There is no compelling reason for the United States to take drastic actions to
reduce emissions of carbon dioxide and other &#147;greenhouse gases.&#148;
There is little evidence that human activity is having more than a marginal
impact on the Earth&#146;s climate and even less that moderate climate shifts
will be disastrous for either human civilization or the environment.<p>
     There is widespread disagreement within the scientific community on both the
nature of global climate change, and the impact it would have on the human
environment.  Recent polls by the Gallup organization and the environmentalist
group Greenpeace demonstrate that there is no scientific consensus to support
the proposition that human activity will produce an apocalyptic warming of the
Earth&#146;s atmosphere.  The primary basis for predictions of human-induced
global warming is a series of complex computer models that have difficulty
predicting present conditions, let alone future possibilities.  As these models
are refined and become more accurate, the direness of their predictions
recedes.<p>
     Moreover, the earth&#146;s climate is in constant flux, and human-induced
changes cannot be presumed necessarily bad.  A warming that occurs
predominately at higher latitudes and at night, as some suggest is the most
probable scenario, would hardly make for an environmental disaster.  Indeed,
some scientists even suggest that it might be, on net, beneficial.  Growing
seasons would be lengthened, and most people would experience a more benign
climate.  Furthermore, there is substantial evidence that increased levels of
atmospheric carbon dioxide would spur terrific advances in plant growth and
agricultural productivity.  In other words, the likeliest global climate change
is the creation of a milder, greener, more prosperous world.<p>
     Global climate science is fraught with uncertainty.  There is no clear
evidence that human activity will drive temperatures significantly upward, and
none that human-induced changes will have on balance a negative impact.  As the
late Roger Revelle, vice President Al Gore&#146;s mentor on global climate
change, wrote shortly before his death, &#147;<i>the scientific evidence for
greenhouse warming is too uncertain to justify drastic action at this
time</i>&#148; (emphasis in original).<p>
     However it is clear that enacting wide-scale policies to forcibly reduce
emissions of carbon dioxide (CO2) and other greenhouse gases would impose
tremendous costs on the American people.  Policies to increase the price of
energy would have a regressive impact and stifle economic productivity.
Emission reduction mandates will cost tens of billions of dollars and produce
no certain benefits.  Looking carefully at the issue, it seems that the risks
of global warming are outweighed by the risks of global warming policy.<p>
     The United States should not embark on a series of costly and ill-conceived
policies seeking to avert an unlikely catastrophe.  Prudence requires that the
U.S. enact only those policies to address global climate change which are
valuable in their own right &#151; such as eliminating subsidies that promote
the excess use of fossil fuels and encouraging increased efficiency in energy
production through the introduction of competition in the electric utility
industry.  Steps beyond these simply cannot be justified given current
knowledge of potential climate change.<p>
<p>
<p>
Q: <i>The Earth&#146;s average temperature has risen in the past 100 years as
emissions of greenhouse gases have increased.  Isn&#146;t this evidence of
global warming?</i><p>
<i></i><p>
A: The Earth has gotten warmer in this century.  But most of the warming
occurred in the first half of this century, prior to World War II.  This was
before the dramatic increase in greenhouse gases occurred.  The increase in
greenhouse gases has occurred primarily in the past few decades.  Thus, most of
the warming in the past 100 years is more likely the result of natural climate
fluctuations than of human activity.<p>
<p>
<p>
Q: <i>Whether the Earth will warm and how warm it will get are still matters of
speculation, but human-induced global warming is a real possibility.  Should
not we take precautionary measures, just in case?</i><p>
<p>
A: Precautionary measures are sometimes a prudent course of action.  Yet, the
simple fact is that coerced reductions in energy use will not come without
costs, both in terms of economic growth and in terms of social dislocation.  As
Dr. Richard Stroup of Montana State University points out, &#147;If
&#145;insurance&#146; against a particular risk, such as the threat of global
warming, is bought at the cost of reduced economic growth, then a decline in
the automatic insurance represented by wealth, and the social resilience it
provides, is one of the costs borne by future generations.&#148;  In other
words, inexpensive precautionary measures &#151; such as those that can be
justified in their own right &#151; may make sense.  Expensive precautionary
measures, on the other hand, may cause more harm than they prevent.<p>
     People do not emit greenhouse gas emissions capriciously.  These emissions are
the by-products of a wide range of activities that benefit everybody, from the
production of goods and services, the transportation of food and medicines, and
the generation of wealth throughout society.  Dramatically reducing greenhouse
gas emissions would mean giving all of this up for uncertain benefits.  That is
not a prudent policy.<p>
<p>
<p>
Q: <i>Why should we take the risk that human activity is warming the
planet?</i><p>
<p>
A: The Earth&#146;s climate is in constant flux.  Temperatures vary from year
to year, decade to decade, thus it is difficult to say that one climate
condition is preferable to another.  Greenhouse gas emissions may cause the
Earth to warm slightly, but that warming is most likely to occur at winter and
at night.  Moreover, warming would produce benefits, as well as costs.  An
increase in the Earth&#146;s food-growing capacity might well offset a marginal
increase in wintertime low temperatures.<p>
     For the time being it makes more sense to continue to study the potential of
global warming and what it might mean for human society.  Should scientific
research confirm the need for action, there will be time to implement the
proper policies.<p>



<BR>
