<HEAD>
<TITLE>CEI: Interstate Transport of Waste</TITLE>
</HEAD>

<BODY BGCOLOR="FFFFFF">

<A NAME="top"></A>
<IMG SRC="ceiebb.gif" ALT="CEI Environmental Briefing Book" ALIGN=LEFT>
<BR>
<BR>
<BR>
<BR>
<BR>

<CENTER>
<H2>Interstate Transport of Waste</H2>
</CENTER>

<P>The United States Constitution explicitly forbids state and local governments
from interfering  with interstate commerce.  In environmentally-related cases,
the Supreme Court has consistently held that &#147;a State may not accord its
own inhabitants a preferred right of access over consumers in other States to
natural resources located within its borders.&#148;  This is also true of waste
disposal services.  Congress should respect the intent of the framers of the
Constitution and the Supreme Court and not enact laws permitting state and
local interference with the interstate transportation of waste.<p>
     States that seek to limit the interstate transportation of waste argue that
some states should not be the dumping grounds for others.  In effect, they
argue that all states should be self-sufficient with regard to waste disposal
services.  This makes no more sense than arguing that all states should be
self-sufficient with regard to food production, energy generation, or mineral
supplies.  Different regions have a comparative advantage in the provision of
certain goods and services.  Unrestricted commerce throughout the nation
promotes the public interest by allowing specialization to increase efficiency,
lower prices and spur innovation.  This is as true in the field of waste
disposal as it is in any other.<p>
     Trade between states occurs for the same reason as trade between countries.
Trade occurs between parties that seek mutual advantage.  Trade encourages
specialization and greater productivity.  The ability of waste disposal
companies to attract business from other states increases the incentive to
develop the most efficient and environmentally-sound waste disposal processes.
Limiting the interstate transportation of waste eliminates these incentives,
and can actually have a negative impact on the environment.<p>
     While some states try to ban waste imports, some municipalities attempt to
restrict waste <i>exports</i> through so-called flow control ordinances.  These
local ordinances require local businesses to process and/or dispose of waste at
a predetermined facility.  This prevents companies that generate waste from
seeking the most efficient means of disposing of that waste.  The Supreme Court
has properly ruled that flow control ordinances are unconstitutional violations
of the interstate commerce clause.  Such ordinances are also unreasonable
infringements upon the right to contract.  They discriminate against
out-of-state companies, increasing waste disposal prices at the expense of the
consumer and the environment.<p>
     It is one thing for governments to impose health and safety regulations that
affect the transportation of waste.  It is quite another for governments to
limit the transportation of waste, as several states have tried to do.
Congress should refrain from authorizing any state or local infringements upon
interstate commerce in solid waste and waste disposal services.<p>
<p>
<p>
Q: <i>Which states are most involved in shipping waste elsewhere and why?</i><p>
<i></i><p>
A: The simple fact is that most states and the District of Columbia <i>both</i>
import and export solid waste.  In 1992, for example, 47 states exported waste
and 42 states imported waste from other parts of the country.  Interstate trade
in waste occurs because communities and waste disposal companies are always
looking for the least expensive and most efficient means of handling trash.
Sometimes this means using a local incinerator or recycling facility, in other
cases it means hauling the waste to a landfill, perhaps one across state
lines.<p>
<p>
<p>
Q: <i>Why should some states be the dumping grounds for the rest of the
country?</i><p>
<i></i><p>
A: Each region of the country has particular features &#151; geography,
population density, natural resource deposits, access to water, etc. &#151;
that make it particularly suited for the provision of particular goods and
services.  Just as some parts of the country are more suited for coal  mining
or orange growing than others, some parts of the country have a comparative
advantage in the provision of waste disposal services.  Some communities reap
significant economic benefits by providing waste disposal services for other
parts of the country.  Indeed, these communities see importing waste as an
opportunity, not a burden.<p>
<p>
<p>
Q:<i> Don&#146;t local flow control laws enable municipalities to manage solid
waste in a more environmentally-sound manner?</i><p>
<p>
A: The experience of most communities with flow control laws is that such rules
are used to prop up inefficient facilities at the expense of consumers
<i>and</i> environmental improvements.  By mandating that local waste haulers
use particular management facilities, they are prevented from using less
expensive or more environmentally-sound alternatives that may exist elsewhere.
The Sierra Club, for one, has pointed out that these regulations often inhibit
the development of recycling facilities and other waste management alternatives
in the marketplace.  It is actually likely that flow control laws do far more
environmental harm than good.<p>





<BR>
