<HEAD>
<TITLE>CEI: Risk Assessment</TITLE>
</HEAD>

<BODY BGCOLOR="FFFFFF">

<A NAME="top"></A>
<IMG SRC="ceiebb.gif" ALT="CEI Environmental Briefing Book" ALIGN=LEFT>
<BR>
<BR>
<BR>
<BR>
<BR>

<CENTER>
<H2>Risk Assessment</H2>
</CENTER>

<P>Regulators are supposed to make our lives safer by eliminating or reducing our
exposure to certain risky substances and products, such as toxic chemicals,
dangerous food additives, or cars without airbags.  The problem is that the
current federal regulatory process often focuses on minute risks while ignoring
far greater threats to public health and safety.  This approach not only wastes
public and private resources, it diverts attention away from those things about
which people should be most concerned.<p>
     In the last fifteen years, regulatory policy has too often evolved in reaction
to popular panic to sensational fear stories in the media, not in response to
sound science.  As a result billions of dollars are wasted every year in
battling problems that are not considered dangerous, leaving no money for
others that cause far more harm.  The government needs to do a better job of
quantifying risks and focusing on those risks which require government action,
as opposed to those which do not.<p>
     Consider the example of a hazardous waste site in New Hampshire that was to be
cleaned up under federal law.  After much expense, the site was clean by any
reasonable standard.  The Environmental Protection Agency, however, was
unsatisfied and demanded that the company spend an additional $9.3 million to
make the soil on the site clean enough for children to eat small amounts of
dirt for 245 days of the year.  This might be justifiable if the site was
destined to become a kindergarten playground.  The site in question, however,
was located in the middle of a swamp.  The dirt-eating children were
nonexistent.  Yet federal regulations required that $9.3 million be spent on
clean up, even though it would not reduce risks to human health whatsoever.
The $9.3 million could have been spent to address other, more important
concerns.<p>
     Congress should pass legislation to reform the federal government&#146;s
efforts at risk assessment and prioritization.  Those reforms should include:<p>
<UL>
<LI><p>An open, transparent process for risk assessments to ensure credibility and
identify critical science issues and uncertainties;<p>

<LI><p>The requirement of a scientific &#147;best estimate&#148; of risks with which
other estimates can be compared;<p>

<LI><p>Publicly available information concerning the population at risk, exposure
scenarios, and known substitution risks;<p>

<LI><p>Meaningful comparisons to other risks to provide an overall perspective;<p>

<LI><p>
A process to review current regulations in light of new scientific
information;<p>

<LI><p>Required analysis of the potential negative impact of proposed risk
regulations on human health and safety;<p>
<p>

<LI><p>Creation of &#147;ombudsman&#148; offices within regulatory agencies with the
purpose of questioning regulatory assumptions and highlighting the costs of
regulatory actions that seek to minimize risks to human health and the
environment.<p>

</UL>
<p>
There are many risks to human health and safety.  Without more accurate risk
assessment and prioritization, taxpayer dollars will continue to be squandered
on questionable programs that do little, if anything, to promote public health,
safety, and environmental protection.<p>
<p>
<p>
<p>
<p>
Q: <i> Shouldn&#146;t the government be protecting us from all unreasonable
risks?</i><p>
<p>
A:  In a world of unlimited abundance and perfect information, the government
might be able to do that.  But society and the government have limited
resources and different people have different risk-reduction priorities.  The
best course of action for the government is to identify the worst risks so that
people can focus their limited resources on those.  In a utopian world, there
would be no risks; there would also be no crime, no hunger, no wars, and so on.
In the real world, risks are always present.  Risk cannot be eliminated, it can
only be managed. The goal is a &#147;safer&#148; world, not a &#147;safe&#148;
world. More effective management of risks is better served by the promulgation
of more accurate information on risks than it is by proscriptive government
regulations.<p>
<p>
<p>
Q:  <i>Risk assessment sounds like putting a price on life.  How can you put an
price on life?</i><p>
<i></i><p>
A:  Benjamin Franklin once said, &#147;In this world nothing can be said to be
certain, except death and taxes.&#148;  Risk assessment doesn&#146;t put a
price on life.  But it does try to focus the government&#146;s resources in
order to make death a little less certain and taxes a little less burdensome.
If the government is going to spend over $100 billion on addressing
environmental risks,  it is important to know how best to spend that money to
make everybody&#146;s lives healthier and safer.<p>
<p>
<p>
Q:<i> Do government agencies tend to exaggerate risks?</i><p>
<p>
A: Yes.  Government agencies often exaggerate the risks they are entrusted to
regulate.  That is because government agencies have to demonstrate they are
needed to continue to receive taxpayer funds.  This does not mean agencies
always exaggerate the nature of risks; it does mean, however, that agencies
often have a strong incentive to do just that.<p>
<p>
<p>
Q: <i>Are there alternatives to federal risk regulation?</i><p>
<p>
A: Certainly.  Many risks that the federal government focuses on do not require
government attention at all.  This is not because these risks do not exist, but
because different individuals and communities are willing to accept different
trade-offs between  environmental risk reduction and other risk reduction or
life-enhancing measures.  These decisions should be left in the hands of the
affected individuals and communities as much as is possible, just as people are
allowed to take risks voluntarily, from riding motorcycles to hangliding, when
they choose.  Where government involvement is unavoidable, regulation should be
undertaken based upon the best available information and the regulated risks
should be placed within their proper context.<p>
<p>




<BR>
