</HTML>
␀␀␀␀␀␀␀␀␀␀␀␀␀␀␀␀␀␀␀␀␀␀␀␀␀␀␀␀␀␀␀␀␀␀␀␀␀␀␀␀␀␀␀␀␀␀␀␀␀␀␀␀␀␀␀␀␀␀␀␀␀␀␀␀␀␀␀␀␀␀␀ebb18.html␀␀␀␀␀␀␀␀␀␀␀␀␀␀␀␀␀␀␀␀␀␀␀␀␀␀␀␀␀␀␀␀␀␀␀␀␀␀␀␀␀␀␀␀␀␀␀␀␀␀␀␀␀␀␀␀␀␀␀␀␀␀␀␀␀␀␀␀␀␀␀␀␀␀␀␀␀␀␀␀␀␀␀␀␀␀␀␀␀␀100644 ␀  1647 ␀   144 ␀      11674  6061645725  11076␀ 0␀␀␀␀␀␀␀␀␀␀␀␀␀␀␀␀␀␀␀␀␀␀␀␀␀␀␀␀␀␀␀␀␀␀␀␀␀␀␀␀␀␀␀␀␀␀␀␀␀␀␀␀␀␀␀␀␀␀␀␀␀␀␀␀␀␀␀␀␀␀␀␀␀␀␀␀␀␀␀␀␀␀␀␀␀␀␀␀␀␀␀␀␀␀␀␀␀␀␀␀ustar  ␀cei␀␀␀␀␀␀␀␀␀␀␀␀␀␀␀␀␀␀␀␀␀␀␀␀␀␀␀␀␀users␀␀␀␀␀␀␀␀␀␀␀␀␀␀␀␀␀␀␀␀␀␀␀␀␀␀␀␀␀␀␀␀␀␀␀␀␀␀␀␀␀␀␀␀␀␀␀␀␀␀␀␀␀␀␀␀␀␀␀␀␀␀␀␀␀␀␀␀␀␀␀␀␀␀␀␀␀␀␀␀␀␀␀␀␀␀␀␀␀␀␀␀␀␀␀␀␀␀␀␀␀␀␀␀␀␀␀␀␀␀␀␀␀␀␀␀␀␀␀␀␀␀␀␀␀␀␀␀␀␀␀␀␀␀␀␀␀␀␀␀␀␀␀␀␀␀␀␀␀␀␀␀␀␀␀␀␀␀␀␀␀␀␀␀␀␀␀␀␀␀␀␀␀␀␀␀␀␀␀␀␀␀␀␀␀␀␀␀␀␀␀␀␀␀␀␀␀␀␀␀␀␀␀␀␀␀␀␀␀␀<HTML>
<HEAD>
<TITLE>CEI: Safe Drinking Water Act (SDWA)</TITLE>
</HEAD>

<BODY BGCOLOR="FFFFFF">

<A NAME="top"></A>
<IMG SRC="ceiebb.gif" ALT="CEI Environmental Briefing Book" ALIGN=LEFT>
<BR>
<BR>
<BR>
<BR>
<BR>

<CENTER>
<H2>Safe Drinking Water Act (SDWA)</H2>
</CENTER>

<P>Today&#146;s drinking water systems are capable of efficiently delivering 40
million gallons of safe water to American homes everyday.  All in all, they
work quite well.  Nonetheless the Safe Drinking Water Act (SDWA) is in need of
reform.  The current law is too rigid and fails to prioritize risks.<p>
     The SDWA currently requires the federal Environmental Protection Agency (EPA)
establish drinking water standards for 83 specific contaminants.  Additionally,
the SDWA requires the EPA to pick an additional 25 contaminants every three
years to regulate.  This mandate applies irrespective of whether there are
additional, identifiable contaminants that pose a human health risk in
America&#146;s water supply.  According to the EPA, the total cost for
implementing the new standards is $1.4 billion a year, nearly all of which is
paid for by local governments.<p>
     This combination of extreme rigidity and high cost results in wasteful
regulation.    For example, the city of Columbus, Ohio, spends thousands of
dollars a year to test its drinking water for 43 pesticides it knows it
won&#146;t find.  One of those pesticides (EBDB) has been banned for all
commercial uses except one, growing pineapples.  Needless to say, pineapples
are not grown in Ohio.  Indeed, most of the pesticides for which the state of
Ohio must test have never been found in Ohio waters.<p>
     The SDWA is premised on the idea that EPA bureaucrats, from thousands of miles
away, are better able than local public health officials to determine the
public health needs of a local community.  EPA officials are necessarily
unfamiliar with the problems of most local communities.  Therefore, this
assumption is questionable, at best.<p>
     To improve the SDWA, a reform package should include the following:<p>
<p>
<UL>

<LI><p>Scientifically accurate assessments of the risks posed by drinking water
contaminants, independently and in relation to other health risks.<p>

<LI><p>
Funding for the compliance of mandatory regulatory standards.  If the federal
government sets stringent new standards which will be expensive to implement,
it should either supply funds for compliance with the standard or make it
voluntary.<p>

<LI><p>
Greater flexibility for local water agencies to set standards based on local
needs.<p>

</UL>
<p>
In the long run, the federal government should return authority for safe
drinking water programs back to the local level.  Safe drinking water is
primarily a local concern and local authorities are up to the task of
protecting their communities from water-borne contaminants.  There is little,
if any, compelling need for continued federal intervention in this area.<p>
<p>
<p>
<p>
Q: <i> In Milwaukee in 1993, more than one hundred thousand people became sick
after a parasite infected the water supply.  Shouldn&#146;t the Safe Drinking
Water Act be strengthened to keep what happened in Milwaukee from happening
elsewhere?</i><p>
<p>
A:  No, the Safe Drinking Water Act is part of the problem.  By requiring
municipalities to test, monitor and treat for so many chemicals (most of which
do not even occur in their local water supplies), the Safe Drinking Water Act
diverts attention and resources away from the most important problems.  Local
water agencies have limited budgets.  When the EPA forces them to test, monitor
and treat for obscure contaminants, it spreads the agencies&#146; resources
even thinner, increasing the likelihood that a mistake will occur.  The
parasite that infected Milwaukee is called Cryptosporidium.  The EPA had been
so busy writing regulations for obscure contaminants that it had not even
developed an approved method to test for the parasite until  thousands became
ill in Milwaukee.<p>
<p>
<p>
Q:  <i>An environmental group recently reported that one out of five Americans
drank water that was inadequately treated for pollutants.  Shouldn&#146;t the
Safe Drinking Water Act be strengthened to ensure that everyone&#146;s water is
adequately treated?</i><p>
<i></i><p>
A:  The current Safe Drinking Water Act is part of the problem, regulating more
stringently or writing more regulations will only exacerbate the problem.
Inadequate treatment occurs most frequently when a water agency&#146;s budget
is stretched to the limit.  Forcing municipalities, especially small
municipalities, to test, monitor and treat so many different substances without
providing additional funds, creates more problems than it solves.<p>
<p>





<BR>
