<HEAD>
<TITLE>CEI: Secondhand Smoke</TITLE>
</HEAD>

<BODY BGCOLOR="FFFFFF">

<A NAME="top"></A>
<IMG SRC="ceiebb.gif" ALT="CEI Environmental Briefing Book" ALIGN=LEFT>
<BR>
<BR>
<BR>
<BR>
<BR>

<CENTER>
<H2>Secondhand Smoke</H2>
</CENTER>


<P>Fueled by public health hysteria, numerous measures have been introduced by
federal, state, and local governments to ban smoking in restaurants and
workplaces.  These pressures should be vigorously resisted.  Scientific
evidence does not support the claim that secondhand smoke is a health threat to
non-smokers.  More importantly, workplaces and restaurants are private spaces,
entered voluntarily by individuals.  Government agencies should not ban smoking
in such places under the guise of protecting public health or anything else.<p>
     Some individuals undeniably dislike being in smoke-filled restaurants and
other public places.  Others like to smoke.  The proper way to handle this
contentious issue is to allow independent establishments to determine their own
smoking rules.  Consumers will then vote with their wallets, frequenting those
establishments that cater to their preferences with regard to the amount of
smoke, as they do with food preparation, quality of service, ambience, and so
on.  If some people object to eating in a smoke-filled restaurant, they are
free to eat somewhere else.  Restaurant owners should be equally free in their
choice whether or not to accommodate smokers, non-smokers, or both.  The same
should be true of all privately owned establishments.<p>
     The impetus behind the movement to ban smoking is an Environmental Protection
Agency study. This study examined other studies to discern a statistical
relationship between secondhand smoke exposure and lung cancer. Almost all of
the studies EPA looked at found no relationship between the two.  Unsatisfied
with the results of these statistical analyses, the EPA engaged in what
<i>Science</i> magazine termed &#147;fancy statistical footwork,&#148;
violating scientific standards by modifying the results of the studies and
flouting conventional statistical methods.  While smoking is itself an
undeniable health risk, the case against secondhand smoke rests on incredibly
shaky ground.  If secondhand smoke is as dangerous as the EPA claims, there was
no need to ignore conventional scientific methodologies.<p>
     Some people undeniably object to secondhand smoke.  However, there are no
grounds for the federal government to legislate how private establishments
address this concern.  It would be one thing for the federal government to
impose standards on federal properties, another for it to reach into every
small business, or even every home, and dictate smoking restrictions to each
and every American.<p>
<p>
<p>
Q: <i>Why would the EPA manipulate science, and make false claims about the
carcinogenicity of substances?</i><p>
<p>
A: The EPA has a strong incentive to label substances carcinogenic. With every
new environmental problem it &#147;discovers,&#148; the agency expands its
budget, influence, and prestige. The agency is in need of oversight and
restraint.<p>
<p>
<p>
Q: <i>Shouldn&#146;t the EPA err on the side of caution? After all, it&#146;s
their job to protect us from environmental hazards.</i><p>
<p>
A: The EPA&#146;s proper function  is to provide accurate data about the risks
we encounter in day-to-day living,  not to protect us from such risks. That
should be the choice of the individual. If, for example, I&#146;m willing to
risk my health by eating in a restaurant that allows smoking, I should have
that option; if not, I should have the right to pick a nonsmoking restaurant.
Government controls remove the option entirely, and the manipulation of science
by the EPA can expand the scope of control.<p>




<BR>
