<HEAD>
<TITLE>CEI: Automobility Fuel Economy Standards</TITLE>
</HEAD>

<BODY BGCOLOR="FFFFFF">

<A NAME="top"></A>
<IMG SRC="ceiebb.gif" ALT="CEI Environmental Briefing Book" ALIGN=LEFT>
<BR>
<BR>
<BR>
<BR>
<BR>

<CENTER>
<H2>Automobility Fuel Economy Standards</H2>
</CENTER>


<P>The federal new car fuel economy program imposes a deadly trade-off of blood
for oil.  Popularly known as CAFE (for Corporate Average Fuel Economy), this
program requires that new cars sold in the U.S. by any carmaker meet, on
average, a specified yearly fuel economy standard.  The current CAFE standard
for passenger cars is 27.5 miles per gallon. Environmental lobbyists are
proposing to raise CAFE to 40 mpg or higher.  If anything, CAFE standards
should be lowered or, better yet, repealed.<p>
     CAFE has a lethal effect on auto safety.  Decades of research have made it
clear that large cars are more crashworthy than similarly equipped small cars
in all collision modes.  CAFE, however, restricts large-car availability.
According to a peer-reviewed Harvard-Brookings study, CAFE is responsible for a
500 pound downsizing of new cars, which translates into 2,200 to 3,900
additional traffic deaths per model year.<p>
     CAFE&#146;s proponents argue that the law is necessary to reduce gasoline
consumption.  But while the need for &#147;fuel efficiency&#148; is highly
touted, its underlying premises are questionable.  Oil is a resource whose use
benefits people.  When fuel-efficiency improvements pay for themselves, there
is no need for government intervention to promote them;
government-<i>mandated</i> fuel efficiency, on the other hand, is an entirely
different animal, as it restricts consumer choice and produces unwelcome
side-effects.<p>
     As for national security and foreign oil, America&#146;s use of foreign oil
depends not on fuel efficiency, but on international oil prices.  When oil
prices drop, our relative use of foreign oil increases, since domestic oil
fields are relatively high-cost producers.  We may well be better off relying
on foreign oil to supply our current needs while leaving our domestic reserves
unused until they are needed.  <p>
     Finally, the correlation between fuel economy and vehicle emissions is far
less direct than it appears to be.  Nitrogen oxide (NOx) emissions, for
example, may actually <i>increase</i> when fuel efficiency rises.<p>
     Even if one accepts the need to reduce gasoline use, CAFE is an incredibly
costly means of accomplishing this.  By focusing on car design rather than car
use, it imposes its costs without regard to actual gasoline consumption.
Because CAFE standards impose a sales mandate, auto manufacturers are forced to
manipulate their prices to sell vehicles that meet the prescribed standards.
As a result, large-car buyers pay heavy CAFE premiums when buying their cars
even if they drive very little, while small-car buyers pay artificially-lowered
car prices regardless of how much they drive.  Moreover, CAFE may actually
increase consumption by reducing  fuel use and thus the cost of driving.
Because of its structure, CAFE penalizes full-line domestic carmakers such as
Ford and GM, to the advantage of foreign car makers.<p>
     In 1992, a federal appeals court ruled that the federal government relied
upon &#147;fudged analysis,&#148; &#147;statistical legerdemain,&#148; and
&#147;bureaucratic mumbo-jumbo&#148; in enacting current CAFE standards and
ignoring their impact on highway fatalities.  CAFE kills, even at current
levels.  If raised, the deadly impact of this law will only increase. <p>
<p>
Q:<i> Isn&#146;t CAFE necessary to increase fuel efficiency</i>?<p>
<p>
A: No.  When fuel efficiency increases were needed, the market has responded
far more quickly than the law.  In the late 1970s to early 1980s, for example,
the fear of rising gasoline prices produced increases in new-car fuel economy
that <i>exceeded</i> CAFE&#146;s requirements.  Should gasoline prices rise
again, there is no reason not to expect the market to respond in the same
fashion.<p>
<p>
<p>
Q: <i>How can CAFE be blamed for highway fatalities when the vehicle death rate
has improved since CAFE&#146;s enactment.</i><p>
<p>
A: The vehicle death rate has been declining not just since CAFE&#146;s
enactment, but for at least the last fifty years.  This has been the result of
improvements in vehicle safety, road design and, more recently, in enforcement
of drunk driving laws.  The death rate would have improved even more in the
absence of CAFE.  America&#146;s highways have been getting safer, but without
CAFE they would be safer still.  The long-term trend in this rate cannot be
used to exonerate CAFE.  <p>
<p>
<p>
Q:<i> If CAFE really is so deadly, why do safety groups such as the Center for
Auto Safety favor </i>increasing<i> the standard?</i><p>
<p>
A: In the case of CAFE, some so-called public interest groups have apparently
chosen to favor more government rather than more safety.  It is noteworthy that
the auto insurance industry, which has a financial stake in vehicle
crashworthiness and which in the past has generally sided with &#147;public
interest&#148; groups on expanding vehicle safety regulation, has opposed them
on the issue of raising CAFE.<p>


<BR>
