<HEAD>
<TITLE>CEI: Superfund</TITLE>
</HEAD>

<BODY BGCOLOR="FFFFFF">

<A NAME="top"></A>
<IMG SRC="ceiebb.gif" ALT="CEI Environmental Briefing Book" ALIGN=LEFT>
<BR>
<BR>
<BR>
<BR>
<BR>

<CENTER>
<H2>Superfund</H2>
</CENTER>


<P>The federal Superfund program to cleanup hazardous waste sites is an utter
failure.  &#147;It is hard to think of a government program with a wider gulf
between ambitions and results,&#148; according to the <i>New York Times</i>.
The existing program should either be radically reformed or replaced with an
entirely different approach.<p>
     Created in 1980 by the Comprehensive Environmental Response, Compensation, and
Liability Act of 1980, Superfund has cleaned up fewer than 20 percent of the
over 1,200 hazardous waste sites in the program.  Those sites that are cleaned,
are cleaned at a cost of over $25 million per site, with a large percentage of
these costs going to pay lawyers and file paperwork.  Originally touted as a
&#147;polluter pays&#148; policy, under Superfund, polluter and non-polluter
alike overpay.<p>
     One of the greatest problems with Superfund is that millions of dollars are
spent on cleanups which produce no environmental or public health benefits.
Current Superfund risk assessments greatly overstate potential risks to human
health.  Less stringent cleanup standards could achieve the same real-world
risk reduction at lower cost.  At some sites, containment of wastes is
preferable to attempting a costly cleanup.  Moreover, many communities with
Superfund sites would benefit more from the diversion of resources away from
Superfund toward more pressing and directly beneficial expenditures.<p>
     Another problem is the set of liability standards that Superfund has created.
Under Superfund, liability for the costs of cleanup is strict, retroactive, and
joint-and-several.  This means that even those who had a tangential
relationship to a Superfund site can be held completely liable for the costs of
cleanup.  For example, private waste hauling firms and previous owners of
materials that end up at a Superfund site have been held liable for
multi-million dollar cleanup bills at Superfund sites.<p>
     Tinkering with Superfund and reallocating costs at the margins will not rescue
this failed program.  Real Superfund reform should include the following
elements:<p>
<UL>

<LI><p>
More accurate assessments of the risks posed by Superfund sites;<p>

<LI><p>
The elimination of retroactive liability for harmless activities;<p>

<LI><p>
The elimination of liability for parties not directly responsible for the
creation or maintenance of sites;<p>

<LI><p>
The phase out of Superfund&#146;s taxes on chemicals, petroleum products and
corporations;<p>

<LI><p>
Increased flexibility in the selection of cleanup and containment standards
and methods;<p>

<LI><p>
Greater local control over the cleanup process;  <p>

<LI><p>
Greater local responsibility for the allocation of cleanup resources;<p>

<LI><p>
The ability of communities and site owners to opt out of the Superfund
process.<p>

</UL>
<p>
One possibility for Superfund reform is the creation of a revolving state loan
fund to assist local communities with the costs of cleaning up abandoned sites
and the phasing out of federal involvement in non-federal waste site cleanup.
This would increase local authority over and responsibility for the clean up of
waste sites and encourage a more rational determination of clean up
priorities.<p>
<p>
<p>
<p>
Q: <i>Should there be a uniform, national cleanup standard for all Superfund
sites? Or should the required level of cleanup be flexible?</i><p>
<i></i><p>
A: Each site is unique, and that is not accounted for in the current Superfund
program.  Instead, the federal government has imposed a one-size fits nobody
approach.  A site that is going to house a school or family homes has different
requirements than a site where industrial development, such as a factory or
waste processing plant, will occur.  This should be a factor in the
determination of cleanup standards.<p>
     This question &#151; &#147;How clean is clean?&#148; &#151; is one of the
central issues in Superfund reform. Equally important should be the question of
who makes that determination: affected communities or the federal government.
Fairness and accountability suggest that local communities, which have more at
stake, should have a greater role in this decisionmaking process. <p>
<p>
<p>
Q: <i>Sites that are placed on the Superfund cleanup list are contaminated with
hazardous wastes. Don&#146;t health concerns justify mandating that all
Superfund sites be cleaned to the highest possible standards?</i><p>
<i></i><p>
A: Although Superfund sites typically contain wastes that are defined as
hazardous, most public health experts do not believe that Superfund sites pose
a significant health risk, particularly when such sites are fenced off or
isolated.  At those sites where health risks are present, it is often possible
to mitigate those risks at far less expense.  For example, it is often possible
to contain contaminated portions of a site for far less money than would be
required to meet the cleanup standards.  Because the last ten percent of
cleanup is often as expensive as the first ninety percent, even though the last
stages of cleanup add minimal risk protection, Superfund regulations should not
be based on the assumption that cleanup to pristine standards is the proper
policy for every site.<p>
<p>
<p>
Q:<i> Does the Clinton Administration Superfund proposal adequately address the
needs of local communities?</i><p>
<p>
A: The Clinton proposal devotes considerable space to the inclusion of local
communities in the Superfund decisionmaking process.  However, the Clinton
proposal stops far short of what is necessary.  Rather than simply including
community representatives in the federal decisionmaking process, the process
itself should be decentralized.  This would truly give local communities the
authority and responsibility they need to adequately address Superfund
concerns.<p>




<BR>
<HR NOSHADE>
