<HEAD>
<TITLE>CEI: Technology Subsidies</TITLE>
</HEAD>

<BODY BGCOLOR="FFFFFF">

<A NAME="top"></A>
<IMG SRC="ceiebb.gif" ALT="CEI Environmental Briefing Book" ALIGN=LEFT>
<BR>
<BR>
<BR>
<BR>
<BR>

<CENTER>
<H2>Technology Subsidies</H2>
</CENTER>


<P>Industrial policy is a dangerous and costly attempt to plan the nation&#146;s
technological future.  The federal government is no more capable of
&#147;forcing&#148; industry to develop viable
&#147;environmentally-sound&#148; technologies than it is capable of
centrally-planning the economy.  Federal subsidies for technological
development &#151; industrial policy by another name &#151; are more likely to
be determined by special interest considerations than they are by accurate
assessments of the technological future.<p>
     Historically, major industrial policy programs have consistently failed.
Federal technology projects such as the supersonic transport plane, the breeder
nuclear reactor, and the synthetic fuels program wasted billions of tax dollars
and produced few, if any, tangible benefits.  In short, the federal government
has a miserable record at picking winners and losers in the marketplace.  There
is no reason to believe that environmental industrial policy programs will be
any different.<p>
     Today the federal government is providing over $1 billion in  subsidies to
American auto-makers to produce an &#147;environmentally friendly&#148; car of
the future.  The true environmental benefits of this program are doubtful.  For
example, electricity must be generated in order to power electric car
batteries, which in turn requires the burning of fossil fuels.  There is no
reason why the &#147;Big Three,&#148; or any other corporations, should be
singled out for special government assistance in funding research and
development.<p>
     Department of Commerce subsidies have also been proposed for developing
technologies such as computers, biotechnology, advanced materials, alternative
fuels, and the fiber optic &#147;information superhighway.&#148;  Though
government subsidies for research and development are supposed to make industry
more competitive, they are more often an instrument for pork-barrel politics.
The Superconducting Supercollider was intended to keep the U.S. on the
forefront of particle physics research and generate thousands of high-tech
jobs.  Yet the $11 billion project hemorrhaged financially from its inception.
Taxpayer dollars were used for a holiday party at a fashionable Dallas hotel,
potted tropical plants, and even four lounge chairs.<p>
     Technology policy is a classic example of what Nobel Prize-winning economist
Friedrich Hayek once called the &#147;fatal conceit,&#148; a  futile attempt to
improve economic outcomes by substituting the judgements of central planners
for the dispersed knowledge of millions of producers and consumers which market
prices communicate and reflect.  Environmental technology subsidies are no
different.  All such programs are likely to do is create a green-coated spoils
system, while failing to advance environmental and economic goals.<p>
<p>
<p>
<p>
<p>
Q:<i> Shouldn&#146;t the federal government ensure that new technologies are
&#147;Earth-friendly&#148;?</i><p>
<i></i><p>
A: Saving the planet is a noble objective, but federal subsidies to the private
sector will not improve environmental quality.  The federal government will not
be able to identify the best technologies in an objective way.  Inevitably,
decisions about which companies to subsidize will come down to politics.
Companies with superior lobbying power in Washington, DC will be the
&#147;winners&#148; in the selection process.  Thus, businesses would have to
spend their money in ways which please politicians, not investors or consumers.
Markets reward technologies with real value; subsidies divert resources away
from the natural winners.<p>
     Bureaucracies have little incentive to spend the taxpayers&#146; money wisely.
If money is wasted on a foolish technological venture, the bureaucracy does not
suffer any loss.  In the private marketplace, businesses are held accountable
for unwise investments, and can be expected to take financial risks more
seriously.  Technology cannot be &#147;Earth-friendly&#148; if it is managed by
politicians.<p>
<p>
<p>
Q: <i>Since the Cold War is over, we are spending less money on defense and
there are fewer jobs for the high-skilled workers in the defense industry.  Why
not spend more of the defense budget on high-tech projects to create worthwhile
jobs for these workers?</i><p>
<p>
A: Massive pork-barrel spending boosts the budget deficit and places
unnecessary burdens upon taxpayers.  When the focus is on creating jobs,
politicians inevitably want the money spent in their districts and at their
universities.  Too often, politics ignores the merits of the technologies
themselves.<p>
     Unfortunately, the record of federal spending on technology is abysmal.
Congressional mega-projects like the Supercollider have been terribly
mismanaged.  High-tech investments involve tremendous risk, and the country
cannot afford more expensive blunders.  Wasteful federal technology projects do
not help high-skilled workers, rather they prevent such workers from finding
productive work in competitive fields.  Instead, we must unleash the job
creation potential of the marketplace by reducing tax and regulatory burdens
and liberalizing tariffs and other trade barriers.<p>



<BR>
<HR NOSHADE>
