␀␀␀␀␀␀␀␀␀␀␀␀␀␀␀␀␀␀␀␀␀␀␀␀␀␀␀␀␀␀␀␀␀␀␀␀␀␀␀␀␀␀␀␀␀␀␀␀␀␀␀␀␀␀␀␀␀␀␀␀␀␀␀␀␀␀␀␀␀␀␀␀␀␀␀␀␀␀␀␀␀␀␀␀␀␀␀␀␀␀␀␀␀␀␀␀␀␀␀␀␀␀␀␀␀␀␀␀␀␀␀␀␀␀␀␀␀␀␀␀␀␀␀␀␀␀␀␀␀␀␀␀␀␀␀␀␀␀␀␀␀␀␀␀␀␀␀␀␀␀␀␀␀␀␀␀␀␀␀␀␀␀␀␀␀␀␀␀␀␀␀␀␀␀␀␀␀␀␀␀␀␀␀␀␀␀␀␀␀␀␀␀␀␀␀␀␀␀␀␀␀␀␀␀␀␀␀␀␀␀␀␀␀␀␀␀␀␀␀␀␀␀␀␀␀␀␀␀␀␀␀␀␀␀␀␀␀␀␀␀␀␀␀␀␀␀␀␀␀␀␀␀␀␀␀␀␀␀␀␀␀␀␀␀␀␀␀␀␀␀␀␀␀␀␀␀␀␀␀␀␀␀␀␀␀␀␀␀␀␀␀␀␀␀␀␀␀␀␀␀␀␀␀␀␀␀␀␀␀␀␀␀␀␀␀␀␀␀␀␀␀␀␀␀␀␀␀␀␀␀␀␀␀␀␀␀␀␀␀␀␀␀␀␀␀␀␀␀␀␀␀␀␀␀␀␀␀␀␀␀␀␀␀␀␀␀␀␀␀␀␀␀␀␀␀␀ebb22.html␀␀␀␀␀␀␀␀␀␀␀␀␀␀␀␀␀␀␀␀␀␀␀␀␀␀␀␀␀␀␀␀␀␀␀␀␀␀␀␀␀␀␀␀␀␀␀␀␀␀␀␀␀␀␀␀␀␀␀␀␀␀␀␀␀␀␀␀␀␀␀␀␀␀␀␀␀␀␀␀␀␀␀␀␀␀␀␀␀␀100644 ␀  1647 ␀   144 ␀      14054  6061646003  11052␀ 0␀␀␀␀␀␀␀␀␀␀␀␀␀␀␀␀␀␀␀␀␀␀␀␀␀␀␀␀␀␀␀␀␀␀␀␀␀␀␀␀␀␀␀␀␀␀␀␀␀␀␀␀␀␀␀␀␀␀␀␀␀␀␀␀␀␀␀␀␀␀␀␀␀␀␀␀␀␀␀␀␀␀␀␀␀␀␀␀␀␀␀␀␀␀␀␀␀␀␀␀ustar  ␀cei␀␀␀␀␀␀␀␀␀␀␀␀␀␀␀␀␀␀␀␀␀␀␀␀␀␀␀␀␀users␀␀␀␀␀␀␀␀␀␀␀␀␀␀␀␀␀␀␀␀␀␀␀␀␀␀␀␀␀␀␀␀␀␀␀␀␀␀␀␀␀␀␀␀␀␀␀␀␀␀␀␀␀␀␀␀␀␀␀␀␀␀␀␀␀␀␀␀␀␀␀␀␀␀␀␀␀␀␀␀␀␀␀␀␀␀␀␀␀␀␀␀␀␀␀␀␀␀␀␀␀␀␀␀␀␀␀␀␀␀␀␀␀␀␀␀␀␀␀␀␀␀␀␀␀␀␀␀␀␀␀␀␀␀␀␀␀␀␀␀␀␀␀␀␀␀␀␀␀␀␀␀␀␀␀␀␀␀␀␀␀␀␀␀␀␀␀␀␀␀␀␀␀␀␀␀␀␀␀␀␀␀␀␀␀␀␀␀␀␀␀␀␀␀␀␀␀␀␀␀␀␀␀␀␀␀␀␀␀␀<HTML>
<HEAD>
<TITLE>CEI: Trade and the Environment</TITLE>
</HEAD>

<BODY BGCOLOR="FFFFFF">

<A NAME="top"></A>
<IMG SRC="ceiebb.gif" ALT="CEI Environmental Briefing Book" ALIGN=LEFT>
<BR>
<BR>
<BR>
<BR>
<BR>

<CENTER>
<H2>Trade and the Environment</H2>
</CENTER>


<P>There is near universal agreement about the economic benefits of free trade.
Lowering trade barriers reduces consumer prices and increases choice in the
marketplace.  At present, environmental restrictions pose the single greatest
threat to the international trading system.  Congress should not allow the
&#147;greening&#148; of international trade to compromise these benefits.<p>
     The &#147;greening&#148; of international trade began under the North American
Free Trade Agreement (NAFTA), which includes an environmental side agreement
that encourages the upward harmonization of environmental regulations.  Similar
efforts are being made to &#147;green&#148; the General Agreement on Tariffs
and Trade (GATT), the Generalized System of Preferences, and the Asia-Pacific
Economic Cooperation forum.  &#147;Green&#148; trade measures are also being
proposed in negotiations with Latin American countries, such as Chile and
Argentina, that oppose linking trade liberalization to environmental
regulations.  Regretably, &#147;green&#148; trade will do little to improve
environmental quality.<p>
     Some attempt to justify environmental import restrictions and trade sanctions
as necessary to reduce trade&#146;s impact on the environment and to equalize
environmental regulations across borders.  These measures are justified on
neither economic nor environmental grounds, and are often a thinly veiled guise
for special interest protectionism.  For example, the U.S. has embargoed
Mexican tuna imports because more dolphins got caught in Mexican tuna fishing
nets than in American nets.  Not only did the embargo protect U.S. sales from
foreign competition, it also forced Mexican fishermen out of the Eastern
Tropical Pacific and into new fisheries where tuna fishing results in even
greater environmental impact.  The ban may have benefited some American tuna
fisherman, but it came at the expense of American consumers and the dolphins it
purported to save.<p>
     The European Community has attempted to use phony health concerns to block
U.S. imports and deny European consumers the access to certain products.  For
example, the EC erected import restrictions on U.S. beef, alleging that the use
of bovine growth hormones posed a health risk to consumers.  However when these
claims were subjected to scientific scrutiny, they were found to be false.  It
is more likely that the EC was simply interested in protecting European beef
producers from American competition.  The &#147;greening&#148; of trade will
allow more industries to allege environmental concerns in order to block
foreign imports in this manner.<p>
     By closing off export markets, &#147;green&#148; protectionism results in
diminished competitiveness, higher prices, and unemployment.  &#147;Green&#148;
trade restrictions also harm the environment by destroying the wealth necessary
to pay for many environmental improvements, such as water sanitation and
purification.  Without access to global markets, developing countries lack the
means to acquire cleaner, more efficient technologies.  Equally important is
the fact that &#147;wealthier-is-healthier.&#148;  As incomes rise in
developing countries, so do life expectancies.  Restricting prosperity through
the imposition of protectionist measures, &#147;green&#148; or otherwise,
necessarily has a negative impact on human health.<p>
     U.S. trade policy should pursue free trade, not managed trade or protectionism
under the guise of environmental protection.  The resulting increase in
productivity and prosperity will do more for environmental quality than any
&#147;greening&#148; of international trade.<p>
<p>
<p>
<p>
Q: <i>Won&#146;t free trade lead to a &#147;race to the bottom&#148; in which
environmental and labor standards are reduced for competitive reasons?</i><p>
<i></i><p>
A: All countries have differing priorities when it comes to environmental
protection.  Developing countries, in particular, do not have the resources to
support massive environmental restrictions on business that we have in the U.S.
It would be unfair to impose our First World standards on Third World
countries.<p>
     There is a necessary trade-off between regulation and economic growth.  If the
U.S. uses its trade leverage to impose higher regulatory costs on developing
countries, crucial economic opportunities will be lost and poverty will
continue.  The best way to ensure environmental quality and economic growth in
developing countries is through free trade.  Only by expanding their trade and
development opportunities can Third World nations create the underlying wealth
that is essential for environmental protection.<p>
<p>
<p>
Q: <i>Shouldn&#146;t America refuse to trade with countries that unfairly
subsidize their domestic industries by maintaining lax environmental
standards?</i><p>
<i></i><p>
A: Trade should not be used as an instrument for social objectives.  President
Clinton wisely decided to separate trade issues from human rights concerns in
China because rising incomes will create greater pressures for democracy.
Higher incomes will have similar effects on environmental quality.<p>
     If trade sanctions are used as a weapon in trade policy, the U.S. risks
becoming the world&#146;s unelected environmental policeman.  Disruptions in
international commerce will unfairly burden American exporters and importers,
and hurt our competitiveness.  The consequences for developing countries &#151;
diminished trade &#151; would perpetuate poverty by preventing them from
exporting to the U.S. market.  Poverty is not an effective pollution-control
measure.<p>



<BR>
<HR NOSHADE>
