<HEAD>
<TITLE>CEI: Unfunded Mandates</TITLE>
</HEAD>

<BODY BGCOLOR="FFFFFF">

<A NAME="top"></A>
<IMG SRC="ceiebb.gif" ALT="CEI Environmental Briefing Book" ALIGN=LEFT>
<BR>
<BR>
<BR>
<BR>
<BR>

<CENTER>
<H2>Unfunded Mandates</H2>
</CENTER>


<P>Congress should scale-back existing unfunded mandates and refrain from passing
more in the future.  Imposing unfunded mandates is a fundamentally unfair and
undemocratic means of enacting environmental policy that short-circuits
accountability and hamstrings the ability to set rational environmental
priorities.<p>
     Congress creates unfunded mandates when it passes environmental laws requiring
state and/or local governments to meet particular goals or enact particular
regulatory programs and then fails to fund their implementation.  Unfunded
mandates are proliferating rapidly across the board.  Prior to 1988, there were
only 40 unfunded federal mandates, environmental and otherwise.  Between 1988
and 1991, that number nearly tripled.  Nearly 12 percent of municipal revenues
must now go to meeting unfunded mandates.<p>
     Environmental mandates are among the most expensive.  There are unfunded
mandates in the Clean Air Act, Clean Water Act, Safe Drinking Water Act, and
many other major environmental laws.  Major cities will spend $3.6 billion on
the Clean Water Act this year, and county governments expect to spend over
$16.1 billion on environmental mandates between now and 1998.  Unfunded
mandates are devastating local treasuries.  For instance:<p>
<UL>
<LI><p>
Columbus, Ohio, is being forced to spend $16 million to lower atrazine levels
in the city&#146;s water supply to avert a speculative cancer risk.  To meet
the requirement, Columbus is forced to consider eliminating or scaling back
other health-related programs.<p>

<LI><p>
Lancaster, New Hampshire, with annual revenues of $1.4 million, will be forced
to spend $2 million meeting federal drinking water standards.<p>

<LI><p>
Lewiston, Maine, is looking at mandate costs of approximately $92 million.
For a city population of only 40,000, this equals $600 per household.<p>

</UL>
<p>
     Unfunded mandates are undemocratic and destroy accountability.  They enable
politicians to enact policies without voting for the taxes (or offsetting
spending cuts) to pay for them.  Members of Congress have used unfunded
mandates to demonstrate their support for popular public goals while disguising
the costs of their programs.  State and local governments, and their taxpayers,
are stuck footing the bill.  Unfunded mandates often mean that higher local
priorities must be pushed aside to meet Washington, D.C.&#146;s dictates.<p>
     Unfunded mandates should come to an end.  A simple &#147;no money, no
mandate&#148; policy whereby state and local governments are not obligated to
establish federally-mandated programs unless those requirements are paid for by
the federal government is one way to achieve this.  <p>
     In the end, Congress simply needs to recognize that not every environmental
concern requires a federal program or initiative.  State and local governments
are just as concerned with the health and well-being of their residents.  They
are more than capable of setting environmental priorities and addressing local
concerns.  In many instances, Congress could best foster more rational
environmental policy-making by simply getting out of the way.  The states were
intended to be &#147;laboratories of democracy,&#148; developing innovative and
experimental approaches to vexing public policy concerns.  Imposing unfunded
mandates prevents states from playing that vital role, and can even inhibit the
development of forward-looking and effective environmental policies.<p>
<p>
<p>
<p>
Q: <i>Why shouldn&#146;t the federal government impose stringent environmental
standards on states and localities?</i><p>
<p>
A: This question assumes that state and local governments are unable to
determine environmental priorities for their own communities.  State officials
are no less concerned about clean water problems or clean air problems than are
federal officials.  If anything, state and local governments are closer to the
environmental concerns of local communities and better able to develop the
proper remedies.  It is one thing for the federal government to provide
guidance to local communities on environmental matters.  It is another thing
for the federal government to require particular programs, and leave state and
local taxpayers footing the bill.<p>
<p>
<p>
Q: <i>Won&#146;t a &#147;no money, no mandate&#148; policy prevent the
government from providing the environmental protection that Americans
want?</i><p>
<p>
A: A &#147;no money, no mandate&#148; policy will restore accountability to
environmental policy.  Protecting the environment is important, but so are
health care, education, crime prevention, and the whole range of concerns that
state and local governments are forced to address.  State and local governments
need the flexibility to be able to respond to the needs of their constituents.
Piling on environmental requirements without providing the resources to meet
those requirements destroys that flexibility.  Environmental protection is
necessary, but it always has costs.  Controlling unfunded mandates ensures that
when environmental policies are enacted, it is clear how they will be paid
for.<p>


<BR>
<HR NOSHADE>
<BR>
<CENTER>
<A HREF="ebb24.html"><IMG SRC="forward.gif" ALT="Forward to the next page"></A>
<A HREF="ebb.html"><IMG SRC="back.gif" ALT="Back to the beginning"></A>

<BR>
<BR>
<A HREF="index.html">Back to the CEI Home Page</A><BR>
</CENTER>
<BR>
<BR>
</BODY>
</HTML>
␀␀␀␀␀␀␀␀␀␀␀␀␀␀␀␀␀␀␀␀␀␀␀␀␀␀␀␀␀␀␀␀␀␀␀␀␀␀␀␀␀␀␀␀␀␀␀␀␀␀␀␀␀␀␀␀␀␀␀␀␀␀␀␀␀␀␀␀␀␀␀␀␀␀␀␀␀␀␀␀␀␀␀␀␀␀␀␀␀␀␀␀␀␀␀␀␀␀␀␀␀␀␀␀␀␀␀␀␀␀␀␀␀␀␀␀␀␀␀␀␀␀␀␀␀␀␀␀␀␀␀␀␀␀␀␀␀␀␀␀␀␀␀␀␀␀␀␀␀␀␀␀␀␀␀␀␀␀␀␀␀␀␀␀␀␀␀␀␀␀␀␀␀␀␀␀␀␀␀␀␀␀␀␀␀␀␀␀␀␀␀␀␀␀␀␀␀␀␀␀␀␀␀␀␀␀␀␀␀␀␀␀␀␀␀␀␀␀␀␀␀␀␀␀␀␀␀␀␀␀␀␀␀␀␀␀␀␀␀␀␀␀␀␀␀␀␀␀␀␀␀␀␀␀␀␀␀␀␀␀␀␀␀␀␀␀␀␀␀␀␀␀␀␀␀␀␀␀␀␀␀␀␀␀␀␀␀␀␀␀␀␀␀␀␀␀␀␀␀␀␀␀␀␀␀␀␀␀␀␀␀␀␀␀␀␀␀␀␀␀␀␀␀␀␀␀␀␀␀␀␀␀␀␀␀␀␀␀␀␀␀␀␀␀␀␀␀␀␀␀␀␀␀␀␀␀␀␀␀␀␀␀␀␀␀␀␀␀␀␀␀␀␀␀␀␀␀␀␀␀␀␀␀␀␀␀␀␀␀␀␀␀␀␀␀␀␀␀␀␀␀␀␀␀␀␀␀␀␀␀␀␀␀␀␀␀␀␀␀␀␀␀␀␀␀␀␀␀␀␀␀␀␀␀␀␀␀␀␀␀␀␀␀␀␀␀␀␀␀␀␀␀␀␀␀␀␀␀␀␀␀␀␀␀␀ebb24.html␀␀␀␀␀␀␀␀␀␀␀␀␀␀␀␀␀␀␀␀␀␀␀␀␀␀␀␀␀␀␀␀␀␀␀␀␀␀␀␀␀␀␀␀␀␀␀␀␀␀␀␀␀␀␀␀␀␀␀␀␀␀␀␀␀␀␀␀␀␀␀␀␀␀␀␀␀␀␀␀␀␀␀␀␀␀␀␀␀␀100644 ␀  1647 ␀   144 ␀      12520  6061646022  11051␀ 0␀␀␀␀␀␀␀␀␀␀␀␀␀␀␀␀␀␀␀␀␀␀␀␀␀␀␀␀␀␀␀␀␀␀␀␀␀␀␀␀␀␀␀␀␀␀␀␀␀␀␀␀␀␀␀␀␀␀␀␀␀␀␀␀␀␀␀␀␀␀␀␀␀␀␀␀␀␀␀␀␀␀␀␀␀␀␀␀␀␀␀␀␀␀␀␀␀␀␀␀ustar  ␀cei␀␀␀␀␀␀␀␀␀␀␀␀␀␀␀␀␀␀␀␀␀␀␀␀␀␀␀␀␀users␀␀␀␀␀␀␀␀␀␀␀␀␀␀␀␀␀␀␀␀␀␀␀␀␀␀␀␀␀␀␀␀␀␀␀␀␀␀␀␀␀␀␀␀␀␀␀␀␀␀␀␀␀␀␀␀␀␀␀␀␀␀␀␀␀␀␀␀␀␀␀␀␀␀␀␀␀␀␀␀␀␀␀␀␀␀␀␀␀␀␀␀␀␀␀␀␀␀␀␀␀␀␀␀␀␀␀␀␀␀␀␀␀␀␀␀␀␀␀␀␀␀␀␀␀␀␀␀␀␀␀␀␀␀␀␀␀␀␀␀␀␀␀␀␀␀␀␀␀␀␀␀␀␀␀␀␀␀␀␀␀␀␀␀␀␀␀␀␀␀␀␀␀␀␀␀␀␀␀␀␀␀␀␀␀␀␀␀␀␀␀␀␀␀␀␀␀␀␀␀␀␀␀␀␀␀␀␀␀␀<HTML>
<HEAD>
<TITLE>CEI: Wetlands</TITLE>
</HEAD>

<BODY BGCOLOR="FFFFFF">

<A NAME="top"></A>
<IMG SRC="ceiebb.gif" ALT="CEI Environmental Briefing Book" ALIGN=LEFT>
<BR>
<BR>
<BR>
<BR>
<BR>

<CENTER>
<H2>Wetlands</H2>
</CENTER>


<P>The federal government has implemented regulations to prevent the destruction
or alteration of America&#146;s wetlands.  These regulations deny private
landowners the productive use of their land without compensation.  Wetlands
rules have bankrupted landowners and even sent Americans to jail for the
&#147;crime&#148; of wetland modification.  The cause of wetland protection is
better served through positive incentives and wetland enhancement programs than
it is by imposing limitations on the use of private land.<p>
     Under section 404 of the Clean Water Act, landowners must receive a permit
from the U.S. Army Corps of Engineers before engaging in any activity that may
affect a wetland.  Because of how the federal government defines wetlands,
there are over 100 million acres of protected wetlands in the United States.
For example, according to North Carolina Senator Lauch Faircloth, 70 percent of
North Carolina is classified as wetlands.<p>
     These regulations restrict the rights and liberties of private property
owners.  Citizens are routinely denied permits from the Corps of Engineers to
modify their properties, even when such activities have minimal environmental
impact.  For example, in Nome, Alaska a woman whose house began to sink, so
much so that she can no longer close her front door, was denied a permit by the
Army Corps of Engineers to add 5 inches of fill material to stabilize her
house.  Similarly, in Sula, Montana a farmer was not allowed to drain water
from a hayfield, even though the field had been rendered unusable after a
nearby beaver dam caused increased seepage.  Similar examples can be found in
nearly every rural district in the country.<p>
     Federal wetlands policies also place burdens on state and local governments.
By prohibiting development, the regulations often depress land values and,
consequently, local government revenues from property taxes.  One study found
that local governments could lose over $180 million in revenue in the state of
Arkansas alone. If the Arkansas analysis is correct, local governments
nationwide may lose up to $6.3 billion in property tax revenues.<p>
     While some argue that section 404 regulations are needed to protect
America&#146;s vanishing wetlands, recent evidence shows that America is
creating more wetlands than are being destroyed.  In 1994, the
government&#146;s top three wetland restoration programs will restore a
combined total of 157,000 acres of wetlands.  At the same time, data from the
government&#146;s National Resource Inventory concludes that the U.S. will only
convert just over 100,000 acres of wetlands to other uses.  In other words, by
the end of 1994 there should be tens of thousands more acres of wetlands than
there were at the beginning.<p>
     When the Clean Water Act is reauthorized, the wetlands protection program
should be reformed.  The following reforms would improve the current federal
approach to wetlands regulation:<p>

<UL>

<LI><p>
Compensate property owners when reasonable use of their land has been taken by
wetland regulation;<p>

<LI><p>
Regulate only those wetlands deemed to be of significant ecological
importance;<p>

<LI><p>
Allow landowners who mitigate (create wetlands to replace the ones which have
be used) the unrestricted use of their land;<p>

<LI><p>
Eliminate &#147;no net loss&#148; of wetlands as an official government
policy.<p>

</UL>
<p>
These steps would enhance the protection of private property without
sacrificing the environmental goal of wetlands protection.<p>
<p>
Q:<i> Some say that America is losing 300,000 acres of wetlands a year.  Is
this true?</i><p>
<p>
A: No. The 300,000 acre figure is based on an old study that did not account
for both public and private wetland restoration projects.  In reality, more
wetlands are being created each year than are being destroyed.  The stated goal
of &#147;no net loss&#148; of American wetlands was achieved several years
ago.<p>
<p>
<p>
Q: <i>What is wrong with a simple permit process for people who wish to
develop, and potentially destroy, ecologically-important wetlands?</i><p>
<i></i><p>
A: The permitting process is not so &#147;simple.&#148;  While the permitting
process sounds reasonable on paper, it has been extremely onerous in practice.
Under current law, the Corps of Engineers must approve or reject a wetland
modification permit application within 60 days.  However, the average wait for
a ruling on a permit application is currently over a year!  Furthermore, the
process does not account for the fact that not all wetlands have equal
ecological significance.  Some wetlands perform important water filtration,
flood mitigation, and habitat enhancement functions.  Others are mere bogs and
breeding grounds for pests.  If a permitting process is necessary, it would be
more appropriate for the federal government to seek to protect the
highest-value wetlands, and the ecological values they promote, than to impose
a blanket wetlands protection policy.<p>
<p>
<BR>
<HR NOSHADE>
