␀␀␀␀␀␀␀␀␀␀␀␀␀␀␀␀␀␀␀␀␀␀␀␀␀␀␀␀␀␀␀␀␀␀␀␀␀␀␀␀␀␀␀␀␀␀␀␀␀␀␀␀␀␀␀␀␀␀␀␀␀␀␀␀␀␀␀␀␀␀␀␀␀␀␀␀␀␀␀␀␀␀␀␀␀␀␀␀␀␀␀␀␀␀␀␀␀␀␀␀␀␀␀␀␀␀␀␀␀␀␀␀␀␀␀␀␀␀␀␀␀␀␀␀␀␀␀␀␀␀␀␀␀␀␀␀␀␀␀␀␀␀␀␀␀␀␀␀␀␀␀␀␀␀␀␀␀␀␀␀␀␀␀␀␀␀␀␀␀␀␀␀␀␀␀␀␀␀␀␀␀␀␀␀␀␀␀␀␀␀␀␀␀␀␀␀␀␀␀␀␀␀␀␀␀␀␀␀␀␀␀␀␀␀␀␀␀␀␀␀␀␀␀␀␀␀␀␀␀␀␀␀␀␀␀␀␀␀␀␀␀␀␀␀␀␀␀␀␀␀␀␀␀␀␀␀␀␀␀␀␀␀␀␀␀␀␀␀␀␀ebb4.html␀␀␀␀␀␀␀␀␀␀␀␀␀␀␀␀␀␀␀␀␀␀␀␀␀␀␀␀␀␀␀␀␀␀␀␀␀␀␀␀␀␀␀␀␀␀␀␀␀␀␀␀␀␀␀␀␀␀␀␀␀␀␀␀␀␀␀␀␀␀␀␀␀␀␀␀␀␀␀␀␀␀␀␀␀␀␀␀␀␀␀100644 ␀  1647 ␀   144 ␀      12564  6061646047  11006␀ 0␀␀␀␀␀␀␀␀␀␀␀␀␀␀␀␀␀␀␀␀␀␀␀␀␀␀␀␀␀␀␀␀␀␀␀␀␀␀␀␀␀␀␀␀␀␀␀␀␀␀␀␀␀␀␀␀␀␀␀␀␀␀␀␀␀␀␀␀␀␀␀␀␀␀␀␀␀␀␀␀␀␀␀␀␀␀␀␀␀␀␀␀␀␀␀␀␀␀␀␀ustar  ␀cei␀␀␀␀␀␀␀␀␀␀␀␀␀␀␀␀␀␀␀␀␀␀␀␀␀␀␀␀␀users␀␀␀␀␀␀␀␀␀␀␀␀␀␀␀␀␀␀␀␀␀␀␀␀␀␀␀␀␀␀␀␀␀␀␀␀␀␀␀␀␀␀␀␀␀␀␀␀␀␀␀␀␀␀␀␀␀␀␀␀␀␀␀␀␀␀␀␀␀␀␀␀␀␀␀␀␀␀␀␀␀␀␀␀␀␀␀␀␀␀␀␀␀␀␀␀␀␀␀␀␀␀␀␀␀␀␀␀␀␀␀␀␀␀␀␀␀␀␀␀␀␀␀␀␀␀␀␀␀␀␀␀␀␀␀␀␀␀␀␀␀␀␀␀␀␀␀␀␀␀␀␀␀␀␀␀␀␀␀␀␀␀␀␀␀␀␀␀␀␀␀␀␀␀␀␀␀␀␀␀␀␀␀␀␀␀␀␀␀␀␀␀␀␀␀␀␀␀␀␀␀␀␀␀␀␀␀␀␀␀<HTML>
<HEAD>
<TITLE>CEI: Clean Air Act Reform</TITLE>
</HEAD>

<BODY BGCOLOR="FFFFFF">

<A NAME="top"></A>
<IMG SRC="ceiebb.gif" ALT="CEI Environmental Briefing Book" ALIGN=LEFT>
<BR>
<BR>
<BR>
<BR>
<BR>

<CENTER>
<H2>Clean Air Act Reform</H2>
</CENTER>


<P>State and local governments should be afforded more flexibility in the
determination of air pollution control methods and goals.  At present, areas
not meeting federal clean air standards are forced to implement costly and
inefficient air pollution control strategies and are discouraged from using
more cost-effective and equitable approaches.<p>
     At an estimated cost of $25 to $35 billion, the Clean Air Act Amendments of
1990 are the most expensive single piece of environmental legislation ever
enacted.  In addition to industrial emissions, it regulates automobile design,
gasoline content, and driving habits, as well as emissions from dry cleaners,
bakeries and other small businesses.<p>
     A significant portion of federal clean air law is aimed at controlling motor
vehicle emissions.  It imposes broad &#147;drift-net&#148; strategies that
impact all vehicles and car owners irrespective of their relative contributions
to pollution levels.  It is well-established that only a small fraction of
motor vehicles generate the lion&#146;s share of emissions.  Ten percent of the
vehicles on the road are responsible for approximately half of
automobile-related emissions.  This means that for every ten vehicles on the
road, the dirtiest car emits as much as the remaining nine.  By failing to
focus emission-reduction efforts on the dirtiest vehicles, federal air
pollution control strategies are both inefficient and inequitable.<p>
     Under federal law, those areas that do not meet federal air quality standards
are required to implement particular pollution control measures, even if better
options are available.  Some of the Clean Air Act&#146;s rigid requirements
include:<p>

<UL>

<LI>Mandating expensive, centralized vehicle inspection and maintenance programs
that impose significant costs and inconvenience upon car owners without
providing corresponding benefits as opposed to less-expensive, decentralized
testing methods.
<LI>Requiring companies in the nine smoggiest metropolitan areas to induce
greater car-pooling and use of mass transit by their employees under threat of
fines.
<LI>Requiring that 30 percent of the oxygenates used in federally-mandated
reformulated gasoline comes from &#147;renewable&#148; sources, even though
these oxygenates are more expensive and no more beneficial for the
environment.
</UL>

<p>
There are few parts of the country that would voluntarily adopt these methods
to achieve the federal government&#146;s stringent air quality standards.
Moreover, air pollution strategies that are effective in one area, may be less
so somewhere else.  States need to be given greater flexibility to meet federal
clean air standards, and perhaps even the authority to evaluate proper regional
standards for themselves.<p>
<p>
Q: <i>Why shouldn&#146;t automakers be forced to manufacture cleaner cars and
the oil companies forced to make cleaner fuels?</i><p>
<p>
A: New cars produced today are already over 90 percent cleaner than those
produced twenty-five years ago.  There simply is not much to be gained from
further tightening new vehicle or new fuel emission standards.  If further
emission reductions are desired, it is better to focus on the greatest source
of emissions.  Ten percent of the cars on the road produce over half of the
emissions.  Targeting those vehicles for emission reductions will be more
effective, and more fair, than imposing fuel standards, vehicle standards, and
other &#147;drift-net&#148; strategies on everybody.<p>
<p>
<p>
Q: <i>Are electric cars a viable way to reduce auto-related air
pollution?</i><p>
<p>
A: Many have proposed encouraging the purchase of electric cars to reduce air
pollution.  Unfortunately, while electric cars sound wonderful on paper, they
are less so in practice.  Electric cars have many drawbacks that make them
insufficient for the needs of most car owners, including limited range,
recharge requirements and a lack of amenities (air conditioning, heater, etc.).
Moreover, electric cars are not without their environmental impacts.  The
electricity to charge the batteries must come from some source, often resulting
in air emissions.  Moreover, we must remember that electric car batteries will
have to be replaced every few years, and used batteries may have to be disposed
of as hazardous wastes.<p>
<p>
<p>
Q:<i> Are existing federal clean air standards stringent enough to protect
human health?</i><p>
<p>
A: Yes, if anything they are too stringent.  Non-attainment status is triggered
by surpassing the federal standard for an hour more than three times over a
three year period.  Thus, four bad hours on four bad days over three years are
sufficient to classify a city as a nonattainment area  by federal standards.
Residents in some areas may prefer such stringent standards, but it would be
better if communities had that choice, rather than having these standards
imposed upon them by the federal government.<p>





<BR>
