<HEAD>
<TITLE>CEI: Clean Water Act</TITLE>
</HEAD>

<BODY BGCOLOR="FFFFFF">

<A NAME="top"></A>
<IMG SRC="ceiebb.gif" ALT="CEI Environmental Briefing Book" ALIGN=LEFT>
<BR>
<BR>
<BR>
<BR>
<BR>

<CENTER>
<H2>Clean Water Act</H2>
</CENTER>
<P>The United States has achieved substantial gains in cleaning up our aquatic
environments over the past two-and-a-half decades.  Yet today, the EPA
continues to write more stringent and more expensive regulations that produce
minimal environmental results.  The Clean Water Act is a prime example of this
problem, and of why environmental regulation needs to be reformed.<p>
     America&#146;s waters were once in bad shape.  On June 22, 1969, sparks from a
passing train ignited floating debris and industrial chemicals in the Cuyahoga
river, near Cleveland, Ohio.  The image of the burning Cuyahoga river spurred
the creation of the Environmental Protection Agency as well as the passage of
the Clean Water Act.  <p>
     Today, the extreme industrial pollution that characterized the 1960s has been
virtually eliminated.  Many rivers are cleaner than they have been in decades.
Along the Cuyahoga riverfront in Cleveland there are now dozens of upscale
restaurants and bars, and during the summertime the river is crowded with
pleasure boats.  Tremendous progress has been made.<p>
     While there is far less water pollution to address, complying with the Clean
Water Act has become far more expensive.  Full compliance would cost as much as
$99 billion per year, according to the Environmental Protection Agency.  This
is more than the federal government collects in corporate income taxes.  The
majority of these costs are placed upon businesses, as much as $46 billion a
year.  A significant portion of the costs, however, are also born by
municipalities, up to $37 billion a year.<p>
     One reason compliance costs are so high is that the EPA&#146;s regulations are
inflexible and overly stringent.  For example, the EPA requires city treatment
plants to remove 30 percent of the organic material from the sewage that they
treat.  In most cities this is quite feasible.  However, in Anchorage, Alaska,
the sewage coming into the treatment plant is so clean that it would cost $135
million to build a facility just to treat water that already meets the
EPA&#146;s discharge standards.  It was cheaper for Anchorage to ask two local
fish processing plants to dump 5,000 pounds of fish guts into the sewer system
so that there would be enough waste in the water to clean it at a lower cost
and meet the regulation.  This is not how environmental policy should work.<p>
     The following elements should be part of any Clean Water Act reform
proposal:<p>

<UL>

<LI>The EPA should be required to perform a cost/benefit analysis of each and
every regulation to ensure that costs of complying with clean water regulation
do not outweigh their benefits.
<LI>If the EPA sets stringent new standards that will be expensive for state and
local governments to implement, it should also provide the funds to comply with
the standard (in other words, the EPA should refrain from imposing unfunded
environmental mandates).

<LI>The EPA should provide greater flexibility for local water agencies to set
standards based on local needs.
</UL>
<p>
Q:  <i>Shouldn&#146;t the clean water act be strengthened to prevent companies
from polluting our steams, lakes and rivers?</i><p>
<p>
A:  The number one source of pollution of America&#146;s rivers and lakes is
not industrial wastes; it is agricultural runoff.  The number two source is
municipal and urban runoff.  According to the EPA, industrial pollution ranks
last as a source of pollution.  Strengthening the current Clean Water Act will
simply create higher costs without achieving significant environmental
improvement.  Tightening standards on industrial discharges would be about as
effective as requiring homeowners to get a permit from the EPA before they
watered their lawns or flushed their toilets.<p>
<p>
<p>
Q:  <i>How would you change the Clean Water Act without weakening it?</i><p>
<p>
A:  The most important change that must be made is to put more flexibility in
the hands of state and local officials.  Even the current administrator of the
EPA, Carol Browner, thinks it&#146;s essential.  In a speech earlier this year
she said, &#147;We must allow for flexibility, innovation, and common sense as
states and communities look for ways to achieve the standards.&#148;  Under the
present scheme, says Browner, &#147;innovation is stifled rather than
encouraged.&#148;  Increasing regulatory flexibility would allow for greater
innovation.<p>
<p>
<p>
Q: <i>Are there ways to protect water quality without resorting to federal
regulation?</i><p>
<p>
A: Yes.  It would be more effective and equitable if water quality was
protected through the assertion and protection of private water rights, rather
than by command-and-control regulation.  Under common law principles,
individual polluters could be held liable for damaging the water quality of
those downstream.  This would provide a strict, but fair, standard whereby no
individual, corporation, or even municipality, could infringe upon the water
rights of another.  This approach also would be more flexible, because upstream
and downstream users could negotiate over competing water uses.  This type of
approach has been preempted by state and federal water pollution laws.  However
it would be useful to move toward this sort of common law, property
rights-based approach.<p>
<p>
<p>
Q: <i>Should the Clean Water Act be expanded to control non-point sources of
pollution such as agricultural and urban runoffs?</i><p>
<i></i><p>
A: Rather than expand the CWA, Congress should amend it to permit local
flexibility and experimentation.  Emissions create problems <i>somewhere</i>
before they create problems <i>elsewhere</i>.  Local communities and water
users should be allowed to deal with runoffs based on their own assessment of
the environmental/economic trade-offs.  In some cases, local solutions might be
facilitated by extending property rights to recreational and sporting clubs,
shell fisheries, and others with a stake in water quality.  When local problems
are addressed locally, they are less apt to become large problems requiring
federal intervention.<P>


<BR>
