␀␀␀␀␀␀␀␀␀␀␀␀␀␀␀␀␀␀␀␀␀␀␀␀␀␀␀␀␀␀␀␀ebb6.html␀␀␀␀␀␀␀␀␀␀␀␀␀␀␀␀␀␀␀␀␀␀␀␀␀␀␀␀␀␀␀␀␀␀␀␀␀␀␀␀␀␀␀␀␀␀␀␀␀␀␀␀␀␀␀␀␀␀␀␀␀␀␀␀␀␀␀␀␀␀␀␀␀␀␀␀␀␀␀␀␀␀␀␀␀␀␀␀␀␀␀100644 ␀  1647 ␀   144 ␀      14257  6061646072  11007␀ 0␀␀␀␀␀␀␀␀␀␀␀␀␀␀␀␀␀␀␀␀␀␀␀␀␀␀␀␀␀␀␀␀␀␀␀␀␀␀␀␀␀␀␀␀␀␀␀␀␀␀␀␀␀␀␀␀␀␀␀␀␀␀␀␀␀␀␀␀␀␀␀␀␀␀␀␀␀␀␀␀␀␀␀␀␀␀␀␀␀␀␀␀␀␀␀␀␀␀␀␀ustar  ␀cei␀␀␀␀␀␀␀␀␀␀␀␀␀␀␀␀␀␀␀␀␀␀␀␀␀␀␀␀␀users␀␀␀␀␀␀␀␀␀␀␀␀␀␀␀␀␀␀␀␀␀␀␀␀␀␀␀␀␀␀␀␀␀␀␀␀␀␀␀␀␀␀␀␀␀␀␀␀␀␀␀␀␀␀␀␀␀␀␀␀␀␀␀␀␀␀␀␀␀␀␀␀␀␀␀␀␀␀␀␀␀␀␀␀␀␀␀␀␀␀␀␀␀␀␀␀␀␀␀␀␀␀␀␀␀␀␀␀␀␀␀␀␀␀␀␀␀␀␀␀␀␀␀␀␀␀␀␀␀␀␀␀␀␀␀␀␀␀␀␀␀␀␀␀␀␀␀␀␀␀␀␀␀␀␀␀␀␀␀␀␀␀␀␀␀␀␀␀␀␀␀␀␀␀␀␀␀␀␀␀␀␀␀␀␀␀␀␀␀␀␀␀␀␀␀␀␀␀␀␀␀␀␀␀␀␀␀␀␀␀<HTML>
<HEAD>
<TITLE>CEI: Ecosystem Management</TITLE>
</HEAD>

<BODY BGCOLOR="FFFFFF">

<A NAME="top"></A>
<IMG SRC="ceiebb.gif" ALT="CEI Environmental Briefing Book" ALIGN=LEFT>
<BR>
<BR>
<BR>
<BR>
<BR>

<CENTER>
<H2>Ecosystem Management</H2>
</CENTER>

<P>Ecosystem management is the newest regulatory strategy advocated by
environmentalists to limit urban growth and preserve undeveloped land.  It
provides the most expansive justification for national land-use planning yet
devised.  Those who want to limit federal control over and regulation of
private land should oppose the implementation of ecosystem management.<p>
     The Endangered Species Act (ESA) currently allows federal regulation only when
a species is listed as threatened or endangered.  Then, regulations are allowed
only to protect the listed species and its habitat.  Advocates of ecosystem
management want to amend the ESA to enact a different approach. &#147;Instead
of focusing on individual species, we would do it on the basis of a whole
ecosystem,&#148; explains Interior Secretary Bruce Babbitt.  Yet ecosystems,
according to Babbitt, are &#147;in the eye of the beholder.&#148;  The goal of
preserving &#147;ecosystems&#148; in their entirety is thus a license to
regulate nearly anything the agency desires.  Because of the discretion that
would be granted to regulatory agencies, ecosystem management would entail an
increase in environmental regulation.<p>
     For example, consider the application of ecosystem management to the
protection of the coastal California gnatcatcher, a small songbird in southern
California.  There are approximately 250 gnatcatcher pairs in Riverside County.
Because each pair of gnatcatchers requires less than 20 acres of habitat,
current endangered species regulations would control around 5,000 acres of
land.  However, under ecosystem management, which focuses on types of habitat
rather than specific species, protection of the gnatcatcher would entail
federal control of nearly 150,000 acres.  Under the Interior Department&#146;s
model, ecosystem management will lock almost 30 times more land!<p>
     One tool for the implementation of ecosystem management is the proposed
National Biological Survey (NBS).  This agency would be responsible for
cataloging all species of flora and fauna in the United States, and it would
provide the federal government with a blueprint for nationwide land-use
regulation.  For this reason, the NBS is extremely controversial in Congress.
When proposed in 1993, Congress voted overwhelmingly to restrain the NBS from
infringing upon the rights of property owners.  Because it remains
controversial, the NBS has yet to be authorized by Congress.  However, despite
Congressional rules prohibiting appropriations that have not been authorized,
the NBS is up and running in the Interior Department nonetheless.<p>
     Ecosystem management will not enhance the position of private property owners,
as some claim.  Rather it will greatly worsen their already precarious state.
The loss of the use of private property without compensation is the primary
problem with the current species-by-species approach; but the ecosystem
approach promises that property owners will lose even more of their land.
Rather than solving the conflict over species protection, ecosystem management
will only worsen it.  <p>
<p>
Q: <i>Isn&#146;t the protection of ecosystems the goal of the Endangered
Species Act?</i><p>
<p>
A: No.  The goal of the ESA is to &#147;recover&#148; listed species to the
point at which the ESA&#146;s protections are no longer required.  Species are
listed under the ESA, ecosystems are not.  Only species can trigger the
Act&#146;s stringent land-use regulations.  There is only one mention of
&#147;ecosystems&#148; in the ESA, and only because it is thought that losing
species is tantamount to losing parts of and thus impairing ecosystems.  We
have no Endangered Ecosystems Act. <p>
<p>
<p>
Q: <i>Secretary Babbitt argues that managing ecosystems will prevent species
from becoming threatened or endangered in the first place.  Won&#146;t that
avoid the strict land-use regulations imposed by the Endangered Species
Act?</i><p>
<p>
A: No.  Under current law, the federal government cannot regulate private
land-use unless a species is listed under the Act and present on the property.
To allow the government to regulate ecosystems to prevent species from becoming
threatened in the first place is an open invitation to regulation of private
land-uses and the problems that it creates, including the creation of barriers
to private conservation and disincentives to preserve and protect wildlife.<p>
<p>
<p>
Q: <i>Is not destruction of vital habitat the greatest threat to endangered
species?</i><p>
<p>
A: Habitation alteration is certainly responsible for the decline of some
species.  With this in mind it is important to recognize that the ESA often
encourages the destruction of habitat because land that is declared habitat by
the federal government cannot be used by its owner.  This creates an incentive
for landowners to destroy habitat, lest it be classified as the home of an
endangered species and placed off limits for productive use.  Such negative
incentives are some of the primary causes of the ESA&#146;s ineffectiveness in
saving species.<p>
<p>
<p>
Q: <i>Wildlife is a public resource.  As such, should not landowners be
prohibited from harming the public&#146;s wildlife habitat?</i><p>
<p>
A: Wildlife may be public, but most wildlife habitat is private.  Instead of
foisting the cost on individual property owners and punishing them for using
their own land, the public as a whole should pay for public goods like wildlife
protection.  We do not force urbanites to solve the homeless problem by giving
up rooms in their home; why should we force rural-dwellers to give up their
property without compensation to provide wildlife habitat?  It is a perverse
morality that gives more rights to imperiled wildlife than to imperiled people.
<p>


<BR>
