␀␀␀␀␀␀␀␀␀␀␀␀␀␀␀␀␀␀␀␀␀␀␀␀␀␀␀␀␀␀␀␀␀␀␀␀␀␀␀␀␀␀␀␀␀␀␀␀␀␀␀␀␀␀␀␀␀␀␀␀␀␀␀␀␀␀␀␀␀␀␀␀␀␀␀␀␀␀␀␀␀␀␀␀␀␀␀␀␀␀␀␀␀␀␀␀␀␀␀␀␀␀␀␀␀␀␀␀␀␀␀␀␀␀␀␀␀␀␀␀␀␀␀␀␀␀␀␀␀␀␀␀␀␀␀␀␀␀␀␀␀␀␀␀␀␀␀␀␀␀␀␀␀␀␀␀␀␀␀␀␀␀␀␀␀␀␀␀␀␀␀␀␀␀␀␀␀␀␀␀␀␀␀␀␀␀␀␀␀␀␀␀␀␀␀␀␀␀␀␀␀␀␀␀␀␀␀␀␀␀␀␀␀␀␀␀␀␀␀␀␀␀␀␀␀␀␀␀␀␀␀␀␀␀␀␀␀␀␀␀␀␀␀␀␀␀␀␀␀␀␀␀␀␀␀␀␀␀␀␀␀␀␀␀␀␀␀␀␀␀␀␀␀␀␀␀␀␀␀␀␀␀␀␀␀␀␀␀␀␀␀␀␀␀␀␀␀␀␀␀␀␀␀␀␀␀␀␀␀␀␀␀␀␀␀␀␀␀␀␀␀␀␀␀␀␀␀␀␀␀␀␀␀␀␀␀␀ebb7.html␀␀␀␀␀␀␀␀␀␀␀␀␀␀␀␀␀␀␀␀␀␀␀␀␀␀␀␀␀␀␀␀␀␀␀␀␀␀␀␀␀␀␀␀␀␀␀␀␀␀␀␀␀␀␀␀␀␀␀␀␀␀␀␀␀␀␀␀␀␀␀␀␀␀␀␀␀␀␀␀␀␀␀␀␀␀␀␀␀␀␀100644 ␀  1647 ␀   144 ␀      13364  6061646101  10777␀ 0␀␀␀␀␀␀␀␀␀␀␀␀␀␀␀␀␀␀␀␀␀␀␀␀␀␀␀␀␀␀␀␀␀␀␀␀␀␀␀␀␀␀␀␀␀␀␀␀␀␀␀␀␀␀␀␀␀␀␀␀␀␀␀␀␀␀␀␀␀␀␀␀␀␀␀␀␀␀␀␀␀␀␀␀␀␀␀␀␀␀␀␀␀␀␀␀␀␀␀␀ustar  ␀cei␀␀␀␀␀␀␀␀␀␀␀␀␀␀␀␀␀␀␀␀␀␀␀␀␀␀␀␀␀users␀␀␀␀␀␀␀␀␀␀␀␀␀␀␀␀␀␀␀␀␀␀␀␀␀␀␀␀␀␀␀␀␀␀␀␀␀␀␀␀␀␀␀␀␀␀␀␀␀␀␀␀␀␀␀␀␀␀␀␀␀␀␀␀␀␀␀␀␀␀␀␀␀␀␀␀␀␀␀␀␀␀␀␀␀␀␀␀␀␀␀␀␀␀␀␀␀␀␀␀␀␀␀␀␀␀␀␀␀␀␀␀␀␀␀␀␀␀␀␀␀␀␀␀␀␀␀␀␀␀␀␀␀␀␀␀␀␀␀␀␀␀␀␀␀␀␀␀␀␀␀␀␀␀␀␀␀␀␀␀␀␀␀␀␀␀␀␀␀␀␀␀␀␀␀␀␀␀␀␀␀␀␀␀␀␀␀␀␀␀␀␀␀␀␀␀␀␀␀␀␀␀␀␀␀␀␀␀␀␀<HTML>
<HEAD>
<TITLE>CEI: Electricity Competition</TITLE>
</HEAD>

<BODY BGCOLOR="FFFFFF">

<A NAME="top"></A>
<IMG SRC="ceiebb.gif" ALT="CEI Environmental Briefing Book" ALIGN=LEFT>
<BR>
<BR>
<BR>
<BR>
<BR>

<CENTER>
<H2>Electricity Competition</H2>
</CENTER>

<P>
The nation&#146;s electricity system is currently dominated by local,
regulated monopolies.  This should change.  There is an &#147;electricity
superhighway&#148; which links utility customers with hundreds of power
producers.   Consumers should have direct access to this network.  This would
enable consumers to pick electric utilities the way they can now pick long
distance telephone service.   Moreover, consumers would no longer be forced to
subsidize wasteful utility &#147;conservation&#148; programs that benefit some
utility consumers at the expense of others.  States have the authority to allow
for direct consumer access within their borders.  However, national competition
in electricity markets cannot occur without explicit Congressional
authorization.<p>
     Utilities already have access to the &#147;electricity superhighway.&#148;
Because most utilities have been granted a local monopoly by government, they
can charge what are often exorbitant rates and deny their patrons access to the
wholesale electricity market, in which power is traded at prices as much as 75
percent less than that paid by retail ratepayers. Giving consumers access to
the wholesale electricity market would reduce rates dramatically, saving
homeowners and businesses hundreds of billions of dollars and eliminating the
need for a cumbersome regulatory bureaucracy to oversee the industry.<p>
     The wholesale electricity market, which has existed in limited form since the
1920s, is made possible by a national network of transmission lines connecting
utilities, wholesale electricity producers, and utility customers to one
another. Power producers use the system to trade electricity with one another
in a diverse and vibrant wholesale market, free of the cost-of-service
regulation imposed on retail consumers. Allowing utility customers to use the
system would liberate them from regulation and give them the same market
options their utilities enjoy.<p>
     Unfortunately, some environmental groups have joined utilities in opposing
reform of the electricity system. Environmental lobbyists are seeking to
preserve Demand-Side Management (DSM) programs administered by the utilities.
Through DSM programs, utilities increase their rates in order to pay for energy
conservation programs that only benefit a select portion of ratepayers.  State
regulators give privately-owned utilities various incentives to administer the
programs. Ratepayers are often entirely unaware of the existence of this
scheme, which costs them billions annually. <p>
     A competitive electricity system would render inefficient energy conservation
programs obsolete.  Conservation investments that could not pay for themselves
through increased efficiency would be jettisoned as utilities would be forced
to compete for customers by offering lower prices.  The result would be
dramatic savings for consumers and increased efficiency within the electricity
industry.<p>
<p>
<p>
<p>
Q: <i>Why should we abandon a proven system of public oversight and regulation
of electric utility monopolies in favor of the uncertainties of a competitive
system?</i><p>
<p>
A: Competition has repeatedly proven itself superior to government regulation.
Only in a free market will producers have incentives to satisfy the demands of
a varied clientele. The current system of command-and-control regulation of
utility monopolies reduces consumer choice, and virtually eliminates incentives
for electricity producers to innovate and cut costs. In a free market,
producers would be immediately accountable to power consumers, who would have
the option to switch providers if the current one proves unsatisfactory.<p>
<p>
<p>
Q:<i> How much would competition in electricity markets reduce prices for
consumers?</i><p>
<p>
A: The consumer savings from electricity competition would vary from community
to community.  In some parts of the country, electric rates would decline by as
much as 50 percent, or more.  Nationwide, the consumer savings from electricity
competition are expected to be $200 to $300 billion.<p>
<p>
<p>
Q: <i>If direct access eliminates DSM programs, will it be bad for the
environment? </i><p>
<p>
A: Efficiency is a friend of the environment.  By encouraging greater
efficiency within the electricity industry, competition will also spur
utilities to develop innovative new methods of electricity generation that
produce more energy by using fewer resources, thereby lessening much of the
environmental impact of electricity generation.<p>
<p>
<p>
Q: <i>Aren&#146;t DSM programs simply an efficient alternative to building new
power plants?</i><p>
<i></i><p>
A: Proponents of DSM often argue that utilities should compare the cost of
constructing new power plants to the cost of avoiding the construction of a new
plant by reducing their customers&#146; electricity demand. If the latter is
less expensive, then clearly it is the optimal choice.  Unfortunately, DSM
programs are no longer used as a less-expensive alternative to power plant
construction.  Rather than reduce electricity rates for all consumers, DSM
programs apply a &#147;surcharge&#148; to rates, raising them to pay for
energy-efficiency subsidies. DSM is not a lower-cost alternative to power plant
construction&#151;it is a system of taxation and redistribution.<p>


<BR>
