␀␀␀␀␀␀␀␀␀␀␀␀␀␀␀␀␀␀␀␀␀␀␀␀␀␀␀␀␀␀␀␀␀␀␀␀␀␀␀␀␀␀␀␀␀␀␀␀␀␀␀␀␀␀␀␀␀␀␀␀␀␀␀␀␀␀␀␀␀␀␀␀␀␀␀␀␀␀␀␀␀␀␀␀␀␀␀␀␀␀␀␀␀␀␀␀␀␀␀␀␀␀␀␀␀␀␀␀␀␀␀␀␀␀␀␀␀␀␀␀␀␀␀␀␀␀␀␀␀␀␀␀␀␀␀␀␀␀␀␀␀␀␀␀␀␀␀␀␀␀␀␀␀␀␀␀␀␀␀␀␀␀␀␀␀␀␀␀␀␀␀␀␀␀␀␀␀␀␀␀␀␀␀␀␀␀␀␀␀␀␀␀␀␀␀␀␀␀␀␀␀␀␀␀␀␀␀␀␀␀␀␀␀␀␀␀␀␀␀␀␀␀␀␀␀␀␀␀␀␀␀␀␀␀␀␀␀␀␀␀␀␀␀␀␀␀␀␀␀␀␀␀␀␀␀␀␀␀␀␀␀␀␀␀␀␀␀␀ebb8.html␀␀␀␀␀␀␀␀␀␀␀␀␀␀␀␀␀␀␀␀␀␀␀␀␀␀␀␀␀␀␀␀␀␀␀␀␀␀␀␀␀␀␀␀␀␀␀␀␀␀␀␀␀␀␀␀␀␀␀␀␀␀␀␀␀␀␀␀␀␀␀␀␀␀␀␀␀␀␀␀␀␀␀␀␀␀␀␀␀␀␀100644 ␀  1647 ␀   144 ␀      16306  6061646111  11000␀ 0␀␀␀␀␀␀␀␀␀␀␀␀␀␀␀␀␀␀␀␀␀␀␀␀␀␀␀␀␀␀␀␀␀␀␀␀␀␀␀␀␀␀␀␀␀␀␀␀␀␀␀␀␀␀␀␀␀␀␀␀␀␀␀␀␀␀␀␀␀␀␀␀␀␀␀␀␀␀␀␀␀␀␀␀␀␀␀␀␀␀␀␀␀␀␀␀␀␀␀␀ustar  ␀cei␀␀␀␀␀␀␀␀␀␀␀␀␀␀␀␀␀␀␀␀␀␀␀␀␀␀␀␀␀users␀␀␀␀␀␀␀␀␀␀␀␀␀␀␀␀␀␀␀␀␀␀␀␀␀␀␀␀␀␀␀␀␀␀␀␀␀␀␀␀␀␀␀␀␀␀␀␀␀␀␀␀␀␀␀␀␀␀␀␀␀␀␀␀␀␀␀␀␀␀␀␀␀␀␀␀␀␀␀␀␀␀␀␀␀␀␀␀␀␀␀␀␀␀␀␀␀␀␀␀␀␀␀␀␀␀␀␀␀␀␀␀␀␀␀␀␀␀␀␀␀␀␀␀␀␀␀␀␀␀␀␀␀␀␀␀␀␀␀␀␀␀␀␀␀␀␀␀␀␀␀␀␀␀␀␀␀␀␀␀␀␀␀␀␀␀␀␀␀␀␀␀␀␀␀␀␀␀␀␀␀␀␀␀␀␀␀␀␀␀␀␀␀␀␀␀␀␀␀␀␀␀␀␀␀␀␀␀␀␀<HTML>
<HEAD>
<TITLE>CEI: Endangered Species Act (ESA)</TITLE>
</HEAD>

<BODY BGCOLOR="FFFFFF">

<A NAME="top"></A>
<IMG SRC="ceiebb.gif" ALT="CEI Environmental Briefing Book" ALIGN=LEFT>
<BR>
<BR>
<BR>
<BR>
<BR>

<CENTER>
<H2>Endangered Species Act (ESA)</H2>
</CENTER>

<P>The Endangered Species Act (ESA), designed to protect all manner of animal and
plant species in the United States, is one of the most controversial of all
environmental laws.  The ESA deprives property owners of the productive use of
their property throughout the country.  If species protection benefits all of
us, then we should be willing to compensate those landowners whose land is
effectively taken to protect endangered species.  The ESA has failed to do this
thus far.  The ESA has also failed to achieve its goal of recovering endangered
species.  The ESA is in need of dramatic reform.<p>
     Enacted in 1973, the ESA sought to prevent people from &#147;taking&#148;
members of species listed as endangered or threatened.  Throughout the history
of American wildlife law, &#147;taking&#148; an animal meant to physically
injure or kill it.  That changed however, when the Fish and Wildlife Service
(the Interior Department agency primarily responsible for administering the
Act) expanded the meaning of &#147;take&#148; in 1975 to prohibit ordinary land
uses that merely modified unoccupied habitat.  As a result, landowners from
coast-to-coast have been prevented from using their land.  In Travis County,
Texas, for example, small property owners have been prevented from building
homes for their retirement.<p>
     In March 1994, the second-highest court in the land said that such actions by
the federal government are illegal because they were never authorized by
Congress.  In the case of <i>Sweet Home v. Babbitt</i>, the court recognized
that Congress did not intend the ESA to apply so broadly on private property.
The decision is now under appeal.  In the meantime, Congress should make its
intentions clear by reforming the ESA to ensure that the Act is no longer used
to turn private property into public wildlife refuges without paying the
landowner just compensation.<p>
     The ESA is a clear failure when evaluated on its environmental impact.  The
ESA&#146;s objective is to recover imperiled species to the point that the
ESA&#146;s regulations are no longer needed and the species can be removed from
the endangered species list.  This rarely happens.  Only seven out of over 850
listed species have been recovered, according to the federal government.  The
same number of species has become extinct under the ESA&#146;s protection.
This is hardly a good track record.  Moreover it is doubtful in most of these
cases whether the ESA can take credit for the recoveries.<p>
     What many fail to realize is that the ESA actually creates incentives
<i>against</i> the protection of endangered species by private landowners.
Indeed, under the ESA, it is in a landowner&#146;s self-interest to destroy
habitat before it is identified and regulated by the federal government.  In
parts of the country, the advice given to individuals who are afraid that they
will lose their land due to endangered species is simply &#147;shoot, shovel,
and shut up.&#148;  This is a terrible incentive structure for a law designed
to protect endangered species. <p>
     The ESA is broken and needs to be fixed.  Most importantly, the ESA needs to
be more respectful of the rights of private landowners.  Landowners should be
compensated when they lose the productive use of their land.  For the ESA to be
more effective, it also needs to rely more upon private conservation efforts
and the power of the marketplace.  Private conservation efforts have been
instrumental in the resurgence of many species, from the wood duck to the
buffalo.  One useful reform would be to make it easier for landowners and
conservation organizations to protect, breed and care for imperiled species.
Until such steps are taken, the ESA will continue to be highly controversial,
and scarcely effective.<p>
<p>
<p>
Q: <i>A recent  </i>Times-Mirror<i> poll found that most Americans support the
ESA. Why should it be reformed?</i><p>
<p>
A: Americans care about wildlife, and so they support government efforts to
protect  endangered species.  However, Americans also believe in property
rights.  That same <i>Times Mirror</i> poll found that 59 percent of Americans
believe landowners should be compensated when they lose the productive use of
their land due to the ESA.  For federal wildlife protection to truly reflect
the will of the American people, it must include a greater protection of
property rights than it does right now.<p>
<p>
<p>
Q: <i>Earlier this year the federal government down-listed the bald eagle from
&#147;endangered&#148; to &#147;threatened&#148; status.  Is this evidence of
the ESA&#146;s success in protecting species?</i><p>
<p>
A: No.  Most ecologists believe the greatest threat to the bald eagle was from
the pesticide DDT.  DDT was banned in this country in 1972, before the ESA was
even passed.  Moreover, harming bald eagles was prohibited decades earlier
under the Eagle Protection Act.  We should be happy that our national symbol,
the bald eagle, is thriving once again in this country.  However, it is not
appropriate to credit the ESA with that success.<p>
<p>
<p>
Q: <i>Some groups implicated Endangered Species Act regulations in the spread
of fires in California last year that burned thousands of acres and destroyed
numerous homes.  Others say it&#146;s not true.  What really happened?</i><p>
<p>
A: When wildfire rips through a community it is impossible to know what
measures could have protected homes and properties that were destroyed.
However, fire experts recognize that some measures, such as &#147;disking&#148;
a fire break by turning the land over with a plow, dramatically reduce the
threat of fire.  Under the ESA, the federal government prevented property
owners in Riverside County, CA from taking such protective measures because of
fear that clearing fire breaks would disturb the habitat of the Stephen&#146;s
Kangaroo Rat.  29 homes were destroyed by the fires.  One landowner who cleared
a fire break in violation of the law saved his home.  So it is likely that the
ESA played some role in the spread of the fire and the loss of homes.<p>
<p>
<p>
Q: <i>Since less than one percent of all projects reviewed under the ESA have
been halted, isn&#146;t the Act much more flexible than its critics
claim?</i><p>
<p>
A: This statistic only pertains to federal projects.  The impact on private
projects has never been reviewed.  More importantly, project approval is no
indication of flexibility, particularly when onerous conditions are attached.
For example, the FWS &#147;approved&#148; a 1,000 acre development project near
golden-cheeked warbler habitat, on the condition that the developer give up 765
acres of its land <i>and</i> purchase an additional 873 acres for a government
warbler preserve.  This is not flexibility, it is extortion.<p>



<BR>
