␀␀␀␀␀␀␀␀␀␀␀␀␀␀␀␀␀␀␀␀␀␀␀␀␀␀␀␀␀␀␀␀␀␀␀␀␀␀␀␀␀␀␀␀␀␀␀␀␀␀␀␀␀␀␀␀␀␀␀␀␀␀␀␀␀␀␀␀␀␀␀␀␀␀␀␀␀␀␀␀␀␀␀␀␀␀␀␀␀␀␀␀␀␀␀␀␀␀␀␀␀␀␀␀␀␀␀␀␀␀␀␀␀␀␀␀␀␀␀␀␀␀␀␀␀␀␀␀␀␀␀␀␀␀␀␀␀␀␀␀␀␀␀␀␀␀␀␀␀␀␀␀␀␀␀␀␀␀␀␀␀␀␀␀␀␀␀␀␀␀␀␀␀␀␀␀␀␀␀␀␀␀␀␀␀␀␀␀␀␀␀␀␀␀␀␀␀␀␀␀␀␀␀␀␀␀␀␀␀␀␀␀␀␀␀␀␀␀␀␀␀␀␀␀␀␀␀␀␀␀␀␀␀␀␀␀␀␀␀␀␀␀␀␀␀␀␀␀␀␀␀␀␀␀␀␀␀␀␀␀␀␀␀␀␀␀␀␀␀␀␀␀␀␀␀␀␀␀␀␀␀␀␀␀␀␀␀␀␀␀␀␀␀␀␀␀␀␀␀␀␀␀␀␀␀␀␀␀␀␀␀␀␀␀ebb9.html␀␀␀␀␀␀␀␀␀␀␀␀␀␀␀␀␀␀␀␀␀␀␀␀␀␀␀␀␀␀␀␀␀␀␀␀␀␀␀␀␀␀␀␀␀␀␀␀␀␀␀␀␀␀␀␀␀␀␀␀␀␀␀␀␀␀␀␀␀␀␀␀␀␀␀␀␀␀␀␀␀␀␀␀␀␀␀␀␀␀␀100644 ␀  1647 ␀   144 ␀      14124  6061646130  10776␀ 0␀␀␀␀␀␀␀␀␀␀␀␀␀␀␀␀␀␀␀␀␀␀␀␀␀␀␀␀␀␀␀␀␀␀␀␀␀␀␀␀␀␀␀␀␀␀␀␀␀␀␀␀␀␀␀␀␀␀␀␀␀␀␀␀␀␀␀␀␀␀␀␀␀␀␀␀␀␀␀␀␀␀␀␀␀␀␀␀␀␀␀␀␀␀␀␀␀␀␀␀ustar  ␀cei␀␀␀␀␀␀␀␀␀␀␀␀␀␀␀␀␀␀␀␀␀␀␀␀␀␀␀␀␀users␀␀␀␀␀␀␀␀␀␀␀␀␀␀␀␀␀␀␀␀␀␀␀␀␀␀␀␀␀␀␀␀␀␀␀␀␀␀␀␀␀␀␀␀␀␀␀␀␀␀␀␀␀␀␀␀␀␀␀␀␀␀␀␀␀␀␀␀␀␀␀␀␀␀␀␀␀␀␀␀␀␀␀␀␀␀␀␀␀␀␀␀␀␀␀␀␀␀␀␀␀␀␀␀␀␀␀␀␀␀␀␀␀␀␀␀␀␀␀␀␀␀␀␀␀␀␀␀␀␀␀␀␀␀␀␀␀␀␀␀␀␀␀␀␀␀␀␀␀␀␀␀␀␀␀␀␀␀␀␀␀␀␀␀␀␀␀␀␀␀␀␀␀␀␀␀␀␀␀␀␀␀␀␀␀␀␀␀␀␀␀␀␀␀␀␀␀␀␀␀␀␀␀␀␀␀␀␀␀␀<HTML>
<HEAD>
<TITLE>CEI: Energy Taxes</TITLE>
</HEAD>

<BODY BGCOLOR="FFFFFF">

<A NAME="top"></A>
<IMG SRC="ceiebb.gif" ALT="CEI Environmental Briefing Book" ALIGN=LEFT>
<BR>
<BR>
<BR>
<BR>
<BR>

<CENTER>
<H2>Energy Taxes</H2>
</CENTER>

<P>Congress should not impose an energy tax of any kind.  Neither a broad-based
energy tax, such as the &#147;Btu tax&#148; or carbon tax, nor an increased
gasoline tax should be used for deficit reduction or environmental protection.
Taxing energy would have a severe negative impact on the economy and produce no
significant environmental improvements.<p>
     Energy taxes would weaken U.S. industry and destroy jobs.  America enjoys an
abundance of energy sources, and as a result the U.S. economy abounds with
energy-intensive industries, from petrochemicals to timber.  Taxing energy will
hurt these industries and compromise America&#146;s competitiveness.  In 1992,
Pittsburgh&#146;s CONSAD Research Corporation estimated that a proposed carbon
tax would destroy 600,000 jobs over an 8-year period.  Other studies have
confirmed that imposing a tax on energy would have dire economic
consequences.<p>
     Moreover, a tax on energy would increase consumer prices and have a general
inflationary effect.  Taxing energy would increase the costs of producing raw
materials and transporting goods, in addition to the costs of heating and
maintaining family homes.  This economic impact would be felt by every
American, particularly the least fortunate.  Energy taxes and other policies
that raise prices are especially burdensome to people with fixed incomes.
Also, fuel taxes tend to hit hardest motorists in low-density rural areas
&#151; areas least affected by pollution.<p>
     Some claim that higher energy taxes, by restricting consumption, will promote
efficiency and protect the environment.  These claims are false.<p>
     Raising the price of energy would certainly reduce energy consumption.
However, energy <i>conservation</i> &#151; using less energy &#151; is not
necessarily the same as energy <i>efficiency</i> &#151; using less energy to
produce the same or higher level of goods.  Energy is used, after all, for a
purpose.  If that purpose is valuable, then taxing energy will just hinder the
production of valuable goods and services.<p>
     Energy taxes may of course impel businesses to adopt new technologies and so
become more energy-efficient.  But <i>energy</i> efficiency is not necessarily
the same as <i>economic</i> efficiency.  The investments businesses make in
response to energy taxes represent resources that cannot be used to develop new
products, raise wages, create jobs, or make other, more urgently-needed
efficiency enhancements.  Attempts by government to force businesses to
&#147;save&#148; energy are inherently wasteful.<p>
     Energy taxes are at best a crude and unreliable method of curbing pollution.
Energy use is not a reliable indicator of pollution created.  For example, two
different automobiles will produce different levels of emissions from the same
amount of gasoline.  Taxing energy is not the same thing as taxing pollution.<p>
<p>
Q: <i> Isn&#146;t it true that Europeans pay much higher gas taxes than
Americans?</i><p>
<p>
A:  Yes, but Europe also has a higher population density and few wide-open
expanses equivalent to those spanning the American West.  Hauling goods from
Frankfurt to Berlin is hardly the same as from St. Louis to Seattle.  The U.S.
transports over 3.7 trillion ton-kilometers of inland freight annually.  This
is more than ten times the amount shipped in Germany and over five times that
transported in the United Kingdom, Italy, France, Spain, Belgium and Denmark
combined.  European-level gas taxes would be economically ruinous in the United
States.<p>
<p>
<p>
Q:  <i>The U.S. contains only 5 percent of the world&#146;s population, yet
accounts for approximately 25 percent of energy use.  Moreover, America uses 10
percent to 25 percent more energy per unit of output than many other industrial
nations.  Doesn&#146;t this mean the U.S. is energy inefficient?</i><p>
<p>
A:  Several factors make it reasonable for Americans to use more energy than
people in Western Europe and Japan.  America has more abundant energy
resources, so energy tends to be less expensive here.  America has a lower
population density, so we must consume more energy for transportation.
Americans have 50 percent  to 80 percent more living space, per capita, than do
Europeans, and 250 percent more than do the Japanese.  Larger domiciles require
more energy to heat and cool.  More living space also means larger household
appliances such as refrigerators and washing machines.  Europeans and Japanese
use significantly more energy than do Africans and Latin Americans.  Does this
make Europe and Japan energy inefficient?  To enjoy the benefits of economic
progress and prosperity is not necessarily to &#147;waste&#148; energy.<p>
<i></i><p>
<i></i>Q:<i>  Won&#146;t energy taxes help prevent the depletion of fossil
fuels?</i><p>
<i></i><p>
A:  We&#146;re in no danger of running out of fossil fuels.  Political pundits
and policy analysts have predicted impending energy shortages for years, yet
these projections have never come true.  For example, in 1970 the International
Energy Agency claimed that the world&#146;s proven oil reserves of 645 billion
barrels would be depleted in the mid-1980s, yet by 1990 world oil reserves had
actually increased to 1 trillion barrels.  Proven oil reserves are more a
function of market prices and extraction technologies than they are of actual
underground supplies.  As knowledge increases, so do proven reserves.  The most
recent estimates place the world&#146;s oil supply at several hundred years.
Energy taxes, by discouraging consumption without augmenting the profit margins
of energy producers, actually discourage the exploration and recovery of fossil
fuels.    <p>



<BR>
