<A NAME="top"></A>

<H1>ENVIRONMENTAL STUDIES PROGRAM</H1>
<A HREF="adler.html">Jonathan Adler, Director</A>
</CENTER>
<BR>
<BR>
<BR>


<P>Instead of relying on the political process to give sustained, long term
attention to environmental protection, <A HREF="/cei.html">CEI</A> has developed and promoted an
alternative strategy called <A HREF="/fme.html">free market environmentalism</A>.  CEI contends that
where individual property rights exist in environmental resources, the
environment is most likely to be protected.  After all, most of the
world's environmental problems exist in those areas where common ownership
of government management is the norm.  A free market environmental program
would allow individuals to advance environmental goals as effectively as free
markets permit individuals to advance economic goals.  The policies that flow
from this approach -- privatization, targeted liability rules, sound scientific
inquiry, reduced reliance on political regulation -- are very different from
those now being sought by environmental activists.  They are, however, far more
likely to prove effective.  <p>

<p>
CEI's Environmental Studies Program includes both an overall effort to
reframe the environmental debate and a series of targeted projects to reform
specific policies.  Only a comprehensive vision of market-oriented
environmental policies will engender the support needed to reform current
policies.  That framework must then be developed in detail for specific
environmental initiatives.<p>
<p>
As the leading proponent of free market environmentalism, the Competitive
Enterprise Institute continues to challenge the conventional wisdom of the
environmental movement and aggressively promotes free market environmentalism
as a more effective strategy for attaining our nation's environmental
goals.  CEI has fostered and coordinated the development of a network of public
policy organizations around the country and across the globe.  CEI has
positioned itself to take a stronger role in both domestic and international
debates over environmental policies in the 1990s.<p>

<p>
Specifically, CEI works on the vast array of particular environmental issues, including:

<UL>
<LI><A HREF="/ebb.cafe2.html">Automobile Fuel Economy Standards</A>
<LI><A HREF="/topic.html#biodiversity">Biodiversity & Wildlife Conservation</A>
<LI><A HREF="/ebb/biotech2.html">Biotechnology</A>
<LI><A HREF="/tru5.html">Carcinogens</A>
<LI><A HREF="/cfcsum.html">CFC Phaseout</A>
<LI><A HREF="/ebb/cleanair.html">Clean Air Act</A>
<LI><A HREF="/ebb/cleanh2o.html">Clean Water Act</A>
<LI><A HREF="/bate.html">Contingent Valuation</A>
<LI><A HREF="/dsm.html">Demand-Side Management</A>
<LI><A HREF="/ebb/ecomgmt.html">Ecosystem Management</A>
<LI><A HREF="/ebb/electric.html">Electricity Competition</A>
<LI><A HREF="/ebb/esa.html">Endangered Species Act</A>
<LI><A HREF="/ebb/energy.html">Energy Taxes</A>
<LI><A HREF="/ebb/fornaid.html">Environmental Foreign Aid</A>
<LI><A HREF="/agpaper.html">Federal Agricultural Policy</A>
<LI><A HREF="/topic.html#lands">Federal Lands</A>
<LI><A HREF="/tru6.html">Forests</A>
<LI><A HREF="/tru10.html">Global Air Quality</A>
