<HEAD>
<TITLE>CEI: Ike C. Sugg</TITLE>
</HEAD>

<BODY BGCOLOR="FFFFFF">

<A NAME="top"></A>

<BR>
<BR>
<CENTER>
<H1>Ike C. Sugg</H1>
</CENTER>

<BR>
<BR>

<P>Ike C. Sugg is the Fellow in Wildlife and Land-Use Policy at the
Competitive Enterprise Institute, a free market research and advocacy
organization headquartered in Washington, D.C.  CEI emphasizes the marketing
and implementation of classical liberal ideals and believes limited government
and competition best serve the public interest.

<P>At CEI, Mr. Sugg works on wildlife and land use issues, focusing both on
the failures of governmental programs and the successes of private conservation
efforts.  Through intensive research, writing and speaking, Mr. Sugg seeks to
heighten public awareness of how government abuses private property owners and
mismanages natural resources.  By showing how private property rights and
economic incentives can work for natural resource conservation, rather than
against it, his work is aimed at reforming failing public policies (both here
and abroad) and fostering greater appreciation for the ethical and conservation
values of human liberty. 

<P>Mr. Sugg has presented his views before Congress, the President&#146;s
Council on Environmental Quality, the Convention on International Trade in
Endangered Species, National Public Radio, CNBC, C-SPAN and other fora.  Some
of his recent writings include a chapter in the book <i>Elephants and Whales:
Resources for Whom?</i> (Gordon and Breach Science Publishers, UK: 1995);
<i>Elephants and Ivory: Lessons from the Trade Ban</i> (IEA Studies on the
Environment No. 2, UK: Nov. 1994); <i>Defining &#145;Harm&#146; to Wildlife</i>
(The National Law Journal, vol. 16, no. 42; June 1994); <i>Caught in the Act:
Evaluating the Endangered Species Act, Its Effects on Man and Prospects for
Reform</i> (Cumberland Law Review, vol. 24:1, 1993-1994); <i>California Fires
-- Losing Houses, Saving Rats</i> (The Wall Street Journal, November 10, 1993
[which sparked ABC News program 20/20&#146;s breakthrough coverage of that
disaster]); and numerous other articles in <i>The Wall Street Journal, The
Washington Times, National Review</i> and <i>The American Spectator,</i> among
others.

<P>CEI is supported solely by donations from foundations, corporations, and
individuals; it accepts no government funds and does not perform contractual
work.<P>

<BR>
