</BODY>
</HTML>
␀␀␀␀␀␀␀␀␀␀␀␀␀␀␀␀␀␀␀␀␀␀␀␀␀␀␀␀␀␀␀␀␀␀␀␀␀marlo.html␀␀␀␀␀␀␀␀␀␀␀␀␀␀␀␀␀␀␀␀␀␀␀␀␀␀␀␀␀␀␀␀␀␀␀␀␀␀␀␀␀␀␀␀␀␀␀␀␀␀␀␀␀␀␀␀␀␀␀␀␀␀␀␀␀␀␀␀␀␀␀␀␀␀␀␀␀␀␀␀␀␀␀␀␀␀␀␀␀␀100644 ␀  1647 ␀   144 ␀       4252  6061646374  11262␀ 0␀␀␀␀␀␀␀␀␀␀␀␀␀␀␀␀␀␀␀␀␀␀␀␀␀␀␀␀␀␀␀␀␀␀␀␀␀␀␀␀␀␀␀␀␀␀␀␀␀␀␀␀␀␀␀␀␀␀␀␀␀␀␀␀␀␀␀␀␀␀␀␀␀␀␀␀␀␀␀␀␀␀␀␀␀␀␀␀␀␀␀␀␀␀␀␀␀␀␀␀ustar  ␀cei␀␀␀␀␀␀␀␀␀␀␀␀␀␀␀␀␀␀␀␀␀␀␀␀␀␀␀␀␀users␀␀␀␀␀␀␀␀␀␀␀␀␀␀␀␀␀␀␀␀␀␀␀␀␀␀␀␀␀␀␀␀␀␀␀␀␀␀␀␀␀␀␀␀␀␀␀␀␀␀␀␀␀␀␀␀␀␀␀␀␀␀␀␀␀␀␀␀␀␀␀␀␀␀␀␀␀␀␀␀␀␀␀␀␀␀␀␀␀␀␀␀␀␀␀␀␀␀␀␀␀␀␀␀␀␀␀␀␀␀␀␀␀␀␀␀␀␀␀␀␀␀␀␀␀␀␀␀␀␀␀␀␀␀␀␀␀␀␀␀␀␀␀␀␀␀␀␀␀␀␀␀␀␀␀␀␀␀␀␀␀␀␀␀␀␀␀␀␀␀␀␀␀␀␀␀␀␀␀␀␀␀␀␀␀␀␀␀␀␀␀␀␀␀␀␀␀␀␀␀␀␀␀␀␀␀␀␀␀␀<HTML>
<HEAD>
<TITLE>CEI: Marlo Lewis, Jr.</TITLE>
</HEAD>

<BODY BGCOLOR="FFFFFF">

<A NAME="top"></A>

<BR>
<BR>
<CENTER>
<H1>Marlo Lewis, Jr.</H1>
</CENTER>

<BR>
<BR>

<P>Marlo Lewis, Jr., is Executive Director of the Competitive Enterprise
Institute, a free market advocacy and research organization headquartered in
Washington, DC.  CEI emphasizes the marketing and implementation of classical
liberal ideals and believes limited government and competition best serve the
public interest.    <p>
<p>
Mr. Lewis, who holds a Ph.D. in Government from Harvard University, previously
served as Director of Research for the grassroots organization, Citizens
Against Government Waste. Before that he was staff consultant to the House
Foreign Affairs Subcommittee on Trade and International Economic Policy, policy
analyst with the U.S. State Department&#146;s Bureau of International
Organization Affairs and Bureau of Inter-American Affairs, and issues advisor
to the 1988 Alan Keyes for U.S. Senate campaign.  Mr. Lewis has also worked as
a Public Affairs Fellow at the Hoover Institution and as a professor of
political theory and American government at Claremont McKenna College and
Claremont Graduate School in California.<p>
<p>
His recent writings include; <i>Danger: Risky Business. Forty-Five Federal
Management Failures and other Accidents Waiting to Happen</i> (Citizens Against
Government Waste, September 1993), &#147;How Pork Promotes Fiscal Profligacy
and Debases Representative Government&#148; (Citizens Against Government Waste,
Issue Brief No. 7, August 1993), <i>Cutting Waste. Campaign &#146;92 Candidate
Handbook: Briefing Papers on the Fiscal Issues Most Important to American
Voters</i> (Citizens Against Government Waste, August 1992).  His latest work
advocates term limits for members of Congress in &#147;Term Limits and the
American Ruling Class&#148; (<i>Washington Times</i>, July 5, 1994).<p>
<p>
CEI is supported solely by donations from foundations, corporations, and
individuals; it accepts no government funds and does not perform contractual
work.<p>



<BR>
