<HEAD>
<TITLE>CEI: Medicare Monet</TITLE>
</HEAD>

<BODY BGCOLOR="FFFFFF">
<BR>

<CENTER>
<H1>Medicare Monet</H1>
by <A HREF="tom4.html">Tom Miller</A>
</CENTER>
<BR>
<BR>

<P>The early versions of Medicare reform plans by House and Senate Republicans
this September bore the imprint of political tacticians rather than policy
revolutionaries.  In the name of &#147;preserving, protecting, and
strengthening Medicare,&#148; congressional leaders were primarily scrambling
to maintain political momentum.  <p>
	In the short run, the focus on properly framing the message, effectively
communicating it, and outmaneuvering statist quo opponents earned high marks.
In the long run, Medicare as we knew it was already dead.  This year&#146;s
proposed life-support surgery, however, sidesteps more direct routes to
reducing the total fiscal and political cost of Medicare&#146;s final funeral.
The political operation might be a success, but the health status of the
patient (Medicare) remains terminal.   <p>
	At the beginning of this year, the &#147;policy&#148; case for radically
overhauling Medicare was overwhelming.  The entitlement program was fiscally
unsustainable on a long-range basis and suffered from an antiquated structure.
Most of all, any credible effort to restrain federal outlays and eventually
achieve a balanced budget required a slowdown of projected Medicare spending
growth.  <p>
	The &#147;political&#148; case for radical reform, however, was more
uncharted.  Republican candidates had said little or nothing about Medicare
overhaul during the 1994 campaign, but the arithmetic of 1995 budgetary
politics insisted upon it.  Congressional Republicans could not afford to end
the year without being able to claim some kind of &#147;victory&#148; on the
budgetary front.  To maintain their political momentum, they first had to come
to terms with Medicare.<p>
	House Republican leaders in particular decided to make a virtue of necessity
by focusing on the Medicare program&#146;s own solvency problems.  They
brilliantly convinced the American public that there was a Medicare fiscal
crisis requiring immediate attention.  By early September, congressional
Republicans had won the broad political debate that Medicare needed to be
&#147;saved.&#148;  With congressional Democrats remaining in deep denial, the
only reform plans in play were the ones offered by House Republicans and Senate
Republicans.  <p>
	Both the House and Senate plans chipped away at the traditional structure of
the Medicare program.  Their key reforms included provisions whereby
beneficiaries could opt out of the traditional Medicare program and purchase a
wide variety of private sector health care plans.  By breaking up
&#147;old&#148; Medicare&#146;s tight control of permissible benefits packages,
fee schedules, cost-sharing structures, and health care delivery systems, the
proposed reforms opened up greater competitive pressure to meet the true
preferences of the elderly.  The trade-off for this greater flexibility and
choice was the recognition that Medicare would become a &#147;capped&#148;
entitlement that had to live within explicit (but still generous) budget
limits.<p>
	The House and Senate plans also hoped to establish several key precedents that
might lead to more far-reaching reforms in the future.  The proposals
introduced limited versions of vouchers, cash rebates, and means testing.  They
allowed beneficiaries to voluntarily bypass price controls on health care
providers and helped begin Medicare&#146;s transition from a largely open-ended, defined benefit program
to a more controllable, defined contribution program.  They also would start to
erode the &#147;universal&#148; nature of Medicare, by permitting beneficiaries
to customize their benefits and recognizing that everyone over age 65 is not
entitled to the same level of taxpayer-financed subsidies.<p>
	The Senate plan was surprisingly bolder than the House version in seeking more
fundamental changes.  Senate Republicans proposed more extensive cash rebates
(75 percent of all savings) to beneficiaries who chose private health plan
alternatives that were less expensive than the budgeted allocation for
quasi-voucher payments.  House Republicans timidly limited the maximum rebate
to the annual charge for Medicare Part B premiums.  Senate Republicans made a
modest attempt at raising Part B deductibles.  House Republicans ducked the
entire issue for political reasons.  Senate Republicans also made a down
payment on long-term Medicare reform by phasing in hikes in the future
eligibility age for Medicare to age 67.  <p>
	Many details of the proposed reforms, however, remain problematic.  Both plans
continue to rely predominantly on top-down budgetary controls that will
discourage any net budget savings below the predetermined baselines.  Minimum
floors on benefit offerings set in both plans will tend to encourage upward
quality competition, rather than downward price competition.  When you blow
away the rhetorical smoke, both plans made their budget cuts the old-fashioned
way &#151; they disguised them and would let private sector providers take the
blame for delivering bad news.  <p>
	The largest &#147;savings&#148; came from that old standby &#151; reduced
payments to health care vendors.  The dubious premise was that beneficiaries
would be unaware of the effect of those cuts on the size and scope of benefits
they ultimately received.  The bulk of the remaining savings came from a modest
increase in Medicare Part B premiums &#151; essentially a tax increase posing
as higher user charges &#151; that would offset only part of the
taxpayer-financed subsidies for a government-administered service.  The
plans&#146; look-back sequester mechanism, aimed at ensuring fiscal savings in
budget &#147;out years,&#148; was a formulaic, expedient placeholder that
sidestepped tougher decisions.  Even if future political pressure did not
prevent the look-back triggers from being pulled, the fail-safe reliance on
relatively crude price controls for a number of health care sectors would
create new rounds of arbitrary and clumsy distortions in medical decision
making.  <p>
	Meanwhile, serious efforts to directly confront Medicare beneficiaries with
more substantial cost sharing were abandoned.  The limited means testing in
both plans was largely symbolic, set at too high a level, and mistakenly
imposed on premium subsidies instead of benefits.  <p>
	Both reform plans refused to challenge and, indeed, reinforced fundamental
elements of Medicare lore.  By vowing to &#147;save&#148; the Hospital
Insurance Trust Fund, they perpetuated the myths that such a trust fund holds
real assets and that beneficiaries &#147;earn&#148; their benefits through
previous payroll tax payments during their working years.  Anyone who reached
the age of 65 next year, for that reason alone, would continue to have a large
part of their health care bills paid with <i>other people&#146;s money</i>.
The limited objectives of congressional Republicans would still perpetuate the
Medicare entitlement as an intergenerational, tax and spend, redistribution
scheme, in a somewhat more efficient manner with increased autonomy for private
sector subcontractors.  <p>
	The voluntary options available under both plans would leave Medicare in an
unstable environment.  Frequent mismatches between an individual
beneficiary&#146;s voucher payment and prospective estimates of his health care
claims are likely.  The transition will be complex and unwieldy in moving from
a community-rated, defined benefit structure for everyone age 65 and over to a
system based on defined contribution payments that are selected voluntarily in
an individual-based health insurance market.<p>
	Consider the shortcomings of existing risk adjustment methodology, the
rigidities of bureaucratic pricing, and strong incentives for healthier
beneficiaries to game the system and race to the front of the line exiting the
traditional Medicare program.  Opportunistic behavior could result in
overcompensation of lower-cost beneficiaries, strained resources for
higher-risk beneficiaries, and dilution of overall budget savings.  The House
and Senate plans stopped short of proposing more aggressive remedies to this
problem and punted the issue of risk adjustment to a study commission.  <p>
	The future scenario for Medicare&#146;s post-reform environment could well
come down to a race among several offsetting trends.  Congressional Republican
leaders are hoping that large numbers of beneficiaries exit the traditional
Medicare program and find more efficient, lower-cost private health plan
alternatives.  At the same time, this exodus must be balanced across risk
categories so that traditional Medicare&#146;s expenses don&#146;t begin to
outrun its remaining revenue base.  If a disproportionate share of high-cost
beneficiaries are reluctant to leave &#147;old&#148; Medicare, the budget
squeeze on the traditional program will grow too tight and require tough
look-back sequesters that could set off a destructive chain reaction.  Deeper
budget cuts would drive more providers out of the fee-for-service structure and
impair its remaining standard of health care.  Current overpromises to
beneficiaries that they can stay in traditional Medicare at no risk to their
health care expectations could come back to haunt congressional Republicans.
If most beneficiaries don&#146;t leave medicare fee-for-service fairly quickly,
a hybrid health care system for the elderly will be tied up in contradictions.
The necessary political groundwork has not been built for voluntarily
unraveling a highly subsidized entitlement that is based on unrealistic popular
assumptions.   <p>
	The two reform plans are betting the political ranch on private sector
efficiencies in restructuring health care services for the elderly.  This also
means that political frustrations will soon be concentrated on the significant
deficiencies that remain in the current version of private health insurance.
Expect greater political tension ahead over consumers&#146; growing
frustrations with the hidden rationing of managed care plans, particularly by
older Americans accustomed to paying only a fraction of the market price of
less-restricted, fee-for-service medicine.  <p>
	The wild card for Republican reformers remains widespread utilization of the
medical savings account (MSA) option.  Although MSA alternatives could be
designed better in both plans, their advocates contend that MSAs will drive
senior citizens&#146; health care utilization and aggregate costs substantially
downward.  Thus far, that remains a hope rather than a probability.  <p>
	More aggressive measures were left out of the congressional reform mix.  They
include:<p>
 <UL>

<LI>Substantially higher, income-based deductibles; <p>

<LI>Pure voucher payments made directly to beneficiaries, with minimal
restrictions on benefit configurations; <p>

<LI>Lower capitated voucher amounts, combined with supplemental financial
assistance to the high-risk poor; <p>
<LI>Integrating Medicare Part A and Part B into a single program; and<p>
<LI>Eliminating Part B premiums in exchange for higher deductibles.<p>

</UL>
The current round of proposed reforms buy a little fiscal time before the
demographic explosion a little more than a decade away.  They represent a mere
down payment on Medicare&#146;s long-term unfunded liabilities.  The plans will
strip away the first layer of accumulated stupidity in a
bureaucratically-guided entitlement program.  They need to dig much deeper in
order to move beyond one-time savings.  But that&#146;s policy, and the
immediate fight ahead is much more about politics.  For now, let&#146;s call
the effort &#147;close enough for government work.&#148;  A political coup?
Apparently.  A policy revolution?  As if. <p>


<BR>
<HR NOSHADE>
<BR>
