2.7.5 --></head><body><b>DEATH BY REGULATION</b><p>
<p>
CEI&#146;s <i>Death by Regulation</i> project is aimed at changing the policy
debate, not only through conventional policy analysis, but also by exploring
new means of bringing this message to a wider audience.  One approach is to
focus on previously unrecognized victims of regulatory failure, showing, for
example, that government regulation can in some cases be literally lethal.<p>
<p>
This focus is based, in part, on our recognition that past deregulatory efforts
have either been outright failures or, at best, only limited successes.
Traditional cost-benefit debates are often rigged contests, with market
advocates easily cast as the &#147;greedy&#148; defenders of
&#147;profits&#148; while regulators are the &#147;good guys&#148; who protect
us.  CEI&#146;s <i>Death by Regulation</i> work attempts an end-run around this
dilemma -- if the public can be persuaded that government intervention carries
its own deadly consequences, then the entire nature of this debate changes.<p>
<p>
The potential of the <i>Death by Regulation </i>project is best illustrated by
CEI&#146;s work on the CAFE issue.  The CAFE (Corporate Average Fuel Economy)
program imposes the minimum fuel efficiency standards for each automaker&#146;s
sales of new cars in this country.  The CAFE program was established by
Congress in 1975 in response to the oil shocks of that period.    <p>
<p>
As oil prices subsequently began to fall in the mid-1980s, however, the public
started to seek larger, safer vehicles once again -- a shift in consumer demand
that ran headlong into CAFE&#146;s constraints.  America&#146;s competitive
advantage in the large-car production was undermined, destroying domestic jobs
and raising consumer prices.  <p>
<p>
CEI entered the CAFE debate in 1986, recognizing that economic arguments alone
were failing to win the policy debate.  CEI raised the CAFE-safety issue,
arguing that CAFE literally kills people by restricting the production of
larger, more crashworthy cars.  Recognizing the lack of formal academic
research on this, CEI persuaded Brookings economist Robert Crandall to
investigate the issue.  The result was a study, co-authored with Harvard Public
Health Professor John D. Graham, that appeared in the 1989 <i>Journal of Law
and Economics</i>.  Its conclusion:  CAFE causes 2,000 to 4,000 car occupant
deaths each year.  <p>
	<p>
CEI also engaged in coalition building, spurring other groups not only to look
at this issue, but to produce their own policy papers on CAFE.  And CEI also
filed a new type of court challenge to CAFE, challenging not its economic
rationality but its lethal effect.  Our first case, in 1986, pitted CEI against
environmental groups who were seeking to make CAFE <u>more</u> stringent.  We
did not win that case on the merits, but we did establish that CEI had judicial
standing to raise the issue.<p>
<p>
The breakthrough came in 1992, in our second court case.  In the first judicial
overturning of a CAFE standard in the program&#146;s history, a federal appeals
court harshly rejected the government&#146;s claim that CAFE kills no one.  It
found that the agency had reached this conclusion through a combination of
&#147;fudged analysis,&#148; &#147;statistical legerdemain,&#148; and
&#147;bureaucratic mumbo-jumbo.&#148;<p>
<p>
The agency at issue was NHTSA (the National Highway Traffic Safety
Administration) whose main job is to promote traffic safety.  An agency whose
middle name is safety had been found to be concealing the fact that one of its
major programs kills people.  A key piece of evidence was the Harvard-Brookings
study that CEI had previously instigated.<p>
<p>
Most importantly, perhaps, the phenomenon of <i>Death by Regulation</i> was no
longer an academic hypothesis; it had been judicially confirmed.  <p>
<p>
The next chapter in the CAFE story is still being written.  CEI is back in
court, challenging NHTSA&#146;s refusal to follow the 1992 court decision.  A
ruling on our new case is imminent.<p>
<p>
<p>
<b>ENVIRONMENTAL STUDIES PROGRAM</b><p>
<p>
Instead of relying on the political process to give sustained, long term
attention to environmental protection, CEI has developed and promoted an
alternative strategy called free market environmentalism.  CEI contends that
where individual property rights exist in environmental resources, the
environment is most likely to be protected.  After all, most of the
world&#146;s environmental problems exist in those areas where common ownership
of government management is the norm.  A free market environmental program
would allow individuals to advance environmental goals as effectively as free
markets permit individuals to advance economic goals.  The policies that flow
from this approach -- privatization, targeted liability rules, sound scientific
inquiry, reduced reliance on political regulation -- are very different from
those now being sought by environmental activists.  They are, however, far more
likely to prove effective.  <p>
<p>
CEI&#146;s Environmental Studies Program includes both an overall effort to
reframe the environmental debate and a series of targeted projects to reform
specific policies.  Only a comprehensive vision of market-oriented
environmental policies will engender the support needed to reform current
policies.  That framework must then be developed in detail for specific
environmental initiatives.<p>
<p>
As the leading proponent of free market environmentalism, the Competitive
Enterprise Institute continues to challenge the conventional wisdom of the
environmental movement and aggressively promotes free market environmentalism
as a more effective strategy for attaining our nation&#146;s environmental
goals.  CEI has fostered and coordinated the development of a network of public
policy organizations around the country and across the globe.  CEI has
positioned itself to take a stronger role in both domestic and international
debates over environmental policies in the 1990s.<p>
<p>
Specifically, CEI works on the vast array of particular environmental issues
including global warming, endangered species, private property rights,
hazardous waste, natural resources, clean air and water, agricultural policy,
oceans and fisheries, biotechnology, energy, trade and the environment,
recycling, pesticides, risk assessment, Superfund, and wetlands.<p>
<p>
<p>
<b>ECONOMIC STUDIES PROGRAM</b><p>
<p>
CEI&#146;s Economic Studies Program deals with many issues concerning the
over-regulation of financial instruments and insurance.  Particular emphasis is
placed on financial instruments used to minimize monetary risks, insurance
reform (which covers such issues as pension funds, social security, Medicare
and Medicaid) and deposit insurance reform.<p>
<p>
<i>Deriviatives, Financial Innovation, and Minimizing Risks in the Banking
System</i><p>
<p>
A story all too familiar to financial practitioners and entrepreneurs is what
Robert Merton calls &#147;the financial innovation spiral.&#148;  Regulatory
bureaucracies, hungry to increase their domains and budgets, keep a watchful
eye on financial innovation and capital markets activities.  When such
activities become &#147;too big&#148; and start growing &#147;too
rapidly,&#148; the busy beavers of Washington begin to build dams.  New
regulations are born.  New jobs for regulators are created.  Bureaucracies are
built up that plug the flows of commerce and capital.<p>
<p>
Entrepreneurship, however, is not typically foiled by regulation.  Indeed, the
<i>response</i> to the regulation of innovation usually is more
innovation&#151;the financial innovation spiral.   When financial
intermediaries are forced to innovate around regulation, further costs are
incurred.  Sometimes it is more efficient to comply with the regulations.  In
either case, unnecessary regulations on financial innovation place a burden on
the processes of capital formation, risk management, and financial
intermediation.<p>
<p>
	Corporations, moreover, face &#147;regulatory risk&#148;&#151;perhaps the one
risk in capital markets which cannot be hedged.  For those firms which must
comply with regulation instead of innovate around it, the risk is that
regulators do not have the requisite expertise to regulate.  As a result, firms
engaged in legitimate albeit complex financial strategies often are penalized
rather than rewarded in the regulatory process.  This problem is compounded by
a typically huge deficit of public education and information on the benefits of
financial innovation.<p>
<p>
	The Competitive Enterprise Institute (CEI) is dedicated to the advancement of
the principles of limited government and free markets.  The advancement of
those principles is perhaps nowhere more necessary than in the arena of
financial intermediation and innovation.  As the world&#146;s commodity and
asset markets have become more volatile, the use of financial contracts in
managing financial risks has become an integral part of every corporate
treasurer&#146;s job.  Because of financial innovations such as
&#147;derivatives&#148; contracts, risks can be managed at a low cost, capital
can be raised efficiently, credit risk can be diversified, and capital can flow
to its most highly valued uses.<p>
<p>
	A derivatives transaction is a bilateral contract which derives its value from
the value of an underlying asset, reference rate, or index.  Popular types
include futures, forwards, swaps, and options.  Over the last two years, more
than ten studies by regulators, congressional committees, and industry have
been completed, virtually all of which explain the numerous benefits of
derivatives.  Despite these benefits, several highly-publicized corporate and
municipal losses&#151;many of which were not <i>caused</i> by
derivatives&#151;have encouraged some members of Congress to ignore the
benefits of derivatives extolled in those studies and instead to focus on the
&#147;risks&#148; of derivatives.<p>
<p>
	The 1994 return of the U.S. Congress to Republican control, moreover, does not
offer much new hope on derivatives policy.  Several key Republican members of
Congress, including new House Banking Committee Chairman Leach, are indeed at
the forefront of the &#147;let&#146;s regulate derivatives&#148; wave.  The
regulatory agencies, in addition, have undertaken several drastic steps
designed to step up their regulation of derivatives.  The CFTC has been
particularly aggressive under the leadership of Mary Shapiro in both calling
into question the regulatory status of privately-negotiated derivatives and in
tightening the CFTC&#146;s grip on the regulated futures exchanges.  The
Federal Reserve Bank of New York also reached a recent agreement with Bankers
Trust which might be viewed as policy-making in disguise, as are the
enforcement actions of the CFTC and SEC against Bankers Trust regarding Gibson
Greetings.  The implications of those actions on the application of the
anti-fraud portions of the Commodity Exchange Act and for the legality of
products like equity swaps is not yet clear.<p>
<p>
	At first glance, the prospects for competition free from regulation in the
derivatives arena seem rather grim.  But then, that shouldn&#146;t surprise
us.<p>
<p>
	In his <i>Wealth of Nations</i>, Adam Smith reviewed 18th-century public
attitudes toward &#147;forestalling&#148; and &#147;engrossing.&#148;
Forestalling was an activity in which corn was purchased during times of plenty
in hopes it could be resold when prices rose.  Engrossing was a similar
activity in which corn was purchased in one city and transported to another,
hopefully to be sold at a profit greater than the transportation cost.<p>
<p>
	The anti-trade Corn Laws were intended in part to restrict forestalling and
engrossing.  Smith nonetheless noted the numerous economic benefits of those
activities and went so far as to call forestalling and engrossing a &#147;most
important operation of commerce.&#148;  He defended the activities and
noted&#151;more prophetically than he may have realized&#151;that &#147;[t]he
popular fear of engrossing and forestalling may be compared to the popular
terrors and suspicions of witchcraft.  The unfortunate wretches accused of this
latter crime were not more innocent of the misfortunes imputed to them, than
those who have been accused of the former.&#148;  <p>
<p>
Witch hunts closer to home have been frighteningly similar to that one in the
18th century.  Consider, for example, what happened when politicians sought in
the 1930s to blame financial activities and &#147;speculative excesses&#148;
for the Great Depression.  Legislation was enacted, for example, to eliminate
financial contracts called &#147;privileges.&#148;  Similar financial contracts
finally were allowed again in 1981, and this time they were called
&#147;options.&#148;  Options traded on organized financial exchanges now meet
rarely with the derision they once did.  The contemporary attacks focus instead
on the same contracts negotiated off the floor of organized exchanges, such as
interest rate options known as caps, collars, and floors, despite the
fundamental similarity of exchange-traded and off-exchange options contracts.<p>
<p>
Depression-era assaults on innovation also gave us the Glass-Steagall act as a
straightjacket for banks to wear.  And thus was born federal deposit insurance,
as well&#151;required to protect the banking system from the &#147;systemic
instability&#148; created by restrictions on bank portfolios and interstate
branching.  Capital formation was first regulated under the Securities Act and
the Securities and Exchange Act during this period.  <p>
<p>
The ratcheting-up of financial regulation, moreover, did not end with the
Depression.  The last fifty years have seen just as much, if not more, of the
financial innovation spiral.  Consider just a few more recent examples:<p>
<p>
 	the Eurodollar market owes much of its origin in the 1950s and 1960s to
Regulation Q, which placed a ceiling on interest rates;<p>
 	the Eurobond market was spawned by the 30% withholding tax on interest
payments on bonds sold in the U.S. to foreign investors;<p>
 	the explosion of issues in deep discount corporate bonds in the early 1980s
was due largely by an error made by the U.S. Treasury in interpreting the tax
treatment of discount securities&#151;the error actually allowed firms to make
money by issuing zero-coupon bonds and <i>giving</i> them away because of the
manner in which the Treasury allowed interest to be deducted; and<p>
 	the &#147;swap&#148; market is said to have developed in response to capital
controls in Europe in the early 1970s. <sup>1</sup><p>
<p>
History thus affirms how the financial innovation spiral plays out.  As
regulations have become more and more onerous, corporations and other
entrepreneurs have had little choice but to live with that regulation through
costly compliance or regulatory avoidance.  At the same time, capital market
participants have stepped up their efforts to innovate.  Financial innovation
allows capital market participants to exploit profit opportunities and manage
their business risks, but it also allows private parties to remain one step
ahead of the political dragon.<p>
<p>
The irony of the financial innovation spiral is that the more rapidly firms
innovate, the more rapidly the legislation and political dinosaurs which
regulate innovation become antiquated and increasingly incapable of addressing
innovation.  One need not look very far for evidence of this.  Consider, for
example, the problems of the Commodity Exchange Act (CEA) which was never
designed to address complex products such as structured (i.e., hybrid)
securities and swaps.  For that matter, consider the decades of case law
generated as courts try to interpret what Congress intended when it regulated
&#147;futures&#148; and &#147;forwards&#148; differently.  Or consider that
when bank examiners must assess capital adequacy of a swap dealer, they must
miraculously become students of such arcane sciences as stochastic calculus to
really judge the quality of a bank&#146;s risk management systems.<p>
<p>
In reality, regulators are slow to respond dynamically to innovation.  It
simply is far easier to change the regulations themselves.  These changes are
on rare occasions positive, such as the Commodity Futures Trading
Commission&#146;s exemption of swaps from the Commodity Exchange Act.  Usually,
however, new regulations compound existing problems by classifying financial
innovations in black and white terms.  Rather than expecting bank examiners
actually to learn the mathematical and financial modeling techniques required
to assess the internal risk management models employed by participants in
derivatives activity, new regulations are promulgated which force innovative
approaches into a box.  Examples are the early drafts of capital requirements
for interest rate risk proposed by the Federal Deposit Insurance Corporation,
Office of the Comptroller of the Currency, and the Federal Reserve Board and
capital requirements for market risk proposed by the Bank for International
Settlements.  Both proposals mandated a &#147;model&#148; which all banks must
use to measure their interest rate risk.  Although the recent provision in the
proposed Bank for International Settlements capital requirements for market
risk represent an encouraging move toward greater reliance on internal models,
the underlying problem is still the inflexibility of bureaucracy and its
inability to expeditiously address the unpredictable dynamic of financial
innovations and market volatility.<p>
<p>
The ostensible justification usually advanced for financial regulations since
World War II is the &#147;market failure&#148; paradigm.  According to this
theory, markets often fail to perform their functions.  When a flaw&#151;real
or perceived&#151;in the market is found, government intervention is required
to &#147;fix&#148; the market&#146;s failure.  <p>
<p>
The work of no less than four Nobel prize winners in economics from The
University of Chicago&#151;George Stigler, Ronald Coase, Merton Miller, and
Gary Becker&#151;explodes the market failure paradigm.  The Nobelists point out
that market failure theory conveniently assumes government regulation to be
perfect and costless; &#147;government failure&#148; is assumed not to occur.
Yet, evidence does not support these assumptions.  Government can fail, too.
The &#147;Chicago approach&#148; demonstrates that sound economic policy can be
crafted only after comparing which failure is the most significant, the
market&#146;s or the government&#146;s.  <p>
<p>
Unfortunately, because the market failure paradigm ignores the possibility of
&#147;government failure,&#148; the problems which arise from regulatory and
political failures are insufficient by themselves to result in a roll-back of
the misguided regulations.  Instead, market failure proponents will point at
the new problems created by regulatory risk as further evidence of market
failure, and new legislation will again follow.<p>
<p>
Once this vicious circle starts, it is difficult to break.  New regulations
create new jobs for regulators, new justifications for fatter bureaucratic
budgets, and new excuses for crusading legislators on re-election trails to
valiantly proclaim their role as the taxpayers&#146; guardians.  All the while,
the derivatives industry in the U.S. will continue its migration to other,
less-regulated shores, thus decreasing competition and raising the costs of
risk management.<p>
<p>
If left unchecked, ever-constrictive regulations chasing on the heels of
financial innovation will progress.  As Adam Smith taught us, however, public
policy advocacy is an effective way to forestall such regulatory encroachments
on the investment and free movements of capital.  His voice stood out against
the doomsayers of 18th-century England, and, indeed, the Corn Laws were
repealed eventually.<p>
<p>
In more modern times, the effectiveness of public policy is evident&#151;at
least temporarily&#151;in recent successes in forestalling the ratcheting-up of
regulations on derivatives.  The earlier capital adequacy proposals on interest
rate risk and market risk were subsequently changed to allow some institutions
the discretion to use their own models.  Examiner oversight will be
complemented by supplemental examiner training.  This temporary success, like
the swap exemption from the CEA, is a result of advocacy, primarily by the
International Swaps and Derivatives Association, Inc. (ISDA).  <p>
<p>
Advocacy is most effective, however, if done by independent organizations whose
only agenda is the promotion of principles.  While ISDA&#146;s advocacy has
been very successful and based on sound economic principles, its efforts to
prevent the ratcheting-up of the regulation of privately-negotiated derivatives
can only be <i>complemented</i> by the efforts of independent, non-profit
advocacy groups like CEI.  The Competitive Enterprise Institute is in fact
uniquely positioned to complement the work of industry in forestalling the
regulation of financial innovation as just such a dispassionate enterprise.  <p>
<p>
<i>Banking and FDIC Reform</i><p>
<p>
The analytical basis for deposit insurance reform is well-developed, with an
extensive array of literature and noted academic experts.  The case for various
forms of comprehensive reform has been made on many occasions and in many
forums, but &#147;bright ideas&#148; alone have not been enough to overcome
substantial problems concerning operational details, political coalition
building, transitional difficulties, and translation of technical jargon into a
message that resonates with the average American.  The critical task today
remains one of effectively marketing many good ideas in the policy arena in a
manner that builds a dominant consensus in favor of fundamental reform.  This
is the task that CEI does best.  <p>
<p>
To advance this reform agenda, CEI launched in 1988 its Financial Services and
Deposit Insurance Reform project -- in anticipation of the federal
government&#146;s initial bailout of the savings and loan industry.  Our aim
was to promote a regulatory framework that would both encourage vigorous
competition in the U.S. financial services industry and ensure that American
taxpayers did not face an even greater insurance fund bailout in the
1990&#146;s.  <p>
<p>
By privatizing deposit insurance, consumers would benefit from a host of
savings including higher interest rates on deposits.  Also, another S &amp; L
fiasco funded by millions of taxpayers dollars would be a thing of the past.<p>
<p>
<i>Private Insurance Reform</i><p>
<p>
Modern society has become increasingly safety conscious and risk-averse.  We
face growing pressures to reduce risks throughout society and to ensure that
those harmed by misadventure receive compensation.  But life is fraught with
uncertainties.  Over time, our societies have developed institutions to help us
mitigate the risk of uncertainty.<p>
<p>
Financial intermediaries, including banks, financial markets, insurance
companies, and others, facilitate the management of our monetary risks.  For
instance, when we buy insurance, we buy peace of mind.  With insurance, we
exchange the chance of a large, unexpected payment, whose timing we cannot
control, for a series of smaller, known payments over the life of the contract.
Moreover, when we shop for insurance, we receive an analysis of our risks.
Insurance companies determine the probability that our house will burn, that
our car will be stolen, or that we will become ill.  Insurers share this
information with consumers through differences in premiums.  We can learn what
actions we can take to reduce our risk by learning what behaviors earn a
discount, or lead to lower premiums.<p>
<p>
One important uncertainty for which we cannot plan and which we cannot manage,
is government policy.  Government action, now and in the future, is more likely
to create risks than to ameliorate them.  Government-imposed rules and
regulations are more likely to inhibit quality than to promote it.  But the
expansion of government regulations and government insurance programs, on both
the state and federal levels, has been significant in recent years.  Government
regulation of prices, capital requirements, rating criteria, and coverage
capacity makes it harder for insurers to offer appropriate risk management at
appropriate prices.  Moreover, these interventions distort markets and force
some to subsidize the politically favored. <p>
<p>
Perhaps the most significant examples are areas in which government actually
provides insurance to protect against certain risks.  These now include poor
health (Medicare, Medicaid), insufficient retirement income (Social Security),
natural disasters (flood insurance), depository institution insolvency (deposit
insurance), underfunding of private pensions (Pension Benefit Guaranty
Corporation), inadequate credit standing for home purchases (FHA-guaranteed
loans), and agricultural business risk (crop insurance).  Government also
provides insurance indirectly through its regulation of safety in private
activities (e.g. EPA, FDA, NHTSA, CPSC, OSHA) and its supervision of the
overall economy.<p>
<p>
Equally significant are attempts by the courts to reduce social risks.  They
are quite pervasive and often counterproductive.  This reduction by American
courts of the right of free contract has limited innovation in the area of risk
management.  If firms cannot assign risks via enforceable contracts, they will
find it difficult to develop the specialized knowledge needed to assess risk
adequately.  Unless a risk reduction firm can shield its customers from their
mistakes, it has little to sell.  The parallel move to transform tort law from
a system of corrective justice &#151; an effort to identify and require
restitution from alleged wrongdoers &#151; to a system of wealth redistribution
has created major difficulties for insurers while doing little to help most
&#147;victims.&#148;<p>
<p>
As a society becomes wealthier, insurance becomes increasingly important as a
means of protecting existing wealth and freeing the resources of businesses and
individuals to be used in furthering economic growth.  As a nation&#146;s
wealth grows, insurance may also come to be viewed by some observers as a
&#147;necessity&#148; akin to sufficient food and adequate housing.  Such
attitudes are becoming more widespread, and insurance issues are becoming
increasingly more prominent at the federal and state levels. 	<p>
<p>
CEI&#146;s Private Insurance Project promotes free market economic solutions to
the problems confronting the industry today.  To meet this end, CEI
concentrates on educating the media, Congress, and the public about the manner
in which the insurance market works and the dangerous effects of misguided
government intervention.  In coming years, CEI will address the important,
emerging issues as they move to the top of the insurance policy agenda.<p>
 <p>
<sup>1</sup>      These examples and many more are discussed in Merton H.
Miller, <i>Financial Innovation and Market Volatility</i> (London:  Blackwell,
1991).
</body></html>␀␀␀␀␀␀␀␀␀␀␀␀␀␀␀␀␀␀␀␀␀␀␀␀␀␀␀␀␀␀␀␀␀␀␀␀␀␀␀␀␀␀␀␀␀␀␀␀␀␀␀␀␀␀␀␀␀␀␀␀␀␀␀␀␀␀␀␀␀␀␀␀␀␀␀␀␀␀␀␀␀␀␀␀␀␀␀␀␀␀␀␀␀␀␀␀␀␀␀␀␀␀␀␀␀␀␀␀␀␀␀␀␀␀␀␀␀␀␀␀␀␀␀␀␀␀␀␀␀␀␀␀␀␀␀␀␀␀␀␀␀␀␀␀␀␀␀␀␀␀␀␀␀␀␀␀␀␀␀␀␀␀␀␀␀␀␀␀␀␀␀␀␀␀␀␀␀␀␀␀␀␀␀␀␀␀␀␀␀␀␀␀␀␀␀␀␀␀␀␀␀␀␀␀␀␀␀␀␀␀␀␀␀␀␀␀␀␀␀␀␀␀␀␀␀␀␀␀␀␀␀␀␀publist1.html␀␀␀␀␀␀␀␀␀␀␀␀␀␀␀␀␀␀␀␀␀␀␀␀␀␀␀␀␀␀␀␀␀␀␀␀␀␀␀␀␀␀␀␀␀␀␀␀␀␀␀␀␀␀␀␀␀␀␀␀␀␀␀␀␀␀␀␀␀␀␀␀␀␀␀␀␀␀␀␀␀␀␀␀␀␀␀100644 ␀  1647 ␀   144 ␀      56721  6211103724  11723␀ 0␀␀␀␀␀␀␀␀␀␀␀␀␀␀␀␀␀␀␀␀␀␀␀␀␀␀␀␀␀␀␀␀␀␀␀␀␀␀␀␀␀␀␀␀␀␀␀␀␀␀␀␀␀␀␀␀␀␀␀␀␀␀␀␀␀␀␀␀␀␀␀␀␀␀␀␀␀␀␀␀␀␀␀␀␀␀␀␀␀␀␀␀␀␀␀␀␀␀␀␀ustar  ␀cei␀␀␀␀␀␀␀␀␀␀␀␀␀␀␀␀␀␀␀␀␀␀␀␀␀␀␀␀␀users␀␀␀␀␀␀␀␀␀␀␀␀␀␀␀␀␀␀␀␀␀␀␀␀␀␀␀␀␀␀␀␀␀␀␀␀␀␀␀␀␀␀␀␀␀␀␀␀␀␀␀␀␀␀␀␀␀␀␀␀␀␀␀␀␀␀␀␀␀␀␀␀␀␀␀␀␀␀␀␀␀␀␀␀␀␀␀␀␀␀␀␀␀␀␀␀␀␀␀␀␀␀␀␀␀␀␀␀␀␀␀␀␀␀␀␀␀␀␀␀␀␀␀␀␀␀␀␀␀␀␀␀␀␀␀␀␀␀␀␀␀␀␀␀␀␀␀␀␀␀␀␀␀␀␀␀␀␀␀␀␀␀␀␀␀␀␀␀␀␀␀␀␀␀␀␀␀␀␀␀␀␀␀␀␀␀␀␀␀␀␀␀␀␀␀␀␀␀␀␀␀␀␀␀␀␀␀␀␀␀<HTML>
