<HEAD>
<TITLE>CEI: Publications List, Part II</TITLE>
</HEAD>

<BODY BGCOLOR="FFFFFF" TEXT="000099" LINK="006633" VLINK="000000">
<BR>
<BR>

<CENTER>
<H1>CEI Publications List, Part II</H1>
</CENTER>
<BR>
<BR>

<P>The following publications are offered for a nominal charge (prices include U.S. postage, but not foreign). Mail checks to
Competitive Enterprise Institute, 
1001 Connecticut Avenue, NW, Suite 1250, 
Washington, DC  20036, call (202) 331-1010, fax (202) 331-0640, or e-mail
<A HREF="mailto:pubs@cei.org">pubs@cei.org</A><BR>
<p>

<BR>
<HR NOSHADE>
<a name="financial"></a>
<b>Financial Services Reform</b><p>
<b></b><p>

<a name="insure1"></A>
<I>The Business and Regulation of Insurance: A Primer</I><p>
by Catherine England<p>
This primer is intended to remove some of the mystery from insurance markets and insurance company operations.  It describes the role insurance companies play in the economy.  It also provides basic information about the insurance
industry's size and the fundamentals of industry operations.  Finally, the
primer reviews insurance company regulation.<p>
March 1996	$12.00<P>


<HR NOSHADE>
<i>A Primer on Derivatives:  Their Mechanics, Uses, Risks, and Regulation</i><p>
by Christopher L. Culp<p>
This monograph is intended to serve as a non-exhaustive primer on the
mechanics, uses, risks, and regulation of derivatives.  Over the past two
years, derivatives have been subjected to numerous criticisms from the media
and Capitol Hill.  Mr. Culp, a Senior Fellow in Financial Regulation at CEI,
hopes that after reading this primer, people will be able to intelligently
question the validity of  headlines about "derivatives doomsday."<p>
September 1995      $15.00<p>



<HR NOSHADE>
<A HREF="redline.html"><i>The Anti-Redlining Agenda:  An Assault on Risk-based Insurance</i></A><p>
by Catherine England<p>
Urban residents often pay higher premiums for auto and homeowners insurance
than suburban because of higher expected claims costs.  Community groups
maintain this should not be allowed to price some consumers out of the
insurance market.  In her paper, England argues that insurance consumers in all
markets would be better served by polices designed to encourage entry into the
insurance market and increase competition in the insurance industry.<p>
July 1994           $5.00<p>




<HR NOSHADE>
<i>A Citizen's Guide to Banking Reform:  Building a Fiscal Firewall Between
Taxpayers and Failing Banks</i><p>
by Tom Miller<p>
A layman-friendly analysis of the banking system, the 1991 debate over banking
reform, and a future agenda for greater market discipline.  Written for
Citizen's Against Government Waste.<p>
December 1992            $8.00<p>



<HR NOSHADE>
<i>The Political Stalemate Behind the Crisis in Banking</i><p>
by Tom Miller<p>
Examines the root political problem behind the mess, the role of regulation,
and how politicians have failed to responsibly address the issue.  <p>
May 1991       $5.00<i></i><p>





<HR NOSHADE>
<i>The Savings and Loan Crisis:  Which Train Derailed--Deregulation or
Deposit Insurance?</i><p>
by Melanie S. Tammen<p>
An analysis of the history of deposit insurance and the failure of FIRREA.
Reprinted from <i>The Journal of Law &amp; Politics</i>, University of
Virginia.<p>
Winter 1990         $4.00<p>



<HR NOSHADE>
<i>Behind the S&amp;L Debacle:  Addressing the Breakdown of Federal Deposit
Insurance</i><p>
A collection of papers from prominent scholars, industry and political analysts
delivered at a CEI/National Taxpayer's Union conference.  <p>
1989           $15.00<p>



<HR NOSHADE>
<i>The Thrift Industry Crisis</i><p>
by Jorge T. Salaverry<p>
Salaverry poses the question, "Is the Federal Home Loan Bank Board the solution
or the problem?"  A critical review of the Board's "direct investment"
regulations, the Management Consignment Program, and the current deposit
insurance system.<p>
December 1986                 $4.00<p>




<HR NOSHADE>
<a name="risk"></A>
<b>Risk and Regulation Issues</b>


<HR NOSHADE>
<A HREF="104th.html"><i>Regulatory Reform: Is it Still a Pipe Dream? A Look at the 104th
Congress</i></A><p>
by Steven J. Milloy<p>
Regulatory reform took center stage in the 104th Congress.  Focusing on H.R. 1022 and S. 343, this monograph by Mr. Milloy, the Director of Science Policy at the National Environmental Policy Institute, examines the efforts made by the House and Senate to slow the explosive growth of federal regulation.<p>
July 1995      $5.00<p>


<HR NOSHADE>
<P><A HREF="autosum.html"><i>Autonomy and Automobility</i></A><p>
by Loren E. Lomasky<p>
The automobile is increasingly attacked as a public malefactor.  In this paper,
Mr. Lomasky, a professor of philosophy at Bowling Green State University,
explores why, despite numerous attempts by bureaucracy to stem the use of the
automobile, people continue to take to the roads in ever increasing numbers.<p>
June 1995      $5.00<p>



<HR NOSHADE>
<i>A National Survey of Oncologists Regarding the Food and Drug
Administration</i><p>
Prepared by <i>the polling company</i> for the Competitive Enterprise
Institute<p>
Oncologists (cancer specialists) know more than anyone about the life and death
consequences of regulation by the FDA.  This poll shows that a majority of
oncologists view the FDA negatively on several major issues including delays is
drug approvals and restrictions on off-label information.<p>
August 1995		$6.00<p>



<HR NOSHADE>
<i>FDA Drug Lag Reader</i><p>
compiled by CEI staff<p>
When the FDA announces the approval of a new drug or device, and proudly
estimates how many lives it will save per year, the real question is how many
lives were lost because of delayed access to therapy.  This reader is a
collection of various studies and articles illustrating this unappreciated
effect of current regulation, and to demonstrate that FDA's mission has been
overshadowed by the FDA's institutional bias against rapid approval.<p>
April 1995          $10.00<p>




<HR NOSHADE>
<i>How FDA is Causing a Technological Exodus:  A Comparative Analysis of
Medical Device Regulation--United States, Europe, Canada, and Japan</i><p>
by Robert Higgs, Ph.D.<p>
This study, prepared for CEI by Robert Higgs, discusses the lengthy delays in
the Food and Drug Administration's approval process for medical devices.  Dr.
Higgs compared the approval processes of several countries and concludes that
the U. S. system imposes unnecessary costs, impedes the capacity of  device
firms and consumers to act quickly and flexibly, and discourages the rapid
innovation firms require to compete in today's world.<p>
February 1995       $5.00<p>




<HR NOSHADE>

<i>Report of the Task Force on Social Security </i>(Citizens Against Government
Waste)<p>
Edited by Tom Miller of CEI<p>
The long-range financial future for Social Security is troubling.  The number
of Social Security beneficiaries is expected to increase more quickly than the
number of covered workers and the latter's taxable earnings.  How do we
stabilize OASDI?  Would reducing payroll taxes expand the economic base and
lessen the long-term burden of financing future retirement benefits?  These
questions and others are tackled by six experts and scholars.<p>
August 1994                   $8.00<i></i><p>



<HR NOSHADE>
<i>Nickles-Stearns is Not the Market Choice for Health Care Reform</i><p>
<i></i>by Tom Miller<p>
In this paper published by the <a href="http://www.cato.org">Cato Institute</A>, CEI Senior Policy Analyst Tom Miller
provides a critical look at the Consumer Choice Health Security Act.  This
legislation fails to provide a clear health care alternative based on market
principles, opening the door to extensive political interference in private
health care decisions.<p>
June 1994                 $5.00<p>




<HR NOSHADE>
<i>Intrastate Trucking:  Stronghold of the Regulators</i><p>
by Cassandra Chrones Moore<p>
CEI adjunct scholar Cassandra Moore argues that leaving state economic
regulations on trucking in place costs American businesses and consumers $5
billion to $12 billion annually.  That regulatory chokehold saps the economic
vitality of the entire country and undermines its competitiveness in world
markets.  This paper was published by the the Cato Institute.<p>
February 1994                 $5.00<p>




<HR NOSHADE>
<i>The Health Care Reader</i><p>
compiled by CEI staff<p>
To inform concerned citizens about the nature of the current health care
debate, CEI has compiled articles published in <i>CEI UpDate</i> over the past
several years on the health care issue.  The result:  CEI's first <i>Health
Care Reader</i>.  This publication includes articles on price controls, FDA
reform, the Canadian system, as well as CEI Senior Policy Analyst Tom Miller's
searing critiques of current reform proposals.<p>
January 1994             $5.00<p>





<HR NOSHADE>
<i>The Impact of Price Regulation on the Pharmaceutical Industry</i><p>
by Terree Wasley<p>
Many advocates of health care reform talk of implementing price controls to
hold down medical costs.  Through a careful examination of the historical and
economic evidence, Wasley demonstrates that such efforts are bound to fail.<p>
March 1993               $5.00<p>




<HR NOSHADE>
<i>Purer Politics, Greasier Pigs, and Other Wonders of Campaign Reform</i><p>
by Sam Kazman<p>
Restrictions on campaign finance turn out to be the oldest form of dirty
politics.  Published in <i>Regulation Magazine.</i><p>
Fall 1992         $4.00<p>



<HR NOSHADE>
<i>Saying Yes to Drugs</i><p>
by Sam Kazman<p>
The argument for a fundamental overhaul of the Food and Drug Administration's
new-drug approval process.  Published in <i>The Journal of Regulation and
Social Costs.</i><p>
<i></i>June 1992         $4.00<p>





<HR NOSHADE>
<i>CEI v. National Highway Traffic Safety Administration</i><p>
A federal court finds that a safety agency concealed the lethal effects of its
fuel efficiency program through the use of "fudged" data, "statistical
legerdemain", and "bureaucratic mumbo-jumbo."  One of the most enjoyable court
decisions you'll ever read.  (U.S. Court of Appeals for the D.C. Circuit)<p>
February 1992       $3.00<p>




<HR NOSHADE>
<i>Death by Regulation</i><p>
by Sam Kazman<p>
Some regulations are not only costly, but lethal as well.  An analysis of how
asymmetries in the visibility of such effects let politicians get away with it.
Published in <i>Regulation Magazine.</i><p>
Fall 1991      $4.00<p>




<HR NOSHADE>
<i>Flip-Flopping on Small Car Safety</i><p>
by Sam Kazman<p>
Ralph Nader, Joan Claybrook and other consumer "protectionists" are in the
forefront of the push to forcibly downsize American cars in the name of energy
conservation.  Yet not very long ago they argued that small cars are inherently
less safe.  This compilation of contradictory quotes demonstrates both the
deadly side of mandated fuel efficiency standards and the distorting effects of
shifting ideology.<p>
November 1991       $3.00<p>




<HR NOSHADE>
<i>Deadly Overcaution:  FDA's Drug Approval Process</i><p>
by Sam Kazman<p>
If a drug approved today by the FDA will start saving lives tomorrow, how many
people died waiting for the agency to act?  Published in <i>The Journal of
Regulation and Social Costs.</i><p>
September 1990           $3.00<p>




<HR NOSHADE>
<i>Intellectual Property:  A Non-Posnerian Law and Economics Approach</i> <p>
by Tom Palmer, Institute for Humane Studies<p>
Commissioned by CEI, Palmer provides a description and background of the
"Posnerian" approach to intellectual property rights, the description between
property rights and technology, and a summary of the functioning of markets for
non-tangible economic goods in the absence of intellectual property rights.
Printed as a Working Paper for the <a href="http://mason.gmu.edu/~ihs/">Institute for Humane Studies</A><p>
February  1989      $6.00<p>




<HR NOSHADE>
<a name="fred"></A>
<A NAME="speeches"␀␀␀␀␀␀␀␀␀␀␀␀␀␀␀␀␀␀␀␀␀␀␀␀␀␀␀␀␀␀␀␀␀␀␀␀␀␀␀␀␀␀␀␀␀␀␀␀␀␀␀␀␀␀␀␀␀␀␀␀␀␀␀␀␀␀␀␀␀␀␀␀␀␀␀␀␀␀␀␀␀␀␀␀␀␀␀␀␀␀␀␀␀␀␀␀␀␀␀␀␀␀␀␀␀␀␀␀␀␀␀␀␀␀␀␀␀␀␀␀␀␀␀␀␀␀␀␀␀␀␀␀␀␀␀␀␀␀␀␀␀␀␀␀␀␀␀␀␀␀␀␀␀␀␀␀␀␀␀␀␀␀␀␀␀␀␀␀␀␀␀␀␀␀␀␀␀␀␀␀␀␀␀␀␀␀␀␀␀␀␀␀␀␀␀␀␀␀␀␀␀␀␀␀␀␀␀␀␀␀␀␀␀␀␀␀␀␀␀␀␀␀␀␀␀␀␀␀␀␀␀␀␀␀␀␀␀␀␀␀␀␀␀␀␀␀␀␀␀␀␀␀␀␀␀␀␀␀␀␀␀␀␀␀␀␀␀␀␀␀␀␀␀␀␀␀␀␀␀␀␀␀␀␀␀␀␀␀␀␀␀␀␀␀␀␀␀␀␀␀␀␀␀␀␀␀␀␀␀␀␀␀␀␀␀␀␀␀␀␀␀␀␀␀␀␀␀␀␀␀␀␀␀␀publist2.html␀␀␀␀␀␀␀␀␀␀␀␀␀␀␀␀␀␀␀␀␀␀␀␀␀␀␀␀␀␀␀␀␀␀␀␀␀␀␀␀␀␀␀␀␀␀␀␀␀␀␀␀␀␀␀␀␀␀␀␀␀␀␀␀␀␀␀␀␀␀␀␀␀␀␀␀␀␀␀␀␀␀␀␀␀␀␀100644 ␀  1647 ␀   144 ␀      61663  6210720115  11723␀ 0␀␀␀␀␀␀␀␀␀␀␀␀␀␀␀␀␀␀␀␀␀␀␀␀␀␀␀␀␀␀␀␀␀␀␀␀␀␀␀␀␀␀␀␀␀␀␀␀␀␀␀␀␀␀␀␀␀␀␀␀␀␀␀␀␀␀␀␀␀␀␀␀␀␀␀␀␀␀␀␀␀␀␀␀␀␀␀␀␀␀␀␀␀␀␀␀␀␀␀␀ustar  ␀cei␀␀␀␀␀␀␀␀␀␀␀␀␀␀␀␀␀␀␀␀␀␀␀␀␀␀␀␀␀users␀␀␀␀␀␀␀␀␀␀␀␀␀␀␀␀␀␀␀␀␀␀␀␀␀␀␀␀␀␀␀␀␀␀␀␀␀␀␀␀␀␀␀␀␀␀␀␀␀␀␀␀␀␀␀␀␀␀␀␀␀␀␀␀␀␀␀␀␀␀␀␀␀␀␀␀␀␀␀␀␀␀␀␀␀␀␀␀␀␀␀␀␀␀␀␀␀␀␀␀␀␀␀␀␀␀␀␀␀␀␀␀␀␀␀␀␀␀␀␀␀␀␀␀␀␀␀␀␀␀␀␀␀␀␀␀␀␀␀␀␀␀␀␀␀␀␀␀␀␀␀␀␀␀␀␀␀␀␀␀␀␀␀␀␀␀␀␀␀␀␀␀␀␀␀␀␀␀␀␀␀␀␀␀␀␀␀␀␀␀␀␀␀␀␀␀␀␀␀␀␀␀␀␀␀␀␀␀␀␀<HTML>
