<BR>

<CENTER>
<H1>CEI Publications List, Part II</H1>
</CENTER>
<BR>
<BR>

<P>The following publications are offered for a nominal charge (prices include U.S. postage, but not foreign). Mail checks to
Competitive Enterprise Institute, 
1001 Connecticut Avenue, NW, Suite 1250, 
Washington, DC  20036, call (202) 331-1010, fax (202) 331-0640, or e-mail
<A HREF="mailto:pubs@cei.org">pubs@cei.org</A><BR>
<p>

<BR>
<HR NOSHADE>
<a name="financial"></a>
<b>Financial Services Reform</b><p>
<b></b><p>

<a name="insure1"></A>
<I>The Business and Regulation of Insurance: A Primer</I><p>
by Catherine England<p>
This primer is intended to remove some of the mystery from insurance markets and insurance company operations.  It describes the role insurance companies play in the economy.  It also provides basic information about the insurance
industry's size and the fundamentals of industry operations.  Finally, the
primer reviews insurance company regulation.<p>
March 1996	$12.00<P>


<HR NOSHADE>
<i>A Primer on Derivatives:  Their Mechanics, Uses, Risks, and Regulation</i><p>
by Christopher L. Culp<p>
This monograph is intended to serve as a non-exhaustive primer on the
mechanics, uses, risks, and regulation of derivatives.  Over the past two
years, derivatives have been subjected to numerous criticisms from the media
and Capitol Hill.  Mr. Culp, a Senior Fellow in Financial Regulation at CEI,
hopes that after reading this primer, people will be able to intelligently
question the validity of  headlines about "derivatives doomsday."<p>
September 1995      $15.00<p>



<HR NOSHADE>
<A HREF="redline.html"><i>The Anti-Redlining Agenda:  An Assault on Risk-based Insurance</i></A><p>
by Catherine England<p>
Urban residents often pay higher premiums for auto and homeowners insurance
than suburban because of higher expected claims costs.  Community groups
maintain this should not be allowed to price some consumers out of the
insurance market.  In her paper, England argues that insurance consumers in all
markets would be better served by polices designed to encourage entry into the
insurance market and increase competition in the insurance industry.<p>
July 1994           $5.00<p>




<HR NOSHADE>
<i>A Citizen's Guide to Banking Reform:  Building a Fiscal Firewall Between
Taxpayers and Failing Banks</i><p>
by Tom Miller<p>
A layman-friendly analysis of the banking system, the 1991 debate over banking
reform, and a future agenda for greater market discipline.  Written for
Citizen's Against Government Waste.<p>
December 1992            $8.00<p>



<HR NOSHADE>
<i>The Political Stalemate Behind the Crisis in Banking</i><p>
by Tom Miller<p>
Examines the root political problem behind the mess, the role of regulation,
and how politicians have failed to responsibly address the issue.  <p>
May 1991       $5.00<i></i><p>





<HR NOSHADE>
<i>The Savings and Loan Crisis:  Which Train Derailed -- Deregulation or
Deposit Insurance?</i><p>
by Melanie S. Tammen<p>
An analysis of the history of deposit insurance and the failure of FIRREA.
Reprinted from <i>The Journal of Law &amp; Politics</i>, University of
Virginia.<p>
Winter 1990         $4.00<p>



<HR NOSHADE>
<i>Behind the S&amp;L Debacle:  Addressing the Breakdown of Federal Deposit
Insurance</i><p>
A collection of papers from prominent scholars, industry and political analysts
delivered at a CEI/National Taxpayer's Union conference.  <p>
1989           $15.00<p>



<HR NOSHADE>
<i>The Thrift Industry Crisis</i><p>
by Jorge T. Salaverry<p>
Salaverry poses the question, "Is the Federal Home Loan Bank Board the solution
or the problem?"  A critical review of the Board's "direct investment"
regulations, the Management Consignment Program, and the current deposit
insurance system.<p>
December 1986                 $4.00<p>




<HR NOSHADE>
<a name="risk"></A>
<b>Risk and Regulation Issues</b>


<HR NOSHADE>
<A HREF="104th.html"><i>Regulatory Reform: Is it Still a Pipe Dream? A Look at the 104th
Congress</i></A><p>
by Steven J. Milloy<p>
Regulatory reform took center stage in the 104th Congress.  Focusing on H.R. 1022 and S. 343, this monograph by Mr. Milloy, the Director of Science Policy at the National Environmental Policy Institute, examines the efforts made by the House and Senate to slow the explosive growth of federal regulation.<p>
July 1995      $5.00<p>


<HR NOSHADE>
<P><A HREF="autosum.html"><i>Autonomy and Automobility</i></A><p>
by Loren E. Lomasky<p>
The automobile is increasingly attacked as a public malefactor.  In this paper,
Mr. Lomasky, a professor of philosophy at Bowling Green State University,
explores why, despite numerous attempts by bureaucracy to stem the use of the
automobile, people continue to take to the roads in ever increasing numbers.<p>
June 1995      $5.00<p>



<HR NOSHADE>
<i>A National Survey of Oncologists Regarding the Food and Drug
Administration</i><p>
Prepared by <i>the polling company</i> for the Competitive Enterprise
Institute<p>
Oncologists (cancer specialists) know more than anyone about the life and death
consequences of regulation by the FDA.  This poll shows that a majority of
oncologists view the FDA negatively on several major issues including delays is
drug approvals and restrictions on off-label information.<p>
August 1995		$6.00<p>



<HR NOSHADE>
<i>FDA Drug Lag Reader</i><p>
compiled by CEI staff<p>
When the FDA announces the approval of a new drug or device, and proudly
estimates how many lives it will save per year, the real question is how many
lives were lost because of delayed access to therapy.  This reader is a
collection of various studies and articles illustrating this unappreciated
effect of current regulation, and to demonstrate that FDA's mission has been
overshadowed by the FDA's institutional bias against rapid approval.<p>
April 1995          $10.00<p>




<HR NOSHADE>
<i>How FDA is Causing a Technological Exodus:  A Comparative Analysis of
Medical Device Regulation  --  United States, Europe, Canada, and Japan</i><p>
by Robert Higgs, Ph.D.<p>
This study, prepared for CEI by Robert Higgs, discusses the lengthy delays in
the Food and Drug Administration's approval process for medical devices.  Dr.
Higgs compared the approval processes of several countries and concludes that
the U. S. system imposes unnecessary costs, impedes the capacity of  device
firms and consumers to act quickly and flexibly, and discourages the rapid
innovation firms require to compete in today's world.<p>
February 1995       $5.00<p>




<HR NOSHADE>

<i>Report of the Task Force on Social Security </i>(Citizens Against Government
Waste)<p>
Edited by Tom Miller of CEI<p>
The long-range financial future for Social Security is troubling.  The number
of Social Security beneficiaries is expected to increase more quickly than the
number of covered workers and the latter's taxable earnings.  How do we
stabilize OASDI?  Would reducing payroll taxes expand the economic base and
lessen the long-term burden of financing future retirement benefits?  These
questions and others are tackled by six experts and scholars.<p>
August 1994                   $8.00<i></i><p>



<HR NOSHADE>
<i>Nickles-Stearns is Not the Market Choice for Health Care Reform</i><p>
<i></i>by Tom Miller<p>
In this paper published by the <a href="http://www.cato.org">Cato Institute</A>, CEI Senior Policy Analyst Tom Miller
provides a critical look at the Consumer Choice Health Security Act.  This
legislation fails to provide a clear health care alternative based on market
principles, opening the door to extensive political interference in private
health care decisions.<p>
June 1994                 $5.00<p>




<HR NOSHADE>
<i>Intrastate Trucking:  Stronghold of the Regulators</i><p>
by Cassandra Chrones Moore<p>
CEI adjunct scholar Cassandra Moore argues that leaving state economic
regulations on trucking in place costs American businesses and consumers $5
billion to $12 billion annually.  That regulatory chokehold saps the economic
vitality of the entire country and undermines its competitiveness in world
markets.  This paper was published by the the Cato Institute.<p>
February 1994                 $5.00<p>




<HR NOSHADE>
<i>The Health Care Reader</i><p>
compiled by CEI staff<p>
To inform concerned citizens about the nature of the current health care
debate, CEI has compiled articles published in <i>CEI UpDate</i> over the past
several years on the health care issue.  The result:  CEI's first <i>Health
Care Reader</i>.  This publication includes articles on price controls, FDA
reform, the Canadian system, as well as CEI Senior Policy Analyst Tom Miller's
searing critiques of current reform proposals.<p>
January 1994             $5.00<p>





<HR NOSHADE>
<i>The Impact of Price Regulation on the Pharmaceutical Industry</i><p>
by Terree Wasley<p>
Many advocates of health care reform talk of implementing price controls to
hold down medical costs.  Through a careful examination of the historical and
economic evidence, Wasley demonstrates that such efforts are bound to fail.<p>
March 1993               $5.00<p>




<HR NOSHADE>
<i>Purer Politics, Greasier Pigs, and Other Wonders of Campaign Reform</i><p>
by Sam Kazman<p>
Restrictions on campaign finance turn out to be the oldest form of dirty
politics.  Published in <i>Regulation Magazine.</i><p>
Fall 1992         $4.00<p>



<HR NOSHADE>
<i>Saying Yes to Drugs</i><p>
by Sam Kazman<p>
The argument for a fundamental overhaul of the Food and Drug Administration's
new-drug approval process.  Published in <i>The Journal of Regulation and
Social Costs.</i><p>
<i></i>June 1992         $4.00<p>





<HR NOSHADE>
<i>CEI v. National Highway Traffic Safety Administration</i><p>
A federal court finds that a safety agency concealed the lethal effects of its
fuel efficiency program through the use of "fudged" data, "statistical
legerdemain", and "bureaucratic mumbo-jumbo."  One of the most enjoyable court
decisions you'll ever read.  (U.S. Court of Appeals for the D.C. Circuit)<p>
February 1992       $3.00<p>




<HR NOSHADE>
<i>Death by Regulation</i><p>
by Sam Kazman<p>
Some regulations are not only costly, but lethal as well.  An analysis of how
asymmetries in the visibility of such effects let politicians get away with it.
Published in <i>Regulation Magazine.</i><p>
Fall 1991      $4.00<p>




<HR NOSHADE>
<i>Flip-Flopping on Small Car Safety</i><p>
by Sam Kazman<p>
Ralph Nader, Joan Claybrook and other consumer "protectionists" are in the
forefront of the push to forcibly downsize American cars in the name of energy
conservation.  Yet not very long ago they argued that small cars are inherently
less safe.  This compilation of contradictory quotes demonstrates both the
deadly side of mandated fuel efficiency standards and the distorting effects of
shifting ideology.<p>
November 1991       $3.00<p>




<HR NOSHADE>
<i>Deadly Overcaution:  FDA's Drug Approval Process</i><p>
by Sam Kazman<p>
If a drug approved today by the FDA will start saving lives tomorrow, how many
people died waiting for the agency to act?  Published in <i>The Journal of
Regulation and Social Costs.</i><p>
September 1990           $3.00<p>




<HR NOSHADE>
<i>Intellectual Property:  A Non-Posnerian Law and Economics Approach</i> <p>
by Tom Palmer, Institute for Humane Studies<p>
Commissioned by CEI, Palmer provides a description and background of the
"Posnerian" approach to intellectual property rights, the description between
property rights and technology, and a summary of the functioning of markets for
non-tangible economic goods in the absence of intellectual property rights.
Printed as a Working Paper for the <a href="http://mason.gmu.edu/~ihs/">Institute for Humane Studies</A><p>
February  1989      $6.00<p>




<HR NOSHADE>
<a name="fred"></A>
<A NAME="speeches"></A>
<b>Speeches by <A HREF="fred.html">Fred Smith</A></b><p>

<i>Environmental Quality, Economic Growth, and International Trade</i><p>
It has become conventional wisdom that free trade and economic growth
reduce environmental quality.  In this speech delivered at the Cato Institute
Conference, Liberty in the Americas:  Free Trade and Beyond, Fred Smith
demonstrates that the reverse is true.  Bureaucratic controls and trade
restrictions can be as damaging to the ecology as they are to the economy.<p>
May 1992       $4.00<p>




<HR NOSHADE>

<i>The Less is More Mantra:  The Greens' Growing Control of American
Energy Policy</i><p>
Modern-day Malthusians are trying to put Americans on an energy diet.  Fred
Smith, in his speech to the Cato Institute Conference on National Energy
Policy, points out the errors in their thinking and proposes a free market
solution to encouraging energy efficiency.<p>
January 1992        $4.00<p>




<HR NOSHADE>
<i>Europe, Energy and the Environment:  The Case Against Carbon Taxes</i><p>
Delivered at the Aspen Institute conference in Berlin, Smith laments Europe's
reliance on failed central planning to determine the "desired" amount of energy
use.  Precisely because our environment is so important, we should not relegate
it to the political arena.<p>
January 1992        $4.00<p>




<HR NOSHADE>
<i>Images of the Scientist in Literature:  Prometheus Bound and
Frankenstein</i><p>
What will happen to a society that turns back progress?  Fred Smith examines
the models of scientist as innovator and scientist as destructor in
literature.<p>
October 1991        $4.00<p>




<HR NOSHADE>
<i>Making Sense of Sustainable Development:  A Free Market Approach to
Environmental Issues</i><p>
Fred Smith, in a provocative speech delivered at the University of Geulph,
Ontario, challenges the assumption that prosperous free economics cannot
simultaneously provide continued economic growth and environmental
protection.<p>
September 1991           $4.00<p>





<HR NOSHADE>
<i>Science and Science Policy:  Can Environmental "Science" Inform
Environmental Politics?</i><p>
Fred Smith examines the recent politicization of science and the implications
for using science as a tool for public policy.  Delivered to the Cato Institute
Conference on Global Environmental Crises.<p>
June 1991      $4.00<p>




<HR NOSHADE>

<i>A Free Market Environmental Program for the Soviet Union</i><p>
Fred Smith urges the Soviets not to follow the lead of the U.S. in
environmental policy, but to base their policies on the principles of property
rights.  Delivered at the Cato Institute Conference, Transition to Freedom:
The New Soviet Challenge in Moscow. <p>
September 1990           $4.00<p>



<HR NOSHADE>
<A NAME="congressional"></A>
<b>Congressional Testimony</b><p>



<b>Robert J. Smith</b><p>
<b></b><i>Testimony before the U. S. Senate Subcommittee on Parks, Historic
Preservation, and Recreation</i><p>
<i></i>CEI's Senior Environmental Scholar, R. J. Smith, testifies about the
"National Heritage Act of 1995."  He argues that this act creates a new federal
program at a time when the American people are calling for fewer.  It also
authorizes more federal government spending and constitutes a threat to private
property rights.<p>
December 12, 1995	$4.00<p>
<b></b><p>

<HR NOSHADE>

<b>Robert H. Nelson</b><p>
<b></b><i>Testimony before the U. S. Senate Subcommittee on Forests and Public
Land Management</i><p>
<i></i>CEI Fellow in Environmental Studies Dr. Robert Nelson testifies that
federal forest management is failing economically and environmentally.   He
proposes classification of federal forests and other public lands into three
categories in order for these lands to be privatized, turned over to state and
local governments, or incorporated into a reorganized federal system.<p>
November 2, 1995	$4.00<p>

<HR NOSHADE>
<b>Jonathan Adler</b><p>
<i>Testimony before the U. S. Senate Committee on the Judiciary</i><p>
Jonathan Adler, Director of Environmental Studies, presents CEI's views
on property rights and compensation for regulatory takings.  He proposes
statutory compensation and discusses the likely impact on environmental
protection.<p>
October 18, 1995		$4.00<p>
<p>


<HR NOSHADE>
<b>Ben Lieberman</b><p>
<i>Testimony before the Committee on Science Subcommittee on Energy and
Environment</i><p>
Environmental Research Associate Ben Lieberman addresses the
Subcommittee on Energy and Environment concerning ozone depletion and the CFC
phaseout, focusing on the consumer impact of the phaseout.<p>
September 20, 1995<p>
<p>


<HR NOSHADE>
<b>Clyde Wayne Crews</b><p>
<i>Comments of the Competitive Enterprise Institute before the Federal
Energy Regulatory Commission</i><p>
Wayne Crews, Fellow in Regulatory Studies, submits CEI's statement on
the proposed rulemaking concerning Recovery of Stranded Costs by Public
Utilities and Transmitting Utilities.  CEI's position is that "FERC
Should Not Assist Stranded Cost Recovery."<p>
August 4, 1995		$4.00<p>


<HR NOSHADE>
<b>Jonathan Adler</b><p>
<i>Testimony before the U. S. Senate Committee on the Environment and
Public Works</i><p>
Director of Environmental Studies Jonathan Adler outlines the extent to
which current environmental infringes upon the rights of landowners, and
discusses the interrelationship between property rights protections and
protecting the environment.<p>
July 12, 1995		$4.00<p>


<HR NOSHADE>
<b>Robert H. Nelson</b><p>
<i>Testimony before the U. S. House of Representatives Resource
Committee Subcommittee on National Parks, Forests and Lands</i><p>
University of Maryland professor, and CEI Senior Fellow in Environmental
Studies Robert Nelson testifies in favor of transferring portions of federal
lands to the states.<p>
June 20, 1995		$4.00<p>


<HR NOSHADE>
<b>Clyde Wayne Crews</b><p>
<i>Testimony before the Committee on Resources Subcommittee on Water and
Power Resources</i><p>
Wayne Crews, CEI Fellow in Regulatory Studies relates CEI's support
for efforts to privatize the Power Marketing Administrations as part of the
public commitment to governmental reform and taxpayer savings.<p>
May 18, 1995		$4.00<p>


<HR NOSHADE>
<b>Ike C. Sugg</b><p>
<i>Testimony before the Endangered Species Act Task Force of the U. S.
House of Representatives Committee on Resources</i><p>
CEI Policy Analyst Ike C. Sugg testifies to the Endangered Species Task
Force on CEI's position that reauthorization of the Endangered Species Act
without reform is not a viable option.  Property rights must be a included when
reforming the Endangered Species Act.<p>
May 18, 1995		$5.00<p>


<HR NOSHADE>
<b>Ben Lieberman</b><p>
<i>Testimony before the U. S. House of Representatives Subcommittee on
Energy and Environment</i><p>
Ben Lieberman, CEI Environmental Research Associate, speaks to the
subcommittee concerning the consumer impact of the CFC phaseout.<p>
September 20, 1995	$4.00<p>


<HR NOSHADE>
<b>Clyde Wayne Crews</b><p>
<i>Comments to the Federal Energy Regulatory Commission</i><p>
Wayne Crews, on behalf of CEI, submitted these comments presenting CEI's
position that FERC should not assist stranded cost recovery.<p>
August 4, 1995		$4.00<p>


<HR NOSHADE>
<b>Jonathan H. Adler</b><p>
<i>Testimony before the U. S. Senate Committee on the Environment and
Public Works</i><p>
Director of Environmental Studies Jonathan Adler testifies concerning
property right, regulatory takings, and environmental protection, and proposals
for statutory compensation.<p>
July 12, 1995		$4.00<p>


<HR NOSHADE>
<b>Robert H. Nelson</b><p>
<i>Testimony before the U. S. House of Representatives Subcommittee on
National Parks, Forests, and Lands</i><p>
Dr. Robert Nelson testifies about the possibility of transferring
portions of federal lands to the states in order to manage those lands more
effectively and more efficiently.<p>
June 20, 1995		$4.00<p>


<HR NOSHADE>
<b>Clyde Wayne Crews</b><p>
<i>Testimony before the U. S. House of Representatives Subcommittee on
Water and Power Resources</i><p>
CEI Fellow in Regulatory Studies Wayne Crews presents CEI's support for
the efforts to privatize the Power Marketing Administrations (PMAs) as a
manifestation of today's wide scale public commitment to fundamental
governmental reform.<p>
May 18, 1995		$4.00<p>


<HR NOSHADE>
<b>Ike Sugg</b><p>
<i>Testimony before the Endangered Species Act Task Force, U. S. House
of Representatives Committee on Resources </i><p>
Ike Sugg, CEI's Fellow in Wildlife and Land-Use Policy, discusses the
property rights perspective of  the Endangered Species Act.<p>
May 18, 1995		$4.00<p>


<HR NOSHADE>
<b>Jonathan Adler</b><p>
<i>Testimony before the Committee on Environment and Public Works
Subcommittee on Superfund, Waste Control, and Risk Assessment</i><p>
Director of Environmental Studies Jonathan Adler presents the
free-market perspectives of  flow control and the interstate transportation of
Solid Waste before the Subcommittee on Superfund, Waste Control, and Risk
Assessment.  <p>
March 1, 1995		$4.00<p>


<HR NOSHADE>
<b>Marlo Lewis, Jr.</b><p>
<i>Testimony before the Joint Economic Committee</i><p>
Marlo Lewis, CEI's Executive Director, presents CEI's
recommendations concerning three proposals which would provide enforcement
mechanisms to achieve a balanced budget by the year 2002 to the Joint Economic
Committee.<p>
February 16, 1995	$4.00<p>


<HR NOSHADE>
<b>Jonathan H. Adler</b><p>
<i>Testimony before the U. S. House of Representatives Committee on the
Judiciary, Subcommittee on the Constitution.</i><p>
Jonathan Adler, Director of Environmental Studies at CEI, addressed the
Subcommittee on the Constitution concerning property rights.  In the past year,
the environmental movement has felt a backlash from property owners who have
lost their land or use of their land because of environmental takings.  Mr.
Adler testified concerning the need for just compensation  to property owners
for these losses.  <p>
February 10, 1995		$4.00<p>


<HR NOSHADE>
<b>Fred L. Smith Jr.  </b><p>
<i>Testimony before the U. S. House of Representatives Appropriations
Committee, Subcommittee on VA, HUD, and Independent Agencies. </i>  <p>
Mr. Smith was asked to testify about the importance of restoring limited
government to America.  He covered many subjects including  the EPA's impact on
the economy, the Radon Action Program,  the Pollution Prevention and Waste
Reduction Program, and the Office of  Environmental Education.<p>
February 2, 1995 		$4.00<p>


<HR NOSHADE>
<b>Sam Kazman</b><p>
<i>Testimony before the U. S. House of Representatives Committee on
Science.</i><p>
Sam Kazman, CEI's Legal Counsel, testified in favor of Title III of H.R.
9, "Risk Assessment and Cost/Benefit Analysis for New Regulations."  CEI has
long had a special interest in raising public awareness of the hidden costs of
overregulation.  Kazman discussed the need for legislation that requires
agencies to ask a few simple questions before enacting a proposed rule:  Do we
really need this?  Will it work?  Is the cost worth it? What could we get
instead with the money we're about to spend on this?<p>
January 30, 1995		$4.00<p>


<HR NOSHADE>
<b>Fred L. Smith Jr. </b><p>
<i>Testimony before the U. S. House of Representatives Appropriation
Committee, Energy and Water Subcommittee.</i><p>
In this testimony, Fred Smith urges Congress to eliminate many of the wasteful
energy and water projects supported by the Federal Government.  Regulatory
programs such as the Civil Works department with in the Army Corps of Engineers
should be dismantled because of the costly and inflammatory nature of its
"mission."<p>
Mr. Smith also discusses privatizing, sorting out, and eliminating the federal
R&amp;D energy research role.<p>
January 18, 1995		$4.00<p>
<p>


<HR NOSHADE>
<b>Catherine England</b><p>
<i>Testimony before the Michigan Insurance Federation: Cost Based
Pricing or Redlining?</i><p>
December 7, 1994	$4.00<p>


<HR NOSHADE>
<b>Tom Miller</b><p>
<i>Testimony before the Social Security Subcommittee of the U. S. House
of Representatives Committee on Ways and Means on alternative investment of
Social Security Trust Fund Reserves.  </i><p>
October 4, 1994		$4.00<p>


<HR NOSHADE>
<b>Jonathan Tolman</b><p>
<i>Statement on the Disinfection By-Products Proposed Rule</i> <p>
In this statement, CEI Policy Analyst Jonathan Tolman conveys CEI's belief
that there are significant and fundamental problems with the Disinfection
By-Products Proposed Rule.<p>
November 1, 1994	$3.00<p>


<HR NOSHADE>
<b>Jonathan Tolman</b><p>
<i>Comments on the Environmental Protection Agency's Disinfectants
and Disinfection By-Products Proposed Rule</i><p>
Reported in the Federal Register<p>
July 29, 1994		$4.00<p>





