<CENTER>
<H1>THE GREENING OF TRADE POLICY<BR>
&#147;Sustainable Development&#148;<BR>
and Global Trade</H1>

<A HREF="sheehan.html">James M. Sheehan</A>
<BR>
<BR>
November 1994
</CENTER>


<BR>
<BR>
<BR>
<UL>
<LI>Executive Summary
<LI><A HREF="trade1.html">Introduction</A>
<LI><A HREF="trade1.html#critique">The Environmental Critique of Trade</A>
<LI><A HREF="trade1.html#free">Free Trade and Environmental Quality</A>
<UL>
<LI><A HREF="trade1.html#markets">Free Markets Are Truly Green</A>
<LI><A HREF="trade1.html#focus">Focus on Global Environment Fosters Ecological Central Planning</A>
</UL>

<LI><A HREF="trade2.html">Trade-Related Environmental Standards</A>
<UL>
<LI><A HREF="trade2.html#green">Green Protectionism</A>
<LI><A HREF="trade2.html#policy">Policy Uniformity Breeds Cartelization</A>
<LI><A HREF="trade2.html#eco">Eco-imperialism</A>
</UL>

<LI><A HREF="trade3.html">International Environmental Laws and Principles</A>
<UL>
<LI><A HREF="trade3.html#earth">The Earth Summit: Defining Sustainable Development</A>
