Because the U.S. business community was reluctant to put trade under the
control of a bureaucracy, GATT exists only by virtue of the 1947 Protocol of
Provisional Application, proclaimed by the president without formal
ratification by the Senate.  The Protocol lacks the binding authority of a
treaty; even its name implies a more tenuous legal standing.  See pp. 28-29.<p>
