<TITLE>CEI EBB: Risk Assessment</TITLE>
</HEAD>

<BODY BGCOLOR="#EEEEEE" TEXT="000000" LINK="009900" VLINK="000099">

<TABLE BORDER=0 WIDTH=100%><TR><TD ALIGN=LEFT><A HREF="/ebb/"><IMG SRC="/images/ceiebb.gif" ALT="CEI Environmental Briefing Book" ALIGN=LEFT BORDER=0></A></TD></TR></TABLE>
<P>
<BR CLEAR>
<table border=0 cellpadding=15><tr><td>

<CENTER>
<H2>Risk Assessment</H2>
</CENTER>

<P><BR>Regulators are supposed to make our lives safer by eliminating or reducing our
exposure to certain risky substances and products, such as toxic chemicals,
dangerous food additives, or cars without airbags.  The problem is that the
current federal regulatory process often focuses on minute risks while ignoring
far greater threats to public health and safety.  This approach not only wastes
public and private resources, it diverts attention away from those things about
which people should be most concerned.<p>
	In the last fifteen years, regulatory policy has too often evolved in reaction
to popular panic over sensational fear stories in the media, not in response to
sound science.  As a result billions of dollars are wasted every year in
battling insignificant problems, leaving no money for others that cause far
more harm.  The government needs to do a better job of quantifying risks and
focusing on those risks that require government action, as opposed to those
that do not.  Even the Environmental Protection Agency&#146;s own scientists
have criticized the federal governments approach to risk.<p>
	Consider the example of a hazardous waste site in New Hampshire that was to be
cleaned up under federal law.  After much expense, the site was clean by any
reasonable standard.  The Environmental Protection Agency, however, was
unsatisfied and demanded that the company spend an additional $9.3 million to
make the soil on the site clean enough for children to eat small amounts of
dirt for 245 days of the year.  This might be justifiable if the site was
destined to become a kindergarten playground.  The site in question, however,
was located in the middle of a swamp.  The dirt-eating children were
nonexistent.  Yet federal regulations required that $9.3 million was to be
spent on clean up, even though it would not reduce any risks to human health
whatsoever.  <p>
	Congress should pass legislation to reform the federal government&#146;s risk
assessment and prioritization.  Those reforms should include:<p>
<UL>
<LI>	An open, transparent process for risk assessments to ensure credibility and
identify critical science issues and uncertainties, the population at risk,
exposure scenarios, and known substitution risks;<p>
<LI>	The requirement of a scientific &#147;best estimate&#148; of risks with which
other estimates, and other risks, can be compared;<p>
<LI>	Required analyses of the potential negative impact of proposed risk
regulations on human health and safety.<p>
</UL>
	<P>There are many risks to human health and safety.  Without more accurate risk
assessment and prioritization, taxpayer dollars will continue to be squandered
on questionable programs that do little, if anything, to promote public health,
safety, and environmental protection.<p>
<p>
<i>Q:  Do government agencies tend to exaggerate risks?</i><p>
<p>
A:  Yes.  Government agencies often exaggerate the risks they are entrusted to
regulate.  That is because government agencies must demonstrate they are needed
to continue to receive taxpayer funds.  This does not mean agencies always
exaggerate the nature of environmental risks; it does mean, however, that
agencies often have a strong incentive to do just that.<p>
<p>
<i>Q:  Shouldn&#146;t the government be protecting us from all unreasonable
risks?</i><p>
<p>
A:  In a world of unlimited abundance and perfect information, the government
might be able to do that.  But society and the government have limited
resources and different people have different risk-reduction priorities.  The
best course of action is to identify the worst public risks so that limited
resources are directed toward those.  More effective management of risks is
better served by the promulgation of more accurate information on risks than it
is by the blanketing of society with proscriptive government regulations.<p>
<p>
<i>Q:  Risk assessment sounds like putting a price on life.  How can you put a
price on life?</i><p>
<p>
A:  Life is priceless.  But when we decide to buy a subcompact instead of a
Volvo, we know that our family will be at somewhat greater risk in a car
accident.  This does not mean we are putting price tags on their heads.  It
simply means that there are better things that we could do with our money.
Forcing bureaucrats to perform risk assessments is not forcing them to put a
price on life.  But it will force them to think more like families, and
recognize the trade-offs that are inherent in everyday life. <p>
<p>
<i>Q:  Are there alternatives to federal risk regulation?</i><p>
<p>
A:  Certainly. Many risks that the federal government focuses on do not require
government attention at all.  This is not because these risks do not exist, but
because different individuals and communities are willing to accept different
trade-offs.  Some people wish to spend more money on reducing environmental
risks; other people prefer to spend their money on family, education or
leisure.  These decisions should be left in the hands of those people who the
decisions will affect. Where government involvement is unavoidable, regulation
should be undertaken based upon the best available information and the
regulated risks should be placed within their proper context.
</td></tr></table>

<P><BR>
<CENTER>
<P>
