<HEAD>
<TITLE>CEI EBB: Safe Drinking Water Act (SDWA)</TITLE>
</HEAD>

<BODY BGCOLOR="#EEEEEE" TEXT="000000" LINK="009900" VLINK="000099">

<TABLE BORDER=0 WIDTH=100%><TR><TD ALIGN=LEFT><A HREF="/ebb/"><IMG SRC="/images/ceiebb.gif" ALT="CEI Environmental Briefing Book" ALIGN=LEFT BORDER=0></A></TD></TR></TABLE>
<P>
<BR CLEAR>
<table border=0 cellpadding=15><tr><td>

<CENTER>
<H2>Safe Drinking Water Act (SDWA)</H2>
</CENTER>

<P><BR>America&#146;s drinking water systems are capable of efficiently delivering 41
billion gallons of safe water to American homes everyday.  Despite this fact,
the Safe Drinking Water Act (SDWA) is in need of reform.  The current law is
too rigid, allows the federal government to impose unneeded and expensive
mandates on local governments, and fails to prioritize risks.<p>
	The SDWA currently requires the federal Environmental Protection Agency (EPA)
to establish drinking water standards for 83 specific contaminants.
Additionally, the SDWA requires the EPA to pick an additional 25 contaminants
every three years to regulate.  This mandate applies irrespective of whether
there are additional, identifiable contaminants that pose a human health risk
in America&#146;s water supply.  According to the EPA, the total cost for
implementing the new standards is $1.4 billion a year, nearly all of which is
paid for by local governments.<p>
	Future regulations are expected to cost even more.  For example, the EPA has
proposed to regulate disinfection by-products.  These are the trace amounts of
chlorinated organic chemicals which are formed when the water is disinfected
with chlorine, the most widely used disinfectant.  Under the disinfection
by-products rule the EPA has estimated the cost of compliance at $2.8 billion a
year.  This single rule would triple the compliance cost of the Safe Drinking
Water Act.  Yet the EPA&#146;s own analysis of the disinfection by-products
rule would increase the risk of microbial contamination.  In other words, the
EPA has proposed a $2.8 billion dollar a year regulation on municipalities
which they estimate would increase the microbial contamination of the
nation&#146;s drinking water.<p>
	This combination of extreme rigidity and high cost results in wasteful
regulation.  For example, the city of Columbus, Ohio, spends thousands of
dollars a year to test its drinking water for 43 pesticides it knows it
won&#146;t find.  Indeed, most of the pesticides for which the state of Ohio
must test have never been found in the waters of Ohio.<p>
	The SDWA is premised on the idea that EPA bureaucrats, from thousands of miles
away, are better able than local public health officials to determine the
public health needs of a local community.  This assumption is questionable, at
best.<p>
	To improve the SDWA, a reform package should include the following:<p>
<UL>
<LI>	Scientifically accurate assessments of the risks posed by drinking water
contaminants, independently and in relation to other health risks;<p>
<LI>	Cost-benefit analyses for <i>all</i> regulatory standards and contaminant
levels;<p>
<LI>	Funding for the compliance of mandatory regulatory standards.  If the federal
government sets stringent new standards which will be expensive to implement,
it should either supply funds for compliance with the standard or make it
voluntary;<p>
<LI>	Sufficient flexibility for local water agencies to set standards based on
local needs.<p>
</UL>
	<P>The SDWA is an embodiment of the federal command-and-control, one-size
fits-nobody approach to environmental protection.  As such, it is in need of
reform.<p>
<p>
<i>Q:  In Milwaukee in 1993, more than one hundred thousand people became sick
after a parasite infected the water supply.  Shouldn&#146;t the Safe Drinking
Water Act be strengthened to keep what happened in Milwaukee from happening
elsewhere?</i><p>
<p>
A:  No, the Safe Drinking Water Act is part of the problem.  By requiring
municipalities to test and monitor for so many chemicals, (most of which do not
even occur in their local water supplies), the Safe Drinking Water Act diverts
attention and resources away from the most important public health problems in
many communities.  Local water agencies have limited budgets.  When the EPA
forces them to test monitor for obscure contaminants it spreads local
agencies&#146; resources even thinner, increasing the likelihood that a mistake
will occur.  The parasite that infected Milwaukee was called Cryptosporidium.
The EPA had been so busy writing regulations for obscure contaminants that it
had not even developed an approved method to even test for the parasite until
hundreds of thousands became ill in Milwaukee.<p>
<p>
<i>Q:  An environmental group recently reported that one out of five Americans
drank water that was inadequately treated for pollutants.  Shouldn&#146;t the
Safe Drinking Water Act be strengthened to ensure that everyone&#146;s water is
adequately treated?</i><p>
<i></i><p>
A:  The current Safe Drinking Water Act is part of the problem.  Regulating
more stringently or writing more regulations will only exacerbate the problem.
Inadequate treatment occurs most frequently when a water agency&#146;s budget
is stretched to the limit.  By forcing municipalities, especially small
municipalities, to test, monitor and treat so many different substances without
providing additional funds creates more problems than it solves.<p>
<p>
<i>Q:  Will the current proposed legislation in the House and Senate make our
nation&#146;s water safer?</i><p>
<i></i><p>
A:  Yes.  The current legislation will enable local and state governments to
more effectively deal with real water quality issues they face rather than
imaginary risks imposed by the EPA.  In addition the legislation would provide
for a state revolving loan fund to provide communities with the financial
support to upgrade their water systems.  This bill is not perfect, however.
Ideally, Congress would return primary standard setting responsibility to local
communities.<p>
<p>
<i>Q:  Should the pending legislation exempt the disinfection by-products (DBP)
rule from the new risk  and cost-benefit requirements?</i><p>
<i></i><p>
A:  No.  It is even more important that the DBP rule be required to comply with
the new risk and cost benefit procedures as it is the most costly regulation
that the EPA has ever contemplated, in addition to the fact that the EPA&#146;s
own studies suggest it would increase the risk of microbial contamination.
</td></tr></table>
<P><BR>
